{"type":"text","timestamp":1782532340911,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f0734baf6001UMoJFDA0CBUSpJ","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","type":"text","text":"`014-routing-benchmark/design-interface` is empty in the current checkout, so the 82/100 Mode A score cannot be independently file-verified from that path. I’ll record it as operator-provided benchmark context and include the empty-directory check as a limitation.","time":{"start":1782532324086,"end":1782532340908},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_045fe83177ea1858016a3f48e415c08191b1749c2e1c083589","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532340940,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_LhwM8H5ckbPXKH6dXR6VpmDW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md","offset":1,"limit":1200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: sk-design\n3: description: \"Distinctive, intentional UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, taste, and build for interfaces; color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, and design tokens; animation, transitions, and micro-interactions; accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, and anti-slop design audit with quality scoring; and live-website CSS to Style Reference DESIGN.md extraction. Use to make a UI look custom and polished rather than templated, design a visual system, choreograph motion, audit and harden design quality, or extract a real design system from a live site. The single advisor-routable design skill: it routes to five modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) via mode-registry.json, and each mode holds its own design logic.\"\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\n5: version: 1.0.0.0\n6: metadata:\n7:   author: OpenCode\n8:   family: sk-code\n9: ---\n10: \n11: <!-- Keywords: sk-design, design-family, mode-registry, workflowmode, backendkind, reference-base, anti-slop, design-tokens, cognitive-laws, interface-design, frontend-design, visual-design, visual-identity, make-it-look-good, looks-templated, redesign-the-ui, hero-section, ui-build, typography, palette, color-palette, font-pairing, ux-quality-checklist, design-variations, foundations, color-system, oklch, color-token-system, dark-mode, typography-scale, spacing-system, responsive-layout, layout, hierarchy, grid, themes, motion-design, animation, animate-this, transitions, micro-interactions, framer-motion, animatepresence, exit-animation, reduced-motion, morphing-icons, motion-performance, design-audit, ui-critique, accessibility-audit, performance-audit, anti-slop-detection, production-hardening, design-quality-score, P0-P1-design-findings, polish, theming, design.md, design-md, css-extraction, website-design-extraction, design-reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system-generator, css-tokens, color-extraction, typography-extraction, hex-extraction, shadow-extraction, spacing-extraction, design-fidelity, anti-hallucination, extract-design-system, generate-design-md, capture-website-css, design-tokens-from-url, distinctive-interface, intentional-design, polished-ui, refined-ui, custom-not-templated, premium-ui, aesthetic, design-taste, visual-direction, craft, make-it-beautiful, less-generic, redesign-distinctive, smooth-animation, hover-effect, scroll-animation, choreography, interaction-feel, animate-the-menu, transition-design, design-audit, accessibility-audit, design-quality-audit, design-review, design-qa, audit-the-design, review-the-ui, wcag-contrast, ui-quality-review -->\n12: \n13: # Design Family Hub (sk-design)\n14: \n15: One skill, five design modes, one shared reference base. `sk-design` is the public, advisor-routable home for every design persona; the shared design reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) is the common vocabulary the modes cite. This hub holds NO per-mode design logic — each mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n20: \n21: Use this skill (through the hub) for any design-family workflow. Invoke it as `sk-design` (optionally with a mode hint such as `motion: <request>`); the hub classifies the request, resolves a mode key, and loads the matching nested packet.\n22: \n23: | Mode | Use it for | Packet |\n24: |------|-----------|--------|\n25: | **interface** | Distinctive, intentional UI direction and build judgment, visual identity, redesign, generic \"make it look good\", interface writing | `sk-design/design-interface/` |\n26: | **foundations** | Static visual-system decisions: color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, responsive adaptation, themes, design tokens | `sk-design/design-foundations/` |\n27: | **motion** | Temporal interaction design: animation, transitions, micro-interactions, motion materials, `AnimatePresence`, reduced motion | `sk-design/design-motion/` |\n28: | **audit** | Design QA and critique: accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, anti-slop detection, scoring, production hardening | `sk-design/design-audit/` |\n29: | **md-generator** | Extract a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference `DESIGN.md` via the embedded extract-write-validate pipeline | `sk-design/design-md-generator/` |\n30: \n31: ### When NOT to Use\n32: - A single quick read/edit with no design judgment — use the relevant skill directly.\n33: - Pure implementation after design direction is settled — hand off to `sk-code`.\n34: - A design transport only (Figma, Open Design) — load the design judgment via this hub first, then use the transport. The transport is never the taste authority.\n35: - The shared reference base itself — it is the vocabulary the modes cite, not a user workflow.\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n40: \n41: Routing is **registry-driven**. `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth; the hub reads it and does not re-derive the mapping. The advisor routes any design query to the single identity `sk-design`; the hub then picks the mode.\n42: \n43: ### The discriminator\n44: - **`workflowMode`** — the public mode key (every mode): `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, `audit`, `md-generator`.\n45: - **`backendKind`** — which backend runs the mode: `reference-base` (the four doc-guidance modes cite the shared design reference base) or `playwright-extract` (`md-generator` runs its embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\n46: \n47: ### Routing rule\n48: ```\n49: classify the request to a workflowMode (dominant design intent; mode hint like \"motion: ...\" overrides)\n50: read mode-registry.json\n51:   → resolve workflowMode from the hint / classified intent\n52:   → load the mode packet at registry[mode].packet (e.g. sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md)\n53:   → the mode cites the shared reference base, or runs its own backend per registry[mode].backendKind\n54: ```\n55: \n56: Intent classification favors the smallest useful mode. Default a generic \"make this look good\" prompt to **interface** unless the prompt is explicitly foundations (tokens/color/type/layout), motion (animation/transition), audit (critique/accessibility/slop), or md-generator (`DESIGN.md`/style-reference extraction). Pair modes only when the prompt has clearly separate design axes (e.g. interface + motion for a landing page with substantial choreography).\n57: \n58: Per-mode behavior is **not flattened**: each packet keeps its own design judgment, examples, standards, verification, and tool-permission needs. The four doc-guidance modes are read-and-guide; `md-generator` is the only mode that runs an extraction pipeline (Write/Edit/Bash over Playwright).\n59: \n60: ---\n61: \n62: ## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n63: \n64: ### Layout\n65: ```\n66: sk-design/\n67:   SKILL.md               # this routing hub (no per-mode design logic)\n68:   mode-registry.json     # the discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)\n69:   graph-metadata.json    # the ONE advisor identity for the whole skill\n70:   references/            # shared design reference base the hub + modes cite\n71:   design-interface/  design-foundations/  design-motion/  design-audit/  design-md-generator/   # five mode packets\n72: ```\n73: \n74: Each mode packet is self-contained (its own `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `assets/`, and `md-generator`'s extraction backend), with internal paths repointed and **no per-packet `graph-metadata.json`** — only this hub carries one, so the advisor discovers exactly one skill. The mode packet folders are created when the flat skills move under the hub; the hub references those packet paths now.\n75: \n76: ### Backend\n77: The four doc-guidance modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit) consume the shared **design reference base** under `references/` — `anti_slop_principles.md`, `cognitive_laws.md`, `design_token_vocabulary.md` — so anti-slop critique, design-token vocabulary, and cognitive-law rationale stay consistent across modes without duplication. The `md-generator` mode consumes its own embedded Playwright extraction backend instead. The reference base provides shared vocabulary; it must never gain per-mode workflow logic.\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ## 4. RULES\n82: \n83: ### ALWAYS\n84: - **ALWAYS** resolve a mode through `mode-registry.json`; never hardcode a router mapping in the hub.\n85: - **ALWAYS** keep each mode's design judgment, examples, and verification in its packet — the hub stays logic-free.\n86: - **ALWAYS** keep exactly one `graph-metadata.json` (this hub's) so the advisor sees one skill identity.\n87: - **ALWAYS** give every mode an `advisorRouting` block with a valid `routingClass` and `packetSkillName`.\n88: - **ALWAYS** route a generic design prompt to the smallest useful mode; default to `interface` when no other axis dominates.\n89: \n90: ### NEVER\n91: - **NEVER** add a `graph-metadata.json` or a discoverable skill marker inside a mode packet or the shared reference base.\n92: - **NEVER** embed per-mode design instructions in this hub — that content lives in the packets.\n93: - **NEVER** treat `mcp-figma` or `mcp-open-design` as taste or critique authority; they are transports loaded after the design mode is chosen.\n94: - **NEVER** route pure code, backend, or data work through the design family.\n95: \n96: ### ESCALATE IF\n97: - A new design mode is needed — extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet; do not bolt logic onto the hub.\n98: - A named mode conflicts with the request's actual intent, or the prompt spans more than three design axes needing an explicit workflow order.\n99: - Brand, accessibility, or production constraints make the requested visual direction unsafe or contradictory.\n100: \n101: ---\n102: \n103: ## 5. REFERENCES\n104: \n105: - Shared reference base: `references/anti_slop_principles.md`, `references/cognitive_laws.md`, `references/design_token_vocabulary.md` (cited by every doc-guidance mode).\n106: - Mode packets: `design-interface/SKILL.md`, `design-foundations/SKILL.md`, `design-motion/SKILL.md`, `design-audit/SKILL.md`, `design-md-generator/SKILL.md` (per-mode detail).\n107: - Registry: `mode-registry.json` (the routing contract).\n108: - Implementation handoff: `sk-code` consumes the design output; `sk-code-review` can audit it after build.\n109: \n110: ---\n111: \n112: ## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n113: \n114: - The hub resolves one primary mode for the request (or a small set only for clearly separate axes).\n115: - The selected mode packet owns the detailed design workflow; the hub stayed routing-only.\n116: - The shared reference base is used only for common vocabulary and cross-mode consistency.\n117: - Exactly one `graph-metadata.json` exists for the whole skill; no packet carries its own.\n118: \n119: ---\n120: \n121: ## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n122: \n123: ### Modes\n124: - `interface` — direction, distinctive UI build judgment, interface writing.\n125: - `foundations` — color, typography, layout, responsive systems, tokens.\n126: - `motion` — animation, transitions, micro-interactions, temporal feel.\n127: - `audit` — accessibility, performance, critique, hardening, production readiness.\n128: - `md-generator` — `DESIGN.md` / style-reference extraction other skills consume.\n129: \n130: ### Transports and Consumers\n131: - `mcp-figma` and `mcp-open-design` are transports. Use them after the design mode is chosen.\n132: - `sk-code` consumes design output and implements it in the detected code surface.\n133: - `sk-code-review` can audit implementation quality after design and build work converge.\n134: \n135: ---\n136: \n137: ## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n138: \n139: - Pattern: `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/references/skill_creation/parent_skills_nested_packets.md` (parent-skill hub + nested packets, the one-graph-metadata invariant).\n140: - Canonical example: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/` (hub + `mode-registry.json` + mode packets).\n141: - Registry: `mode-registry.json` (this hub's routing contract).\n\n(End of file - total 141 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: sk-design\ndescription: \"Distinctive, intentional UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, taste, and build for interfaces; color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, and design tokens; animation, transitions, and micro-interactions; accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, and anti-slop design audit with quality scoring; and live-website CSS to Style Reference DESIGN.md extraction. Use to make a UI look custom and polished rather than templated, design a visual system, choreograph motion, audit and harden design quality, or extract a real design system from a live site. The single advisor-routable design skill: it routes to five modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) via mode-registry.json, and each mode holds its own design logic.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nmetadata:\n  author: OpenCode\n  family: sk-code\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: sk-design, design-family, mode-registry, workflowmode, backendkind, reference-base, anti-slop, design-tokens, cognitive-laws, interface-design, frontend-design, visual-design, visual-identity, make-it-look-good, looks-templated, redesign-the-ui, hero-section, ui-build, typography, palette, color-palette, font-pairing, ux-quality-checklist, design-variations, foundations, color-system, oklch, color-token-system, dark-mode, typography-scale, spacing-system, responsive-layout, layout, hierarchy, grid, themes, motion-design, animation, animate-this, transitions, micro-interactions, framer-motion, animatepresence, exit-animation, reduced-motion, morphing-icons, motion-performance, design-audit, ui-critique, accessibility-audit, performance-audit, anti-slop-detection, production-hardening, design-quality-score, P0-P1-design-findings, polish, theming, design.md, design-md, css-extraction, website-design-extraction, design-reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system-generator, css-tokens, color-extraction, typography-extraction, hex-extraction, shadow-extraction, spacing-extraction, design-fidelity, anti-hallucination, extract-design-system, generate-design-md, capture-website-css, design-tokens-from-url, distinctive-interface, intentional-design, polished-ui, refined-ui, custom-not-templated, premium-ui, aesthetic, design-taste, visual-direction, craft, make-it-beautiful, less-generic, redesign-distinctive, smooth-animation, hover-effect, scroll-animation, choreography, interaction-feel, animate-the-menu, transition-design, design-audit, accessibility-audit, design-quality-audit, design-review, design-qa, audit-the-design, review-the-ui, wcag-contrast, ui-quality-review -->\n\n# Design Family Hub (sk-design)\n\nOne skill, five design modes, one shared reference base. `sk-design` is the public, advisor-routable home for every design persona; the shared design reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) is the common vocabulary the modes cite. This hub holds NO per-mode design logic — each mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: sk-design\ndescription: \"Distinctive, intentional UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, taste, and build for interfaces; color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, and design tokens; animation, transitions, and micro-interactions; accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, and anti-slop design audit with quality scoring; and live-website CSS to Style Reference DESIGN.md extraction. Use to make a UI look custom and polished rather than templated, design a visual system, choreograph motion, audit and harden design quality, or extract a real design system from a live site. The single advisor-routable design skill: it routes to five modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) via mode-registry.json, and each mode holds its own design logic.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nmetadata:\n  author: OpenCode\n  family: sk-code\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: sk-design, design-family, mode-registry, workflowmode, backendkind, reference-base, anti-slop, design-tokens, cognitive-laws, interface-design, frontend-design, visual-design, visual-identity, make-it-look-good, looks-templated, redesign-the-ui, hero-section, ui-build, typography, palette, color-palette, font-pairing, ux-quality-checklist, design-variations, foundations, color-system, oklch, color-token-system, dark-mode, typography-scale, spacing-system, responsive-layout, layout, hierarchy, grid, themes, motion-design, animation, animate-this, transitions, micro-interactions, framer-motion, animatepresence, exit-animation, reduced-motion, morphing-icons, motion-performance, design-audit, ui-critique, accessibility-audit, performance-audit, anti-slop-detection, production-hardening, design-quality-score, P0-P1-design-findings, polish, theming, design.md, design-md, css-extraction, website-design-extraction, design-reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system-generator, css-tokens, color-extraction, typography-extraction, hex-extraction, shadow-extraction, spacing-extraction, design-fidelity, anti-hallucination, extract-design-system, generate-design-md, capture-website-css, design-tokens-from-url, distinctive-interface, intentional-design, polished-ui, refined-ui, custom-not-templated, premium-ui, aesthetic, design-taste, visual-direction, craft, make-it-beautiful, less-generic, redesign-distinctive, smooth-animation, hover-effect, scroll-animation, choreography, interaction-feel, animate-the-menu, transition-design, design-audit, accessibility-audit, design-quality-audit, design-review, design-qa, audit-the-design, review-the-ui, wcag-contrast, ui-quality-review -->\n\n# Design Family Hub (sk-design)\n\nOne skill, five design modes, one shared reference base. `sk-design` is the public, advisor-routable home for every design persona; the shared design reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) is the common vocabulary the modes cite. This hub holds NO per-mode design logic — each mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\nUse this skill (through the hub) for any design-family workflow. Invoke it as `sk-design` (optionally with a mode hint such as `motion: <request>`); the hub classifies the request, resolves a mode key, and loads the matching nested packet.\n\n| Mode | Use it for | Packet |\n|------|-----------|--------|\n| **interface** | Distinctive, intentional UI direction and build judgment, visual identity, redesign, generic \"make it look good\", interface writing | `sk-design/design-interface/` |\n| **foundations** | Static visual-system decisions: color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, responsive adaptation, themes, design tokens | `sk-design/design-foundations/` |\n| **motion** | Temporal interaction design: animation, transitions, micro-interactions, motion materials, `AnimatePresence`, reduced motion | `sk-design/design-motion/` |\n| **audit** | Design QA and critique: accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, anti-slop detection, scoring, production hardening | `sk-design/design-audit/` |\n| **md-generator** | Extract a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference `DESIGN.md` via the embedded extract-write-validate pipeline | `sk-design/design-md-generator/` |\n\n### When NOT to Use\n- A single quick read/edit with no design judgment — use the relevant skill directly.\n- Pure implementation after design direction is settled — hand off to `sk-code`.\n- A design transport only (Figma, Open Design) — load the design judgment via this hub first, then use the transport. The transport is never the taste authority.\n- The shared reference base itself — it is the vocabulary the modes cite, not a user workflow.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SMART ROUTING\n\nRouting is **registry-driven**. `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth; the hub reads it and does not re-derive the mapping. The advisor routes any design query to the single identity `sk-design`; the hub then picks the mode.\n\n### The discriminator\n- **`workflowMode`** — the public mode key (every mode): `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, `audit`, `md-generator`.\n- **`backendKind`** — which backend runs the mode: `reference-base` (the four doc-guidance modes cite the shared design reference base) or `playwright-extract` (`md-generator` runs its embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\n\n### Routing rule\n```\nclassify the request to a workflowMode (dominant design intent; mode hint like \"motion: ...\" overrides)\nread mode-registry.json\n  → resolve workflowMode from the hint / classified intent\n  → load the mode packet at registry[mode].packet (e.g. sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md)\n  → the mode cites the shared reference base, or runs its own backend per registry[mode].backendKind\n```\n\nIntent classification favors the smallest useful mode. Default a generic \"make this look good\" prompt to **interface** unless the prompt is explicitly foundations (tokens/color/type/layout), motion (animation/transition), audit (critique/accessibility/slop), or md-generator (`DESIGN.md`/style-reference extraction). Pair modes only when the prompt has clearly separate design axes (e.g. interface + motion for a landing page with substantial choreography).\n\nPer-mode behavior is **not flattened**: each packet keeps its own design judgment, examples, standards, verification, and tool-permission needs. The four doc-guidance modes are read-and-guide; `md-generator` is the only mode that runs an extraction pipeline (Write/Edit/Bash over Playwright).\n\n---\n\n## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n\n### Layout\n```\nsk-design/\n  SKILL.md               # this routing hub (no per-mode design logic)\n  mode-registry.json     # the discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)\n  graph-metadata.json    # the ONE advisor identity for the whole skill\n  references/            # shared design reference base the hub + modes cite\n  design-interface/  design-foundations/  design-motion/  design-audit/  design-md-generator/   # five mode packets\n```\n\nEach mode packet is self-contained (its own `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `assets/`, and `md-generator`'s extraction backend), with internal paths repointed and **no per-packet `graph-metadata.json`** — only this hub carries one, so the advisor discovers exactly one skill. The mode packet folders are created when the flat skills move under the hub; the hub references those packet paths now.\n\n### Backend\nThe four doc-guidance modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit) consume the shared **design reference base** under `references/` — `anti_slop_principles.md`, `cognitive_laws.md`, `design_token_vocabulary.md` — so anti-slop critique, design-token vocabulary, and cognitive-law rationale stay consistent across modes without duplication. The `md-generator` mode consumes its own embedded Playwright extraction backend instead. The reference base provides shared vocabulary; it must never gain per-mode workflow logic.\n\n---\n\n## 4. RULES\n\n### ALWAYS\n- **ALWAYS** resolve a mode through `mode-registry.json`; never hardcode a router mapping in the hub.\n- **ALWAYS** keep each mode's design judgment, examples, and verification in its packet — the hub stays logic-free.\n- **ALWAYS** keep exactly one `graph-metadata.json` (this hub's) so the advisor sees one skill identity.\n- **ALWAYS** give every mode an `advisorRouting` block with a valid `routingClass` and `packetSkillName`.\n- **ALWAYS** route a generic design prompt to the smallest useful mode; default to `interface` when no other axis dominates.\n\n### NEVER\n- **NEVER** add a `graph-metadata.json` or a discoverable skill marker inside a mode packet or the shared reference base.\n- **NEVER** embed per-mode design instructions in this hub — that content lives in the packets.\n- **NEVER** treat `mcp-figma` or `mcp-open-design` as taste or critique authority; they are transports loaded after the design mode is chosen.\n- **NEVER** route pure code, backend, or data work through the design family.\n\n### ESCALATE IF\n- A new design mode is needed — extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet; do not bolt logic onto the hub.\n- A named mode conflicts with the request's actual intent, or the prompt spans more than three design axes needing an explicit workflow order.\n- Brand, accessibility, or production constraints make the requested visual direction unsafe or contradictory.\n\n---\n\n## 5. REFERENCES\n\n- Shared reference base: `references/anti_slop_principles.md`, `references/cognitive_laws.md`, `references/design_token_vocabulary.md` (cited by every doc-guidance mode).\n- Mode packets: `design-interface/SKILL.md`, `design-foundations/SKILL.md`, `design-motion/SKILL.md`, `design-audit/SKILL.md`, `design-md-generator/SKILL.md` (per-mode detail).\n- Registry: `mode-registry.json` (the routing contract).\n- Implementation handoff: `sk-code` consumes the design output; `sk-code-review` can audit it after build.\n\n---\n\n## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n\n- The hub resolves one primary mode for the request (or a small set only for clearly separate axes).\n- The selected mode packet owns the detailed design workflow; the hub stayed routing-only.\n- The shared reference base is used only for common vocabulary and cross-mode consistency.\n- Exactly one `graph-metadata.json` exists for the whole skill; no packet carries its own.\n\n---\n\n## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n\n### Modes\n- `interface` — direction, distinctive UI build judgment, interface writing.\n- `foundations` — color, typography, layout, responsive systems, tokens.\n- `motion` — animation, transitions, micro-interactions, temporal feel.\n- `audit` — accessibility, performance, critique, hardening, production readiness.\n- `md-generator` — `DESIGN.md` / style-reference extraction other skills consume.\n\n### Transports and Consumers\n- `mcp-figma` and `mcp-open-design` are transports. Use them after the design mode is chosen.\n- `sk-code` consumes design output and implements it in the detected code surface.\n- `sk-code-review` can audit implementation quality after design and build work converge.\n\n---\n\n## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- Pattern: `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/references/skill_creation/parent_skills_nested_packets.md` (parent-skill hub + nested packets, the one-graph-metadata invariant).\n- Canonical example: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/` (hub + `mode-registry.json` + mode packets).\n- Registry: `mode-registry.json` (this hub's routing contract).","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":141,"totalLines":141,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782532340934,"end":1782532340937}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_045fe83177ea1858016a3f48f4d778819194388d8f476f653d"}},"id":"prt_f0734fcc4001MSd3HSNlDbwTH9","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532340940,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_rt9ntoD4wwaXmSCH0jTiGUL5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: design-audit\n3: description: Design QA and critique mode for accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, anti-slop detection, scoring, and production hardening.\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Grep, Glob, Task]\n5: version: 1.0.0.1\n6: metadata:\n7:   author: OpenCode\n8:   family: sk-code\n9: ---\n10: \n11: <!-- Keywords: audit, design-audit, accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, critique, polish, hardening, anti-slop, P0-P3, design-quality-score -->\n12: \n13: # Design Audit (audit)\n14: \n15: `audit` is the cross-cutting QA and critique MODE child of the `sk-design` family. It reviews built or planned interfaces for accessibility, performance, responsive behavior, theming, anti-patterns, design quality, and production hardening. It reports severity-ranked findings and a 5-dimension `/20` score.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n20: \n21: ### Activation Triggers\n22: \n23: Use this skill when the request involves:\n24: - Auditing or critiquing a UI, design plan, component, page, or design-system output.\n25: - Checking accessibility, contrast, keyboard navigation, focus, forms, ARIA, or WCAG compliance.\n26: - Reviewing animation performance, load performance, responsive behavior, touch targets, or production readiness.\n27: - Detecting AI-generated design slop, theming drift, token misuse, hard-coded values, or generic patterns, including the model-specific tell catalog for Codex, Gemini and 2026-general fingerprints.\n28: - Routing a bolder, quieter, distill or redesign direction to the right owner once a finding names the problem.\n29: - Producing a findings-first design quality report with P0-P3 severity and a `/20` score, including the fill-in report template.\n30: \n31: Keyword triggers: `audit design`, `critique UI`, `design review`, `accessibility audit`, `WCAG`, `performance audit`, `hardening`, `polish pass`, `responsive QA`, `anti-slop`, `looks AI-generated`, `AI tell`, `bolder`, `quieter`, `distill`, `quality score`, `P0`, `P1`.\n32: \n33: ### When NOT to Use\n34: \n35: Skip this skill when:\n36: - The user wants to invent a new visual direction. Use `interface`.\n37: - The user wants a static token system, palette, typography, or layout plan. Use `foundations`.\n38: - The user wants to create motion choreography. Use `motion`.\n39: - The user wants implementation after findings are accepted. Hand off to `sk-code`.\n40: - The user asks for a code review outside design/UI concerns. Use `sk-code-review`.\n41: \n42: ### Family Boundary\n43: \n44: This is an independently invokable member of the `sk-design` family. It owns review, scoring, severity, risk surfacing, and hardening. It may cite sibling standards but does not replace them.\n45: \n46: Pairs well with:\n47: - `interface` after a direction or build needs critique.\n48: - `foundations` when token/theming/layout findings need a system fix.\n49: - `motion` when motion-performance findings need choreography repair.\n50: - `sk-code-review` when the UI change also needs code correctness/security review.\n51: \n52: ---\n53: \n54: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n55: \n56: ### Primary Detection Signal\n57: \n58: Route by audit mode:\n59: \n60: ```text\n61: DESIGN QA TASK\n62:     |\n63:     +- Full audit / score / release readiness -> references/audit_contract.md\n64:     +- A11y or motion/load perf -> references/accessibility_performance.md\n65:     +- Critique / cognitive load / persona / polish -> references/critique_hardening.md\n66:     +- Edge cases / copy / pseudo-elements / production -> references/anti_patterns_production.md\n67: ```\n68: \n69: ### Phase Detection\n70: \n71: ```text\n72: DESIGN QA TASK\n73:     |\n74:     +- STEP 0: Detect audit mode (contract / a11y-perf / critique-harden / anti-pattern)\n75:     +- STEP 1: Score intents (top-2 when scores are close)\n76:     +- Phase 1: Resolve target and state evidence available vs missing\n77:     +- Phase 2: Findings + five-dimension scoring\n78:     +- Phase 3: Owner mapping and verification\n79: ```\n80: \n81: ### Resource Domains\n82: \n83: - `references/audit_contract.md` defines the P0-P3 severity model, 5-dimension `/20` scoring contract, output format, and evidence rules.\n84: - `references/accessibility_performance.md` covers accessible names, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms, announcements, contrast, motion performance, Core Web Vitals, and measurement.\n85: - `references/critique_hardening.md` covers critique workflow, cognitive load, Nielsen heuristics, personas, polish, edge cases, i18n, error states, and resilience.\n86: - `references/anti_patterns_production.md` covers slop detection, theming drift, token misuse, pseudo-elements, View Transitions, copy clarity, and production hardening.\n87: - `references/corpus_map.md` maps the source corpus.\n88: \n89: ### Resource Loading Levels\n90: \n91: | Level | When to Load | Resources |\n92: | --- | --- | --- |\n93: | ALWAYS | Any audit or critique | `references/corpus_map.md`, `references/audit_contract.md` |\n94: | ALWAYS | Set the audit-severity posture | `../shared/register.md` (the audit-severity dial weights findings by Brand-vs-Product posture) |\n95: | CONDITIONAL | Accessibility or performance concern | `references/accessibility_performance.md` |\n96: | CONDITIONAL | Holistic critique, UX score, persona, polish, hardening | `references/critique_hardening.md` |\n97: | CONDITIONAL | Slop, theming, pseudo-elements, copy clarity, production details | `references/anti_patterns_production.md` |\n98: | CONDITIONAL | Detecting model-specific AI tells | `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` (Codex, Gemini, 2026-general fingerprints as checkable findings) |\n99: | CONDITIONAL | Routing a bolder, quieter or simpler request | `references/transform_remediation.md` (register-gated transform verbs mapped to findings and owners) |\n100: | CONDITIONAL | Resolving the target and labeling evidence | `references/evidence_capture.md` (target resolution, browser and deterministic evidence, fallback labels) |\n101: | CONDITIONAL | Production-readiness and edge-case probes | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` (extreme inputs, errors, permissions, concurrency, i18n and RTL, text expansion, CJK and emoji) |\n102: | CONDITIONAL | Producing the audit report | `assets/audit_report_template.md` (fill-in 5-dimension score plus P0-P3 findings) |\n103: | CONDITIONAL | Citing the snippet-level accessibility fix | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` (accessible names, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms, announcements, contrast, motion) |\n104: | ON_DEMAND | Code correctness beyond UI quality | `sk-code-review` plus `sk-code` surface evidence |\n105: \n106: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n107: \n108: #### Smart Router (Resilience Pattern)\n109: \n110: > Pattern: see [sk-doc smart-router resilience template](../sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_smart_router.md) for the full runtime discovery, guarded load, routing-key, and fallback reference.\n111: \n112: The router fills in this skill's a11y/perf/critique/harden `INTENT_SIGNALS`, `RESOURCE_MAP`, loading levels, and routing key while keeping the resilience mechanics unchanged: discover resources at runtime, guard every path before loading, derive a routing key from the audit mode or task, and return an `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK` checklist when confidence is too low.\n113: \n114: - Pattern 1: Runtime Discovery - `discover_markdown_resources()` recursively scans `references/` and `assets/`.\n115: - Pattern 2: Existence-Check Before Load - `load_if_available()` guards, checks `inventory`, and suppresses repeats with `seen`.\n116: - Pattern 3: Extensible Routing Key - audit-mode intent labels route to keyed folders without static inventories.\n117: - Pattern 4: Multi-Tier Graceful Fallback - `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK` requests disambiguation and missing keyed families return a \"no knowledge base\" notice.\n118: \n119: ```python\n120: from pathlib import Path\n121: \n122: SKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\n123: RESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\n124: DEFAULT_RESOURCE = \"references/corpus_map.md\"\n125: \n126: INTENT_SIGNALS = {\n127:     \"AUDIT_CONTRACT\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"audit\", \"score\", \"release readiness\", \"severity\", \"p0\", \"p1\", \"quality score\", \"report template\"]},\n128:     \"ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"accessibility\", \"wcag\", \"aria\", \"keyboard\", \"focus\", \"contrast\", \"performance\", \"jank\", \"core web vitals\", \"a11y fix\"]},\n129:     \"CRITIQUE_HARDENING\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"critique\", \"cognitive\", \"heuristic\", \"persona\", \"polish\", \"harden\", \"edge case\", \"i18n\", \"production readiness\"]},\n130:     \"ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"slop\", \"ai-generated\", \"theme\", \"token\", \"pseudo\", \"copy\", \"clarify\", \"view transition\", \"fingerprint\", \"model tell\"]},\n131:     \"TRANSFORM_REMEDIATION\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"bolder\", \"quieter\", \"distill\", \"redesign\", \"transform\", \"remediation\", \"make it bolder\"]},\n132:     \"EVIDENCE_CAPTURE\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"evidence\", \"screenshot\", \"browser\", \"deterministic scan\", \"source target\", \"provenance\"]},\n133: }\n134: \n135: RESOURCE_MAP = {\n136:     \"AUDIT_CONTRACT\": [\"references/corpus_map.md\", \"references/audit_contract.md\", \"assets/audit_report_template.md\"],\n137:     \"ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE\": [\"references/accessibility_performance.md\", \"assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md\"],\n138:     \"CRITIQUE_HARDENING\": [\"references/critique_hardening.md\", \"references/hardening_edge_cases.md\"],\n139:     \"ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION\": [\"references/anti_patterns_production.md\", \"references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md\"],\n140:     \"TRANSFORM_REMEDIATION\": [\"references/transform_remediation.md\"],\n141:     \"EVIDENCE_CAPTURE\": [\"references/evidence_capture.md\"],\n142: }\n143: \n144: LOAD_LEVELS = {\n145:     \"AUDIT_CONTRACT\": \"STANDARD\",\n146:     \"ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE\": \"STANDARD\",\n147:     \"CRITIQUE_HARDENING\": \"STANDARD\",\n148:     \"ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION\": \"STANDARD\",\n149:     \"TRANSFORM_REMEDIATION\": \"STANDARD\",\n150:     \"EVIDENCE_CAPTURE\": \"STANDARD\",\n151: }\n152: \n153: UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\n154:     \"Confirm the audit mode: contract/score, accessibility/performance, critique/hardening, or anti-pattern/production\",\n155:     \"Confirm the target artifact: file, URL, screenshot, or design plan\",\n156:     \"Provide one concrete input, rendered observation, or expected output\",\n157:     \"Confirm whether a full five-dimension score or a focused review is needed\",\n158: ]\n159: \n160: AMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1\n161: \n162: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n163:     resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n164:     resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n165:     if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n166:         raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routable: {relative_path}\")\n167:     return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n168: \n169: def discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n170:     docs = []\n171:     for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n172:         if base.exists():\n173:             docs.extend(path for path in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if path.is_file())\n174:     return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}\n175: \n176: def get_routing_key(task, intents: list[str]) -> str:\n177:     override = str(getattr(task, \"routing_key\", \"\")).strip().lower()\n178:     if override:\n179:         return override\n180:     return (intents[0] if intents else \"unknown\").lower()\n181: \n182: def classify_intents(user_request, task=None):\n183:     text = (user_request or \"\").lower()\n184:     scores = {intent: 0 for intent in INTENT_SIGNALS}\n185:     for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n186:         for keyword, weight in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n187:             if keyword in text:\n188:                 scores[intent] += weight\n189: \n190:     ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda pair: pair[1], reverse=True)\n191:     primary, primary_score = ranked[0]\n192:     secondary, secondary_score = ranked[1]\n193:     if secondary_score > 0 and (primary_score - secondary_score) <= AMBIGUITY_DELTA:\n194:         return (primary, secondary, scores)\n195:     return (primary, None, scores)\n196: \n197: def route_audit_resources(user_request, task=None):\n198:     inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n199:     primary, secondary, scores = classify_intents(user_request, task)\n200:     intents = [primary] + ([secondary] if secondary else [])\n201:     routing_key = get_routing_key(task, intents)\n202:     reference_prefix = f\"references/{routing_key}/\"\n203:     asset_prefix = f\"assets/{routing_key}/\"\n204:     keyed_refs = sorted(path for path in inventory if path.startswith(reference_prefix))\n205:     keyed_assets = sorted(path for path in inventory if path.startswith(asset_prefix))\n206:     loaded = []\n207:     seen = set()\n208: \n209:     def load_if_available(relative_path: str):\n210:         guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n211:         if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n212:             load(guarded)\n213:             loaded.append(guarded)\n214:             seen.add(guarded)\n215: \n216:     load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n217:     baseline_count = len(loaded)\n218:     if max(scores.values() or [0]) < 0.5:\n219:         return {\n220:             \"routing_key\": routing_key,\n221:             \"intents\": intents,\n222:             \"intent_scores\": scores,\n223:             \"load_level\": \"UNKNOWN_FALLBACK\",\n224:             \"needs_disambiguation\": True,\n225:             \"disambiguation_checklist\": UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST,\n226:             \"resources\": loaded,\n227:         }\n228: \n229:     for intent in intents:\n230:         for relative_path in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n231:             load_if_available(relative_path)\n232: \n233:     for relative_path in keyed_refs:\n234:         load_if_available(relative_path)\n235:     for relative_path in keyed_assets:\n236:         load_if_available(relative_path)\n237: \n238:     if routing_key == \"unknown\" or (len(loaded) == baseline_count and not keyed_refs):\n239:         return {\n240:             \"routing_key\": routing_key,\n241:             \"intents\": intents,\n242:             \"intent_scores\": scores,\n243:             \"notice\": f\"No keyed knowledge base found for routing key '{routing_key}'\",\n244:             \"resources\": loaded,\n245:         }\n246: \n247:     return {\"routing_key\": routing_key, \"intents\": intents, \"intent_scores\": scores, \"resources\": loaded}\n248: ```\n249: \n250: ---\n251: \n252: ## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n253: \n254: ### Audit Workflow\n255: \n256: 1. Resolve the target and the register: source files, URL, screenshot, design plan or rendered UI evidence, then read `../shared/register.md` so the audit-severity dial weights findings by Brand-vs-Product posture. `references/evidence_capture.md` owns target resolution.\n257: 2. State evidence available and evidence missing. A visual claim needs visual evidence or a clear caveat. A finding read from real evidence is confirmed, while a finding from a screenshot alone is inferred.\n258: 3. Score the five audit dimensions 0-4 each:\n259:    - Accessibility.\n260:    - Performance.\n261:    - Responsive Design.\n262:    - Theming.\n263:    - Anti-Patterns. Detect model-specific tells with `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` and probe production readiness with `references/hardening_edge_cases.md`.\n264: 4. Produce a findings-first report ordered by P0, P1, P2, P3. Use `assets/audit_report_template.md` for the fill-in skeleton.\n265: 5. Map each finding to the owning sibling or implementation skill. Route a bolder, quieter, distill or redesign direction through `references/transform_remediation.md` first, because the correct direction depends on the register.\n266: 6. End with recommended next actions; do not silently implement fixes during a review-only request.\n267: \n268: ### Severity Model\n269: \n270: Use the same findings-first spirit as `sk-code-review`: concrete evidence, severity order, impact, and recommended fix.\n271: \n272: | Severity | Meaning | Release effect |\n273: | --- | --- | --- |\n274: | P0 Critical | Prevents task completion, blocks access, creates severe WCAG failure, or makes UI unusable | Must fix immediately |\n275: | P1 High | Significant user difficulty, WCAG AA violation, broken responsive behavior, severe jank, or systemic token drift | Fix before release |\n276: | P2 Medium | Annoyance or quality issue with a workaround, localized performance issue, minor inconsistency | Fix in next pass |\n277: | P3 Polish | Nice-to-fix detail with low user impact | Fix if time permits |\n278: \n279: ### 5-Dimension Score\n280: \n281: Each dimension scores 0-4. Total `/20` rating:\n282: - `18-20` Excellent: minor polish only.\n283: - `14-17` Good: address weak dimensions.\n284: - `10-13` Acceptable: significant work needed.\n285: - `6-9` Poor: major overhaul.\n286: - `0-5` Critical: fundamental issues.\n287: \n288: ---\n289: \n290: ## 4. RULES\n291: \n292: ### ALWAYS\n293: \n294: 1. Present findings before summary when doing a review or audit.\n295: 2. Include evidence for every actionable finding: file/line, rendered behavior, prompt output, screenshot observation, or explicit limitation.\n296: 3. Score all five dimensions for full audits; mark a dimension `not assessed` only when evidence is unavailable and explain why.\n297: 4. Apply accessibility minimums first: accessible names, keyboard access, focus, semantics, forms, announcements, contrast, and reduced motion.\n298: 5. Separate design critique from deterministic findings; both can matter, but label the evidence type.\n299: 6. Explain user impact, not just rule violation.\n300: 7. Map each fix to the right owner: foundations, motion, interface, spec/extraction, or code implementation.\n301: 8. Celebrate positive findings briefly so teams know what to preserve.\n302: \n303: ### NEVER\n304: \n305: 1. Never report vague issues without location, impact, and fix.\n306: 2. Never claim a design is accessible without keyboard, focus, name, semantics, and contrast evidence.\n307: 3. Never treat a clean automated scan as proof of strong design.\n308: 4. Never score generously to avoid criticism; a `4` means genuinely excellent.\n309: 5. Never bury a P0/P1 under polish comments.\n310: 6. Never invent browser, screenshot, or detector evidence.\n311: 7. Never recommend a sibling skill when it addresses zero findings.\n312: \n313: ### ESCALATE IF\n314: \n315: 1. The target cannot be resolved to a file, URL, screenshot, or concrete design artifact.\n316: 2. Visual evidence is required but unavailable and the score would be misleading.\n317: 3. Accessibility or performance findings imply high-impact implementation changes outside design scope.\n318: 4. Brand or legal constraints conflict with accessibility or production hardening.\n319: \n320: ---\n321: \n322: ## 5. REFERENCES\n323: \n324: ### Core References\n325: \n326: - [`references/audit_contract.md`](references/audit_contract.md) - Severity, `/20` score, findings schema, and audit output contract.\n327: - [`references/accessibility_performance.md`](references/accessibility_performance.md) - Accessibility and performance checks.\n328: - [`references/critique_hardening.md`](references/critique_hardening.md) - Holistic critique, cognitive load, personas, polish, and hardening.\n329: - [`references/anti_patterns_production.md`](references/anti_patterns_production.md) - Anti-slop, theming, pseudo-elements, copy clarity, and production details.\n330: - [`references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md`](references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md) - Model-specific AI tells turned into checkable P0-P3 findings.\n331: - [`references/transform_remediation.md`](references/transform_remediation.md) - Register-gated directional verbs mapped to findings and owners.\n332: - [`references/evidence_capture.md`](references/evidence_capture.md) - Target resolution, browser and deterministic evidence, screenshot and overlay notes, fallback labels.\n333: - [`references/hardening_edge_cases.md`](references/hardening_edge_cases.md) - Production-readiness matrix of extreme inputs, errors, permissions, concurrency, i18n and RTL, text expansion, CJK and emoji.\n334: - [`references/corpus_map.md`](references/corpus_map.md) - Source traceability for the distilled corpus.\n335: \n336: ### Assets\n337: \n338: - [`assets/audit_report_template.md`](assets/audit_report_template.md) - Fill-in findings-first report with the five-dimension `/20` score, anti-pattern verdict, owner mapping, and evidence caveats.\n339: - [`assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md`](assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md) - Snippet-level accessibility fixes the report cites by reference; the audit names the fix, `sk-code` applies it.\n340: \n341: ### Parent Shared Base\n342: \n343: Use, do not duplicate, the parent references for shared vocabulary:\n344: - [`../shared/register.md`](../shared/register.md) - The Brand-vs-Product register that sets the audit-severity dial; outside this mode's scope, so cited explicitly.\n345: - `../shared/anti_slop_principles.md`\n346: - `../shared/design_token_vocabulary.md`\n347: - `../shared/cognitive_laws.md`\n348: \n349: ---\n350: \n351: ## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n352: \n353: - Audit output is findings-first, severity-ordered and evidence-backed, with each finding labeled confirmed or inferred.\n354: - The register is resolved before scoring so the audit-severity dial weights findings by Brand-vs-Product posture.\n355: - Full audits include the five-dimension `/20` score or explicit caveats for unassessed dimensions. The fill-in report template carries the structure when a full report is requested.\n356: - Accessibility, performance, responsive, theming and anti-patterns are all considered, with model-specific tells and production-readiness edge cases checked where they apply.\n357: - Findings map to concrete next actions and owning skills, with directional remediation routed by register.\n358: - No positive completion or release-readiness claim is made from missing evidence.\n359: \n360: ---\n361: \n362: ## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n363: \n364: - `sk-design` routes audit, critique, and hardening prompts here.\n365: - `interface` owns direction changes recommended by critique.\n366: - `foundations` owns color, type, layout, responsive, and theming fixes.\n367: - `motion` owns motion choreography fixes.\n368: - `sk-code` implements accepted fixes.\n369: - `sk-code-review` handles broader code correctness, security, and test-quality review.\n370: \n371: ---\n372: \n373: ## 8. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n374: \n375: Manual validation scenarios live in `manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md`. Release notes live in `changelog/`; the latest is `changelog/v1.0.0.0.md`.\n\n(End of file - total 375 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: design-audit\ndescription: Design QA and critique mode for accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, anti-slop detection, scoring, and production hardening.\nallowed-tools: [Read, Grep, Glob, Task]\nversion: 1.0.0.1\nmetadata:\n  author: OpenCode\n  family: sk-code\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: audit, design-audit, accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, critique, polish, hardening, anti-slop, P0-P3, design-quality-score -->\n\n# Design Audit (audit)\n\n`audit` is the cross-cutting QA and critique MODE child of the `sk-design` family. It reviews built or planned interfaces for accessibility, performance, responsive behavior, theming, anti-patterns, design quality, and production hardening. It reports severity-ranked findings and a 5-dimension `/20` score.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: design-audit\ndescription: Design QA and critique mode for accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, anti-slop detection, scoring, and production hardening.\nallowed-tools: [Read, Grep, Glob, Task]\nversion: 1.0.0.1\nmetadata:\n  author: OpenCode\n  family: sk-code\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: audit, design-audit, accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, critique, polish, hardening, anti-slop, P0-P3, design-quality-score -->\n\n# Design Audit (audit)\n\n`audit` is the cross-cutting QA and critique MODE child of the `sk-design` family. It reviews built or planned interfaces for accessibility, performance, responsive behavior, theming, anti-patterns, design quality, and production hardening. It reports severity-ranked findings and a 5-dimension `/20` score.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\n### Activation Triggers\n\nUse this skill when the request involves:\n- Auditing or critiquing a UI, design plan, component, page, or design-system output.\n- Checking accessibility, contrast, keyboard navigation, focus, forms, ARIA, or WCAG compliance.\n- Reviewing animation performance, load performance, responsive behavior, touch targets, or production readiness.\n- Detecting AI-generated design slop, theming drift, token misuse, hard-coded values, or generic patterns, including the model-specific tell catalog for Codex, Gemini and 2026-general fingerprints.\n- Routing a bolder, quieter, distill or redesign direction to the right owner once a finding names the problem.\n- Producing a findings-first design quality report with P0-P3 severity and a `/20` score, including the fill-in report template.\n\nKeyword triggers: `audit design`, `critique UI`, `design review`, `accessibility audit`, `WCAG`, `performance audit`, `hardening`, `polish pass`, `responsive QA`, `anti-slop`, `looks AI-generated`, `AI tell`, `bolder`, `quieter`, `distill`, `quality score`, `P0`, `P1`.\n\n### When NOT to Use\n\nSkip this skill when:\n- The user wants to invent a new visual direction. Use `interface`.\n- The user wants a static token system, palette, typography, or layout plan. Use `foundations`.\n- The user wants to create motion choreography. Use `motion`.\n- The user wants implementation after findings are accepted. Hand off to `sk-code`.\n- The user asks for a code review outside design/UI concerns. Use `sk-code-review`.\n\n### Family Boundary\n\nThis is an independently invokable member of the `sk-design` family. It owns review, scoring, severity, risk surfacing, and hardening. It may cite sibling standards but does not replace them.\n\nPairs well with:\n- `interface` after a direction or build needs critique.\n- `foundations` when token/theming/layout findings need a system fix.\n- `motion` when motion-performance findings need choreography repair.\n- `sk-code-review` when the UI change also needs code correctness/security review.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SMART ROUTING\n\n### Primary Detection Signal\n\nRoute by audit mode:\n\n```text\nDESIGN QA TASK\n    |\n    +- Full audit / score / release readiness -> references/audit_contract.md\n    +- A11y or motion/load perf -> references/accessibility_performance.md\n    +- Critique / cognitive load / persona / polish -> references/critique_hardening.md\n    +- Edge cases / copy / pseudo-elements / production -> references/anti_patterns_production.md\n```\n\n### Phase Detection\n\n```text\nDESIGN QA TASK\n    |\n    +- STEP 0: Detect audit mode (contract / a11y-perf / critique-harden / anti-pattern)\n    +- STEP 1: Score intents (top-2 when scores are close)\n    +- Phase 1: Resolve target and state evidence available vs missing\n    +- Phase 2: Findings + five-dimension scoring\n    +- Phase 3: Owner mapping and verification\n```\n\n### Resource Domains\n\n- `references/audit_contract.md` defines the P0-P3 severity model, 5-dimension `/20` scoring contract, output format, and evidence rules.\n- `references/accessibility_performance.md` covers accessible names, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms, announcements, contrast, motion performance, Core Web Vitals, and measurement.\n- `references/critique_hardening.md` covers critique workflow, cognitive load, Nielsen heuristics, personas, polish, edge cases, i18n, error states, and resilience.\n- `references/anti_patterns_production.md` covers slop detection, theming drift, token misuse, pseudo-elements, View Transitions, copy clarity, and production hardening.\n- `references/corpus_map.md` maps the source corpus.\n\n### Resource Loading Levels\n\n| Level | When to Load | Resources |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| ALWAYS | Any audit or critique | `references/corpus_map.md`, `references/audit_contract.md` |\n| ALWAYS | Set the audit-severity posture | `../shared/register.md` (the audit-severity dial weights findings by Brand-vs-Product posture) |\n| CONDITIONAL | Accessibility or performance concern | `references/accessibility_performance.md` |\n| CONDITIONAL | Holistic critique, UX score, persona, polish, hardening | `references/critique_hardening.md` |\n| CONDITIONAL | Slop, theming, pseudo-elements, copy clarity, production details | `references/anti_patterns_production.md` |\n| CONDITIONAL | Detecting model-specific AI tells | `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` (Codex, Gemini, 2026-general fingerprints as checkable findings) |\n| CONDITIONAL | Routing a bolder, quieter or simpler request | `references/transform_remediation.md` (register-gated transform verbs mapped to findings and owners) |\n| CONDITIONAL | Resolving the target and labeling evidence | `references/evidence_capture.md` (target resolution, browser and deterministic evidence, fallback labels) |\n| CONDITIONAL | Production-readiness and edge-case probes | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` (extreme inputs, errors, permissions, concurrency, i18n and RTL, text expansion, CJK and emoji) |\n| CONDITIONAL | Producing the audit report | `assets/audit_report_template.md` (fill-in 5-dimension score plus P0-P3 findings) |\n| CONDITIONAL | Citing the snippet-level accessibility fix | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` (accessible names, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms, announcements, contrast, motion) |\n| ON_DEMAND | Code correctness beyond UI quality | `sk-code-review` plus `sk-code` surface evidence |\n\n### Smart Router Pseudocode\n\n#### Smart Router (Resilience Pattern)\n\n> Pattern: see [sk-doc smart-router resilience template](../sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_smart_router.md) for the full runtime discovery, guarded load, routing-key, and fallback reference.\n\nThe router fills in this skill's a11y/perf/critique/harden `INTENT_SIGNALS`, `RESOURCE_MAP`, loading levels, and routing key while keeping the resilience mechanics unchanged: discover resources at runtime, guard every path before loading, derive a routing key from the audit mode or task, and return an `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK` checklist when confidence is too low.\n\n- Pattern 1: Runtime Discovery - `discover_markdown_resources()` recursively scans `references/` and `assets/`.\n- Pattern 2: Existence-Check Before Load - `load_if_available()` guards, checks `inventory`, and suppresses repeats with `seen`.\n- Pattern 3: Extensible Routing Key - audit-mode intent labels route to keyed folders without static inventories.\n- Pattern 4: Multi-Tier Graceful Fallback - `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK` requests disambiguation and missing keyed families return a \"no knowledge base\" notice.\n\n```python\nfrom pathlib import Path\n\nSKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\nRESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\nDEFAULT_RESOURCE = \"references/corpus_map.md\"\n\nINTENT_SIGNALS = {\n    \"AUDIT_CONTRACT\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"audit\", \"score\", \"release readiness\", \"severity\", \"p0\", \"p1\", \"quality score\", \"report template\"]},\n    \"ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"accessibility\", \"wcag\", \"aria\", \"keyboard\", \"focus\", \"contrast\", \"performance\", \"jank\", \"core web vitals\", \"a11y fix\"]},\n    \"CRITIQUE_HARDENING\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"critique\", \"cognitive\", \"heuristic\", \"persona\", \"polish\", \"harden\", \"edge case\", \"i18n\", \"production readiness\"]},\n    \"ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"slop\", \"ai-generated\", \"theme\", \"token\", \"pseudo\", \"copy\", \"clarify\", \"view transition\", \"fingerprint\", \"model tell\"]},\n    \"TRANSFORM_REMEDIATION\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"bolder\", \"quieter\", \"distill\", \"redesign\", \"transform\", \"remediation\", \"make it bolder\"]},\n    \"EVIDENCE_CAPTURE\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"evidence\", \"screenshot\", \"browser\", \"deterministic scan\", \"source target\", \"provenance\"]},\n}\n\nRESOURCE_MAP = {\n    \"AUDIT_CONTRACT\": [\"references/corpus_map.md\", \"references/audit_contract.md\", \"assets/audit_report_template.md\"],\n    \"ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE\": [\"references/accessibility_performance.md\", \"assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md\"],\n    \"CRITIQUE_HARDENING\": [\"references/critique_hardening.md\", \"references/hardening_edge_cases.md\"],\n    \"ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION\": [\"references/anti_patterns_production.md\", \"references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md\"],\n    \"TRANSFORM_REMEDIATION\": [\"references/transform_remediation.md\"],\n    \"EVIDENCE_CAPTURE\": [\"references/evidence_capture.md\"],\n}\n\nLOAD_LEVELS = {\n    \"AUDIT_CONTRACT\": \"STANDARD\",\n    \"ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE\": \"STANDARD\",\n    \"CRITIQUE_HARDENING\": \"STANDARD\",\n    \"ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION\": \"STANDARD\",\n    \"TRANSFORM_REMEDIATION\": \"STANDARD\",\n    \"EVIDENCE_CAPTURE\": \"STANDARD\",\n}\n\nUNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\n    \"Confirm the audit mode: contract/score, accessibility/performance, critique/hardening, or anti-pattern/production\",\n    \"Confirm the target artifact: file, URL, screenshot, or design plan\",\n    \"Provide one concrete input, rendered observation, or expected output\",\n    \"Confirm whether a full five-dimension score or a focused review is needed\",\n]\n\nAMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1\n\ndef _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n    resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n    resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n    if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n        raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routable: {relative_path}\")\n    return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n\ndef discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n    docs = []\n    for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n        if base.exists():\n            docs.extend(path for path in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if path.is_file())\n    return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}\n\ndef get_routing_key(task, intents: list[str]) -> str:\n    override = str(getattr(task, \"routing_key\", \"\")).strip().lower()\n    if override:\n        return override\n    return (intents[0] if intents else \"unknown\").lower()\n\ndef classify_intents(user_request, task=None):\n    text = (user_request or \"\").lower()\n    scores = {intent: 0 for intent in INTENT_SIGNALS}\n    for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n        for keyword, weight in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n            if keyword in text:\n                scores[intent] += weight\n\n    ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda pair: pair[1], reverse=True)\n    primary, primary_score = ranked[0]\n    secondary, secondary_score = ranked[1]\n    if secondary_score > 0 and (primary_score - secondary_score) <= AMBIGUITY_DELTA:\n        return (primary, secondary, scores)\n    return (primary, None, scores)\n\ndef route_audit_resources(user_request, task=None):\n    inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n    primary, secondary, scores = classify_intents(user_request, task)\n    intents = [primary] + ([secondary] if secondary else [])\n    routing_key = get_routing_key(task, intents)\n    reference_prefix = f\"references/{routing_key}/\"\n    asset_prefix = f\"assets/{routing_key}/\"\n    keyed_refs = sorted(path for path in inventory if path.startswith(reference_prefix))\n    keyed_assets = sorted(path for path in inventory if path.startswith(asset_prefix))\n    loaded = []\n    seen = set()\n\n    def load_if_available(relative_path: str):\n        guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n        if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n            load(guarded)\n            loaded.append(guarded)\n            seen.add(guarded)\n\n    load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n    baseline_count = len(loaded)\n    if max(scores.values() or [0]) < 0.5:\n        return {\n            \"routing_key\": routing_key,\n            \"intents\": intents,\n            \"intent_scores\": scores,\n            \"load_level\": \"UNKNOWN_FALLBACK\",\n            \"needs_disambiguation\": True,\n            \"disambiguation_checklist\": UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST,\n            \"resources\": loaded,\n        }\n\n    for intent in intents:\n        for relative_path in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n            load_if_available(relative_path)\n\n    for relative_path in keyed_refs:\n        load_if_available(relative_path)\n    for relative_path in keyed_assets:\n        load_if_available(relative_path)\n\n    if routing_key == \"unknown\" or (len(loaded) == baseline_count and not keyed_refs):\n        return {\n            \"routing_key\": routing_key,\n            \"intents\": intents,\n            \"intent_scores\": scores,\n            \"notice\": f\"No keyed knowledge base found for routing key '{routing_key}'\",\n            \"resources\": loaded,\n        }\n\n    return {\"routing_key\": routing_key, \"intents\": intents, \"intent_scores\": scores, \"resources\": loaded}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n\n### Audit Workflow\n\n1. Resolve the target and the register: source files, URL, screenshot, design plan or rendered UI evidence, then read `../shared/register.md` so the audit-severity dial weights findings by Brand-vs-Product posture. `references/evidence_capture.md` owns target resolution.\n2. State evidence available and evidence missing. A visual claim needs visual evidence or a clear caveat. A finding read from real evidence is confirmed, while a finding from a screenshot alone is inferred.\n3. Score the five audit dimensions 0-4 each:\n   - Accessibility.\n   - Performance.\n   - Responsive Design.\n   - Theming.\n   - Anti-Patterns. Detect model-specific tells with `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` and probe production readiness with `references/hardening_edge_cases.md`.\n4. Produce a findings-first report ordered by P0, P1, P2, P3. Use `assets/audit_report_template.md` for the fill-in skeleton.\n5. Map each finding to the owning sibling or implementation skill. Route a bolder, quieter, distill or redesign direction through `references/transform_remediation.md` first, because the correct direction depends on the register.\n6. End with recommended next actions; do not silently implement fixes during a review-only request.\n\n### Severity Model\n\nUse the same findings-first spirit as `sk-code-review`: concrete evidence, severity order, impact, and recommended fix.\n\n| Severity | Meaning | Release effect |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| P0 Critical | Prevents task completion, blocks access, creates severe WCAG failure, or makes UI unusable | Must fix immediately |\n| P1 High | Significant user difficulty, WCAG AA violation, broken responsive behavior, severe jank, or systemic token drift | Fix before release |\n| P2 Medium | Annoyance or quality issue with a workaround, localized performance issue, minor inconsistency | Fix in next pass |\n| P3 Polish | Nice-to-fix detail with low user impact | Fix if time permits |\n\n### 5-Dimension Score\n\nEach dimension scores 0-4. Total `/20` rating:\n- `18-20` Excellent: minor polish only.\n- `14-17` Good: address weak dimensions.\n- `10-13` Acceptable: significant work needed.\n- `6-9` Poor: major overhaul.\n- `0-5` Critical: fundamental issues.\n\n---\n\n## 4. RULES\n\n### ALWAYS\n\n1. Present findings before summary when doing a review or audit.\n2. Include evidence for every actionable finding: file/line, rendered behavior, prompt output, screenshot observation, or explicit limitation.\n3. Score all five dimensions for full audits; mark a dimension `not assessed` only when evidence is unavailable and explain why.\n4. Apply accessibility minimums first: accessible names, keyboard access, focus, semantics, forms, announcements, contrast, and reduced motion.\n5. Separate design critique from deterministic findings; both can matter, but label the evidence type.\n6. Explain user impact, not just rule violation.\n7. Map each fix to the right owner: foundations, motion, interface, spec/extraction, or code implementation.\n8. Celebrate positive findings briefly so teams know what to preserve.\n\n### NEVER\n\n1. Never report vague issues without location, impact, and fix.\n2. Never claim a design is accessible without keyboard, focus, name, semantics, and contrast evidence.\n3. Never treat a clean automated scan as proof of strong design.\n4. Never score generously to avoid criticism; a `4` means genuinely excellent.\n5. Never bury a P0/P1 under polish comments.\n6. Never invent browser, screenshot, or detector evidence.\n7. Never recommend a sibling skill when it addresses zero findings.\n\n### ESCALATE IF\n\n1. The target cannot be resolved to a file, URL, screenshot, or concrete design artifact.\n2. Visual evidence is required but unavailable and the score would be misleading.\n3. Accessibility or performance findings imply high-impact implementation changes outside design scope.\n4. Brand or legal constraints conflict with accessibility or production hardening.\n\n---\n\n## 5. REFERENCES\n\n### Core References\n\n- [`references/audit_contract.md`](references/audit_contract.md) - Severity, `/20` score, findings schema, and audit output contract.\n- [`references/accessibility_performance.md`](references/accessibility_performance.md) - Accessibility and performance checks.\n- [`references/critique_hardening.md`](references/critique_hardening.md) - Holistic critique, cognitive load, personas, polish, and hardening.\n- [`references/anti_patterns_production.md`](references/anti_patterns_production.md) - Anti-slop, theming, pseudo-elements, copy clarity, and production details.\n- [`references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md`](references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md) - Model-specific AI tells turned into checkable P0-P3 findings.\n- [`references/transform_remediation.md`](references/transform_remediation.md) - Register-gated directional verbs mapped to findings and owners.\n- [`references/evidence_capture.md`](references/evidence_capture.md) - Target resolution, browser and deterministic evidence, screenshot and overlay notes, fallback labels.\n- [`references/hardening_edge_cases.md`](references/hardening_edge_cases.md) - Production-readiness matrix of extreme inputs, errors, permissions, concurrency, i18n and RTL, text expansion, CJK and emoji.\n- [`references/corpus_map.md`](references/corpus_map.md) - Source traceability for the distilled corpus.\n\n### Assets\n\n- [`assets/audit_report_template.md`](assets/audit_report_template.md) - Fill-in findings-first report with the five-dimension `/20` score, anti-pattern verdict, owner mapping, and evidence caveats.\n- [`assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md`](assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md) - Snippet-level accessibility fixes the report cites by reference; the audit names the fix, `sk-code` applies it.\n\n### Parent Shared Base\n\nUse, do not duplicate, the parent references for shared vocabulary:\n- [`../shared/register.md`](../shared/register.md) - The Brand-vs-Product register that sets the audit-severity dial; outside this mode's scope, so cited explicitly.\n- `../shared/anti_slop_principles.md`\n- `../shared/design_token_vocabulary.md`\n- `../shared/cognitive_laws.md`\n\n---\n\n## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n\n- Audit output is findings-first, severity-ordered and evidence-backed, with each finding labeled confirmed or inferred.\n- The register is resolved before scoring so the audit-severity dial weights findings by Brand-vs-Product posture.\n- Full audits include the five-dimension `/20` score or explicit caveats for unassessed dimensions. The fill-in report template carries the structure when a full report is requested.\n- Accessibility, performance, responsive, theming and anti-patterns are all considered, with model-specific tells and production-readiness edge cases checked where they apply.\n- Findings map to concrete next actions and owning skills, with directional remediation routed by register.\n- No positive completion or release-readiness claim is made from missing evidence.\n\n---\n\n## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n\n- `sk-design` routes audit, critique, and hardening prompts here.\n- `interface` owns direction changes recommended by critique.\n- `foundations` owns color, type, layout, responsive, and theming fixes.\n- `motion` owns motion choreography fixes.\n- `sk-code` implements accepted fixes.\n- `sk-code-review` handles broader code correctness, security, and test-quality review.\n\n---\n\n## 8. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n\nManual validation scenarios live in `manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md`. Release notes live in `changelog/`; the latest is `changelog/v1.0.0.0.md`.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":375,"totalLines":375,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782532340931,"end":1782532340939}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_045fe83177ea1858016a3f48f4d7688191b42c6d3969eb0887"}},"id":"prt_f0734fcb7001u4Xd0pPOszLYRH","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532340986,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_fCG0ptTo72n2mqtBohyfWfTF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md","offset":1,"limit":1200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Evidence Capture\n3: description: The evidence model for an audit. How to resolve the target, gather browser and deterministic evidence, record screenshot and overlay notes, then label findings honestly when evidence is unavailable.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"evidence capture\"\n6:   - \"audit evidence model\"\n7:   - \"resolve audit target\"\n8:   - \"fallback label evidence\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Evidence Capture\n15: \n16: Every finding rests on evidence, and the quality of an audit is the quality of that evidence. This reference is the evidence model: how to resolve the surface to a stable target, what counts as evidence, then how to label a finding when the evidence you wanted was out of reach. The severity model and the per-finding schema live in `audit_contract.md`. This file is the layer underneath it, the part that decides whether a finding is confirmed or inferred before it ever gets a severity.\n17: \n18: The audit gathers and labels evidence. It does not implement the fix, which is `sk-code` work once the user accepts the recommendation.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. RESOLVE THE TARGET\n23: \n24: Resolve the request to one concrete target before any evidence is gathered. A vague target produces vague findings.\n25: \n26: 1. **Prefer a source path over a dev-server URL** when both name the same surface. Ports drift and dev servers restart, file paths stay put. Use the URL only when no source path identifies the surface, such as a deployed page you cannot map to a file.\n27: 2. **Map the phrasing to a concrete artifact.**\n28:    - \"the homepage\" resolves to the page source or the rendered route.\n29:    - \"the settings modal\" resolves to the primary component file.\n30:    - \"this page\" resolves to the current URL or the open source file.\n31: 3. **Pass markup to deterministic scans, not CSS-only files.** A stylesheet alone is not a scannable target.\n32: 4. **Narrow a very large tree before scanning.** For a tree of several hundred scannable files, scope to the surface in question or ask which surface to audit. Do not scan the whole repository to review one page.\n33: \n34: State the resolved target at the top of the report so the reader knows exactly what was looked at. If the target cannot be resolved to a file, URL, screenshot or concrete design artifact, escalate rather than audit a guess.\n35: \n36: ---\n37: \n38: ## 2. THE THREE EVIDENCE TYPES\n39: \n40: An audit draws on three kinds of evidence. Each finding cites at least one, and the type is part of the finding.\n41: \n42: | Evidence type | What it is | Strength |\n43: |---|---|---|\n44: | Source | The actual file and line, the selector, the declared value | Strongest. A defect read in the code is a confirmed defect. |\n45: | Rendered | A live page, a screenshot, an observed behavior | Confirms what the surface does, not always why. Pair with source when both exist. |\n46: | Design-artifact | A plan, a spec, a wireframe with no built surface yet | Weakest for runtime claims. Good for intent, cannot prove behavior. |\n47: \n48: Source plus rendered together is the gold standard: the code explains the cause and the render proves the effect. When only one is available, the finding is still valid, but its label in Section 5 must say which one.\n49: \n50: ---\n51: \n52: ## 3. BROWSER EVIDENCE\n53: \n54: When browser automation is available and the target is viewable, rendered evidence makes a real difference to hierarchy, contrast, flow and motion claims that source alone cannot settle.\n55: \n56: - **Use a local dev or static URL for local files.** Avoid `file://` unless the available browser explicitly supports that workflow.\n57: - **Open a fresh tab for each independent pass.** Do not reuse a tab that is already at the right URL, because residual state contaminates the observation.\n58: - **Run any local server in the background, record how to stop it, then stop it before final reporting** unless the user asks to keep it running.\n59: - **Inspect representative views for a multi-view surface,** not just one. Three to five views across the flow catch state-specific defects a single screen hides.\n60: \n61: Browser evidence is rendered evidence. It confirms what the surface does. Pair it with the source when you have both, because the render shows the symptom and the source shows the cause.\n62: \n63: ---\n64: \n65: ## 4. DETERMINISTIC SCANS\n66: \n67: A deterministic scan is a repeatable check that returns the same finding every run: a contrast measurement, a selector match, a token-usage grep, an automated accessibility pass. Deterministic evidence is strong because anyone can rerun it and get the same answer.\n68: \n69: - **Cite the measured value, not an impression.** A contrast finding states the ratio, a touch-target finding states the size. The pass and fail numbers behind these checks live in `accessibility_performance.md`. Do not file a contrast or touch finding on a guess.\n70: - **Reuse a scan result instead of rerunning it.** If a scan has already produced usable counts, rule names and locations, cite those. Rerun only when the prior result was truncated or missing detail.\n71: - **A clean scan is not proof of a strong design.** It proves the absence of the defects the scan checks for, nothing more. Hierarchy, voice, emotional fit and flow still need the judgment lens in `critique_hardening.md`. Pair every clean deterministic pass with that lens before any positive verdict.\n72: - **Anchor judgment first when both run.** Form the design-review read before deterministic counts enter the picture, so the numbers sharpen the judgment rather than replace it.\n73: \n74: ---\n75: \n76: ## 5. SCREENSHOT AND OVERLAY NOTES\n77: \n78: Screenshots and visual overlays are persuasive, which is exactly why they need honest labeling.\n79: \n80: - **A claim about a visual overlay requires that the overlay actually rendered.** Do not say overlays are visible, do not say a detector ran in the page, do not say a scan highlighted issues on screen, unless the injection or the run genuinely succeeded.\n81: - **When a visual pass was attempted but could not run,** say so plainly and report the fallback signal instead of implying a result. A reader who trusts a fabricated overlay ships on false confidence.\n82: - **A finding from a screenshot without the underlying source is inferred,** because a screenshot shows the symptom but not the cause. Label it inferred and state that the source would confirm it.\n83: - **Name the exact element in any visual finding,** the region, the selector or the component. \"The submit button on the checkout step,\" never \"some elements.\"\n84: \n85: ---\n86: \n87: ## 6. FALLBACK LABELS WHEN EVIDENCE IS UNAVAILABLE\n88: \n89: Evidence is often partial. A missing capability is never a reason to invent a result or to inflate confidence. Label the gap and keep going.\n90: \n91: | Situation | Label and behavior |\n92: |---|---|\n93: | Source unavailable, only a screenshot | File the finding as inferred, state that the source would confirm it. |\n94: | Browser or overlay could not run | Report the fallback signal, do not claim a visual result, continue with source and manual review. |\n95: | Deterministic scan unavailable or crashed | Note the scan as unavailable, continue with browser and manual review, do not present a missing scan as a clean pass. |\n96: | Metrics unavailable for a performance claim | File it as a static-risk finding and state the measurement needed to confirm it. |\n97: | A dimension cannot be assessed at all | Mark the dimension not assessed in the score and explain why, rather than scoring it on no evidence. |\n98: \n99: The rule under every row: a confirmed finding is read from real evidence, an inferred finding names what would confirm it, a fabricated finding has no place in an audit at all. A report that names its blind spots is worth more than one that hides them.\n100: \n101: ---\n102: \n103: ## 7. EVIDENCE TO SEVERITY HANDOFF\n104: \n105: Once a finding has evidence and a confirmed-or-inferred label, it carries that into the severity and scoring step in `audit_contract.md`. The handoff rules:\n106: \n107: 1. Severity reflects user impact, not evidence strength. A confirmed P3 stays P3, and a well-grounded P0 is still a P0.\n108: 2. An inferred finding keeps its inferred label all the way into the report. Do not quietly upgrade an inference to a fact between this file and the score.\n109: 3. The findings-first order holds: evidence and findings come before the five-dimension score, never after it.\n\n(End of file - total 109 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Evidence Capture\ndescription: The evidence model for an audit. How to resolve the target, gather browser and deterministic evidence, record screenshot and overlay notes, then label findings honestly when evidence is unavailable.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"evidence capture\"\n  - \"audit evidence model\"\n  - \"resolve audit target\"\n  - \"fallback label evidence\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Evidence Capture\n\nEvery finding rests on evidence, and the quality of an audit is the quality of that evidence. This reference is the evidence model: how to resolve the surface to a stable target, what counts as evidence, then how to label a finding when the evidence you wanted was out of reach. The severity model and the per-finding schema live in `audit_contract.md`. This file is the layer underneath it, the part that decides whether a finding is confirmed or inferred before it ever gets a severity.\n\nThe audit gathers and labels evidence. It does not implement the fix, which is `sk-code` work once the user accepts the recommendation.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md","text":"---\ntitle: Evidence Capture\ndescription: The evidence model for an audit. How to resolve the target, gather browser and deterministic evidence, record screenshot and overlay notes, then label findings honestly when evidence is unavailable.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"evidence capture\"\n  - \"audit evidence model\"\n  - \"resolve audit target\"\n  - \"fallback label evidence\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Evidence Capture\n\nEvery finding rests on evidence, and the quality of an audit is the quality of that evidence. This reference is the evidence model: how to resolve the surface to a stable target, what counts as evidence, then how to label a finding when the evidence you wanted was out of reach. The severity model and the per-finding schema live in `audit_contract.md`. This file is the layer underneath it, the part that decides whether a finding is confirmed or inferred before it ever gets a severity.\n\nThe audit gathers and labels evidence. It does not implement the fix, which is `sk-code` work once the user accepts the recommendation.\n\n---\n\n## 1. RESOLVE THE TARGET\n\nResolve the request to one concrete target before any evidence is gathered. A vague target produces vague findings.\n\n1. **Prefer a source path over a dev-server URL** when both name the same surface. Ports drift and dev servers restart, file paths stay put. Use the URL only when no source path identifies the surface, such as a deployed page you cannot map to a file.\n2. **Map the phrasing to a concrete artifact.**\n   - \"the homepage\" resolves to the page source or the rendered route.\n   - \"the settings modal\" resolves to the primary component file.\n   - \"this page\" resolves to the current URL or the open source file.\n3. **Pass markup to deterministic scans, not CSS-only files.** A stylesheet alone is not a scannable target.\n4. **Narrow a very large tree before scanning.** For a tree of several hundred scannable files, scope to the surface in question or ask which surface to audit. Do not scan the whole repository to review one page.\n\nState the resolved target at the top of the report so the reader knows exactly what was looked at. If the target cannot be resolved to a file, URL, screenshot or concrete design artifact, escalate rather than audit a guess.\n\n---\n\n## 2. THE THREE EVIDENCE TYPES\n\nAn audit draws on three kinds of evidence. Each finding cites at least one, and the type is part of the finding.\n\n| Evidence type | What it is | Strength |\n|---|---|---|\n| Source | The actual file and line, the selector, the declared value | Strongest. A defect read in the code is a confirmed defect. |\n| Rendered | A live page, a screenshot, an observed behavior | Confirms what the surface does, not always why. Pair with source when both exist. |\n| Design-artifact | A plan, a spec, a wireframe with no built surface yet | Weakest for runtime claims. Good for intent, cannot prove behavior. |\n\nSource plus rendered together is the gold standard: the code explains the cause and the render proves the effect. When only one is available, the finding is still valid, but its label in Section 5 must say which one.\n\n---\n\n## 3. BROWSER EVIDENCE\n\nWhen browser automation is available and the target is viewable, rendered evidence makes a real difference to hierarchy, contrast, flow and motion claims that source alone cannot settle.\n\n- **Use a local dev or static URL for local files.** Avoid `file://` unless the available browser explicitly supports that workflow.\n- **Open a fresh tab for each independent pass.** Do not reuse a tab that is already at the right URL, because residual state contaminates the observation.\n- **Run any local server in the background, record how to stop it, then stop it before final reporting** unless the user asks to keep it running.\n- **Inspect representative views for a multi-view surface,** not just one. Three to five views across the flow catch state-specific defects a single screen hides.\n\nBrowser evidence is rendered evidence. It confirms what the surface does. Pair it with the source when you have both, because the render shows the symptom and the source shows the cause.\n\n---\n\n## 4. DETERMINISTIC SCANS\n\nA deterministic scan is a repeatable check that returns the same finding every run: a contrast measurement, a selector match, a token-usage grep, an automated accessibility pass. Deterministic evidence is strong because anyone can rerun it and get the same answer.\n\n- **Cite the measured value, not an impression.** A contrast finding states the ratio, a touch-target finding states the size. The pass and fail numbers behind these checks live in `accessibility_performance.md`. Do not file a contrast or touch finding on a guess.\n- **Reuse a scan result instead of rerunning it.** If a scan has already produced usable counts, rule names and locations, cite those. Rerun only when the prior result was truncated or missing detail.\n- **A clean scan is not proof of a strong design.** It proves the absence of the defects the scan checks for, nothing more. Hierarchy, voice, emotional fit and flow still need the judgment lens in `critique_hardening.md`. Pair every clean deterministic pass with that lens before any positive verdict.\n- **Anchor judgment first when both run.** Form the design-review read before deterministic counts enter the picture, so the numbers sharpen the judgment rather than replace it.\n\n---\n\n## 5. SCREENSHOT AND OVERLAY NOTES\n\nScreenshots and visual overlays are persuasive, which is exactly why they need honest labeling.\n\n- **A claim about a visual overlay requires that the overlay actually rendered.** Do not say overlays are visible, do not say a detector ran in the page, do not say a scan highlighted issues on screen, unless the injection or the run genuinely succeeded.\n- **When a visual pass was attempted but could not run,** say so plainly and report the fallback signal instead of implying a result. A reader who trusts a fabricated overlay ships on false confidence.\n- **A finding from a screenshot without the underlying source is inferred,** because a screenshot shows the symptom but not the cause. Label it inferred and state that the source would confirm it.\n- **Name the exact element in any visual finding,** the region, the selector or the component. \"The submit button on the checkout step,\" never \"some elements.\"\n\n---\n\n## 6. FALLBACK LABELS WHEN EVIDENCE IS UNAVAILABLE\n\nEvidence is often partial. A missing capability is never a reason to invent a result or to inflate confidence. Label the gap and keep going.\n\n| Situation | Label and behavior |\n|---|---|\n| Source unavailable, only a screenshot | File the finding as inferred, state that the source would confirm it. |\n| Browser or overlay could not run | Report the fallback signal, do not claim a visual result, continue with source and manual review. |\n| Deterministic scan unavailable or crashed | Note the scan as unavailable, continue with browser and manual review, do not present a missing scan as a clean pass. |\n| Metrics unavailable for a performance claim | File it as a static-risk finding and state the measurement needed to confirm it. |\n| A dimension cannot be assessed at all | Mark the dimension not assessed in the score and explain why, rather than scoring it on no evidence. |\n\nThe rule under every row: a confirmed finding is read from real evidence, an inferred finding names what would confirm it, a fabricated finding has no place in an audit at all. A report that names its blind spots is worth more than one that hides them.\n\n---\n\n## 7. EVIDENCE TO SEVERITY HANDOFF\n\nOnce a finding has evidence and a confirmed-or-inferred label, it carries that into the severity and scoring step in `audit_contract.md`. The handoff rules:\n\n1. Severity reflects user impact, not evidence strength. A confirmed P3 stays P3, and a well-grounded P0 is still a P0.\n2. An inferred finding keeps its inferred label all the way into the report. Do not quietly upgrade an inference to a fact between this file and the score.\n3. The findings-first order holds: evidence and findings come before the five-dimension score, never after it.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":109,"totalLines":109,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md","time":{"start":1782532340965,"end":1782532340970}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_045fe83177ea1858016a3f48f4d7888191a294fcc1f001a0e8"}},"id":"prt_f0734fce4001On1ZVxQHskV7Xh","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532340986,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_o6kE75ySCfjQvU1vzuFXPQi0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md","offset":1,"limit":1200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Audit Contract\n3: description: P0-P3 severity model, five-dimension /20 scoring contract, findings schema, and evidence rules for design QA.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"audit contract\"\n6:   - \"P0 P1 P2 P3 design\"\n7:   - \"design quality score\"\n8:   - \"five dimension score\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Audit Contract\n15: \n16: This is the output contract for `audit`. It is aligned in spirit with `sk-code-review`: findings first, evidence-backed, severity ordered, and actionable.\n17: \n18: ## 1. Severity\n19: \n20: | Severity | Name | Definition | Examples |\n21: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n22: | P0 | Critical | Prevents task completion, blocks access, or creates severe usability/accessibility failure | keyboard trap in checkout, inaccessible modal, primary action impossible on mobile |\n23: | P1 | High | Significant difficulty, WCAG AA violation, severe responsive failure, systemic drift | unlabeled controls, text contrast fail, touch targets too small across flow |\n24: | P2 | Medium | Annoyance with workaround, localized inconsistency, non-blocking performance issue | one cramped panel, isolated hard-coded color, minor jank |\n25: | P3 | Polish | Low-impact detail that improves craft | optical alignment, copy tightening, subtle spacing refinement |\n26: \n27: If unsure between severities, ask: would a real user fail, contact support, or abandon? If yes, it is at least P1.\n28: \n29: ## 2. Five-Dimension Score\n30: \n31: Score each dimension 0-4.\n32: \n33: | Dimension | 0 | 2 | 4 |\n34: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n35: | Accessibility | inaccessible or blocks assistive use | partial a11y with significant gaps | WCAG AA met, keyboard/focus/names/forms solid |\n36: | Performance | severe load/render/jank issues | some optimization, visible gaps | fast, measured, smooth on target devices |\n37: | Responsive Design | desktop-only or breaks on mobile | works but rough edges | fluid, context-aware, touch targets >=44x44px (24x24px CSS WCAG 2.2 minimum) |\n38: | Theming | hard-coded and no theme support | tokens exist but inconsistent | full semantic token use, dark mode works |\n39: | Anti-Patterns | obvious AI slop/gallery of tells | one or two noticeable tells | distinctive, intentional, no generic tells |\n40: \n41: Rating bands:\n42: - `18-20` Excellent.\n43: - `14-17` Good.\n44: - `10-13` Acceptable.\n45: - `6-9` Poor.\n46: - `0-5` Critical.\n47: \n48: ## 3. Findings Schema\n49: \n50: Use this shape for actionable findings:\n51: \n52: ```markdown\n53: ### P1 - Text contrast fails on primary CTA\n54: - Evidence: `Button` text uses `#8aa0a8` on `#ffffff`; observed contrast below AA target.\n55: - Category: Accessibility / Theming\n56: - Impact: Low-vision users may not read the primary action.\n57: - Recommended fix: Use semantic `text-on-accent` token with AA contrast, or darken foreground via OKLCH lightness.\n58: - Owner: `foundations` for token choice; `sk-code` for implementation.\n59: ```\n60: \n61: ## 4. Evidence Rules\n62: \n63: - Use file/line when code is provided.\n64: - Use rendered observation when a screenshot or live page is available.\n65: - Use prompt/design artifact evidence when reviewing a plan.\n66: - Label any inferred issue as inferred and state what would confirm it.\n67: - Do not claim visual overlays, browser inspection, or automated scans ran unless they actually ran.\n68: \n69: ## 5. Report Order\n70: \n71: 1. Findings by severity.\n72: 2. Audit Health Score table.\n73: 3. Anti-pattern verdict.\n74: 4. What is working.\n75: 5. Recommended next actions by owner.\n76: 6. Evidence limits and residual risks.\n\n(End of file - total 76 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Audit Contract\ndescription: P0-P3 severity model, five-dimension /20 scoring contract, findings schema, and evidence rules for design QA.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"audit contract\"\n  - \"P0 P1 P2 P3 design\"\n  - \"design quality score\"\n  - \"five dimension score\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Audit Contract\n\nThis is the output contract for `audit`. It is aligned in spirit with `sk-code-review`: findings first, evidence-backed, severity ordered, and actionable.\n\n## 1. Severity\n\n| Severity | Name | Definition | Examples |","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md","text":"---\ntitle: Audit Contract\ndescription: P0-P3 severity model, five-dimension /20 scoring contract, findings schema, and evidence rules for design QA.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"audit contract\"\n  - \"P0 P1 P2 P3 design\"\n  - \"design quality score\"\n  - \"five dimension score\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Audit Contract\n\nThis is the output contract for `audit`. It is aligned in spirit with `sk-code-review`: findings first, evidence-backed, severity ordered, and actionable.\n\n## 1. Severity\n\n| Severity | Name | Definition | Examples |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| P0 | Critical | Prevents task completion, blocks access, or creates severe usability/accessibility failure | keyboard trap in checkout, inaccessible modal, primary action impossible on mobile |\n| P1 | High | Significant difficulty, WCAG AA violation, severe responsive failure, systemic drift | unlabeled controls, text contrast fail, touch targets too small across flow |\n| P2 | Medium | Annoyance with workaround, localized inconsistency, non-blocking performance issue | one cramped panel, isolated hard-coded color, minor jank |\n| P3 | Polish | Low-impact detail that improves craft | optical alignment, copy tightening, subtle spacing refinement |\n\nIf unsure between severities, ask: would a real user fail, contact support, or abandon? If yes, it is at least P1.\n\n## 2. Five-Dimension Score\n\nScore each dimension 0-4.\n\n| Dimension | 0 | 2 | 4 |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Accessibility | inaccessible or blocks assistive use | partial a11y with significant gaps | WCAG AA met, keyboard/focus/names/forms solid |\n| Performance | severe load/render/jank issues | some optimization, visible gaps | fast, measured, smooth on target devices |\n| Responsive Design | desktop-only or breaks on mobile | works but rough edges | fluid, context-aware, touch targets >=44x44px (24x24px CSS WCAG 2.2 minimum) |\n| Theming | hard-coded and no theme support | tokens exist but inconsistent | full semantic token use, dark mode works |\n| Anti-Patterns | obvious AI slop/gallery of tells | one or two noticeable tells | distinctive, intentional, no generic tells |\n\nRating bands:\n- `18-20` Excellent.\n- `14-17` Good.\n- `10-13` Acceptable.\n- `6-9` Poor.\n- `0-5` Critical.\n\n## 3. Findings Schema\n\nUse this shape for actionable findings:\n\n```markdown\n### P1 - Text contrast fails on primary CTA\n- Evidence: `Button` text uses `#8aa0a8` on `#ffffff`; observed contrast below AA target.\n- Category: Accessibility / Theming\n- Impact: Low-vision users may not read the primary action.\n- Recommended fix: Use semantic `text-on-accent` token with AA contrast, or darken foreground via OKLCH lightness.\n- Owner: `foundations` for token choice; `sk-code` for implementation.\n```\n\n## 4. Evidence Rules\n\n- Use file/line when code is provided.\n- Use rendered observation when a screenshot or live page is available.\n- Use prompt/design artifact evidence when reviewing a plan.\n- Label any inferred issue as inferred and state what would confirm it.\n- Do not claim visual overlays, browser inspection, or automated scans ran unless they actually ran.\n\n## 5. Report Order\n\n1. Findings by severity.\n2. Audit Health Score table.\n3. Anti-pattern verdict.\n4. What is working.\n5. Recommended next actions by owner.\n6. Evidence limits and residual risks.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":76,"totalLines":76,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md","time":{"start":1782532340963,"end":1782532340983}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_045fe83177ea1858016a3f48f4d7808191b12b7f3310a19439"}},"id":"prt_f0734fcc6001Zq7fg43kWgj1uD","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532340986,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_AfZmIvDHPsOsw8VYnXeHoQGM","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/transform_remediation.md","offset":1,"limit":1200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/transform_remediation.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Transform Remediation\n3: description: Maps directional transform verbs bolder, quieter, distill and redesign to findings, the owner mode and the accepted remediation path. Register-gated.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"transform remediation\"\n6:   - \"bolder quieter distill audit\"\n7:   - \"directional remediation path\"\n8:   - \"which transform verb\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Transform Remediation\n15: \n16: When an audit finds a surface that is bland, loud, cluttered or generic, the fix has a direction. This reference maps four directional verbs to the findings that call for them, the mode that owns the work and the remediation path. The audit names the direction and routes it. It does not perform the transform, which is `interface` or `foundations` work, with implementation by `sk-code` after the user accepts the recommendation.\n17: \n18: This file is register-gated. Which direction is correct depends on the Brand-vs-Product posture, so resolve the register first: `../../shared/register.md`. A loud Brand hero and a loud Product dashboard get opposite verdicts from the same observation. Severity and the findings schema come from `audit_contract.md`. The general anti-slop signals are in `anti_patterns_production.md`, and the model-specific tells are in `ai_fingerprint_tells.md`.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. THE FOUR VERBS\n23: \n24: | Verb | The problem it fixes | One-line direction |\n25: |---|---|---|\n26: | bolder | Too safe, bland, flat hierarchy, generic choices | Increase impact through stronger hierarchy and committed choices, not more effects |\n27: | quieter | Too loud, overstimulating, competing weight, motion excess | Reduce intensity with precision, keep the point of view intact |\n28: | distill | Cluttered, redundant, too many elements and choices | Strip to essence, remove what does not earn its place |\n29: | redesign | Generic across the board, multiple tells, a default look | Upgrade an existing surface to premium without breaking it |\n30: \n31: bolder, quieter and distill are single-axis moves on one surface. redesign is the broad upgrade pass that runs when the surface is generic in several dimensions at once and a single verb is not enough.\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 2. REGISTER GATE\n36: \n37: The same observation routes to a different verb depending on posture. Read the register before assigning a remediation.\n38: \n39: | Observation | Brand verdict | Product verdict |\n40: |---|---|---|\n41: | Surface feels flat and safe | bolder, toward distinctiveness: committed scale, unexpected color, typographic risk | bolder, toward clarity only: stronger hierarchy, sharper single accent, more committed density. No theatrics, they undercut trust |\n42: | Surface feels loud and busy | quieter, but the point of view survives the cuts: drama reduced, not eliminated | quieter, toward disappearing into the task: fewer background accents, flatter cards, less color, less motion |\n43: | Surface feels cluttered | distill, toward one big move with room to breathe | distill, toward density that still reads: one primary action, progressive disclosure for the rest |\n44: | Surface feels generic everywhere | redesign, weighted to voice and a signature moment | redesign, weighted to affordance, consistency and accessibility |\n45: \n46: The audit-severity dial follows from this. On a Brand surface a generic-but-functional result is a real finding, so bland scores against Anti-Patterns. On a Product surface an expressive-but-unclear result is a real finding, so theatrics score against Accessibility and consistency. A verdict that ignores the register will push a dashboard toward marketing drama or flatten a campaign into a tool.\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## 3. FINDING TO VERB MAP\n51: \n52: Map the observed finding to a verb, then to the owner mode and the accepted path. None of these are implementation steps. They are the direction the owner mode will take.\n53: \n54: ### 3.1 Bland signals to bolder\n55: \n56: Signals: system fonts, everything medium-sized with no drama, uniform visual weight, no focal point, predictable standard patterns.\n57: \n58: - Verb: bolder.\n59: - Owner: `interface` for the focal moment and overall direction, `foundations` for the type scale, weight contrast and color strategy.\n60: - Accepted path: pick one hero moment, widen the size and weight contrast, commit the color strategy a step up the commitment axis. The trap to avoid is the AI idea of bold: gradient text, glassmorphism, neon on dark, hero-metric templates. Those are the opposite of bold and are themselves findings.\n61: \n62: ### 3.2 Loud signals to quieter\n63: \n64: Signals: oversaturated color, high-contrast everywhere, too many heavy elements competing, motion excess, no hierarchy because everything shouts.\n65: \n66: - Verb: quieter.\n67: - Owner: `foundations` for desaturation, neutral dominance and weight reduction, `motion` for cutting decorative animation.\n68: - Accepted path: reduce saturation, let neutrals carry more, raise contrast only where it matters, replace dramatic motion with gentle feedback. The trap is collapsing to grayscale or killing all character. Quiet is precision, not absence.\n69: \n70: ### 3.3 Cluttered signals to distill\n71: \n72: Signals: competing buttons, repeated information, too many colors and fonts and sizes, everything visible at once, unclear hierarchy, feature creep.\n73: \n74: - Verb: distill.\n75: - Owner: `interface` for the information architecture and the single primary goal, `foundations` for cutting the palette and type variants.\n76: - Accepted path: find the one primary goal, hide complexity behind progressive disclosure, merge related actions, reduce to one primary action with the rest tertiary or hidden. The trap is removing necessary function or making the surface so sparse it turns unclear. Distill removes obstacles, not features.\n77: \n78: ### 3.4 Generic-everywhere signals to redesign\n79: \n80: Signals: default or Inter-everywhere type, pure-black backgrounds, oversaturated or multiple accents, the purple-blue AI gradient, three equal feature cards, generic card look of border plus shadow plus white, no hover or active states, missing empty and error states.\n81: \n82: - Verb: redesign.\n83: - Owner: `interface` leads the upgrade direction, `foundations` carries type, color, layout and state tokens, `sk-code` implements without breaking the stack.\n84: - Accepted path: scan the existing stack, diagnose every generic pattern and missing state, then apply targeted upgrades that work with the current framework rather than a rewrite. Order the work for impact over risk: type first, then palette cleanup, then states, then layout and spacing, then component swaps, then the missing empty and error states.\n85: \n86: ---\n87: \n88: ## 4. CONTENT-REALISM AND MECHANICAL-LAYOUT CHECKS\n89: \n90: Two recurring generic signals have their own authored gates on the interface side. Do not re-document them here. Reference the interface gate and report the review-side finding.\n91: \n92: - Content realism. Placeholder names like John Doe, round fake numbers, Acme-style company names, Lorem Ipsum, identical avatars and dates, AI copy cliches are a generic-content signal. The authored gate is `../../design-interface/references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md`. When the audit finds unrealistic mock content, file the finding against Anti-Patterns and route remediation through that gate, owned by `interface` for the content direction.\n93: \n94: - Mechanical layout. Everything centered and symmetrical, three equal columns as the feature row, uniform card grids, identical vertical padding top and bottom, snap-to-grid placement with no rhythm are a mechanical-default signal. The authored gate is `../../design-interface/references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md`. When the audit finds mechanical layout, file the finding against Anti-Patterns or Responsive as fits, and route remediation through that gate, owned by `foundations` for spacing and layout tokens and `interface` for the composition call.\n95: \n96: These two checks are the review-side view of the interface authoring gates. The audit reports the defect and points at the gate. The interface and foundations modes own the actual transform.\n97: \n98: ---\n99: \n100: ## 5. ROUTING SUMMARY\n101: \n102: 1. Resolve the register before assigning any verb.\n103: 2. Match the finding to one verb, or step up to redesign when several findings stack.\n104: 3. Name the owner mode: interface for direction, foundations for tokens, motion for choreography.\n105: 4. State the accepted path as a direction, not an implementation.\n106: 5. Hand implementation to `sk-code` only after the user accepts the recommendation.\n107: \n108: The audit chooses and routes the direction. It does not turn the dial.\n\n(End of file - total 108 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Transform Remediation\ndescription: Maps directional transform verbs bolder, quieter, distill and redesign to findings, the owner mode and the accepted remediation path. Register-gated.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"transform remediation\"\n  - \"bolder quieter distill audit\"\n  - \"directional remediation path\"\n  - \"which transform verb\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Transform Remediation\n\nWhen an audit finds a surface that is bland, loud, cluttered or generic, the fix has a direction. This reference maps four directional verbs to the findings that call for them, the mode that owns the work and the remediation path. The audit names the direction and routes it. It does not perform the transform, which is `interface` or `foundations` work, with implementation by `sk-code` after the user accepts the recommendation.\n\nThis file is register-gated. Which direction is correct depends on the Brand-vs-Product posture, so resolve the register first: `../../shared/register.md`. A loud Brand hero and a loud Product dashboard get opposite verdicts from the same observation. Severity and the findings schema come from `audit_contract.md`. The general anti-slop signals are in `anti_patterns_production.md`, and the model-specific tells are in `ai_fingerprint_tells.md`.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/transform_remediation.md","text":"---\ntitle: Transform Remediation\ndescription: Maps directional transform verbs bolder, quieter, distill and redesign to findings, the owner mode and the accepted remediation path. Register-gated.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"transform remediation\"\n  - \"bolder quieter distill audit\"\n  - \"directional remediation path\"\n  - \"which transform verb\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Transform Remediation\n\nWhen an audit finds a surface that is bland, loud, cluttered or generic, the fix has a direction. This reference maps four directional verbs to the findings that call for them, the mode that owns the work and the remediation path. The audit names the direction and routes it. It does not perform the transform, which is `interface` or `foundations` work, with implementation by `sk-code` after the user accepts the recommendation.\n\nThis file is register-gated. Which direction is correct depends on the Brand-vs-Product posture, so resolve the register first: `../../shared/register.md`. A loud Brand hero and a loud Product dashboard get opposite verdicts from the same observation. Severity and the findings schema come from `audit_contract.md`. The general anti-slop signals are in `anti_patterns_production.md`, and the model-specific tells are in `ai_fingerprint_tells.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. THE FOUR VERBS\n\n| Verb | The problem it fixes | One-line direction |\n|---|---|---|\n| bolder | Too safe, bland, flat hierarchy, generic choices | Increase impact through stronger hierarchy and committed choices, not more effects |\n| quieter | Too loud, overstimulating, competing weight, motion excess | Reduce intensity with precision, keep the point of view intact |\n| distill | Cluttered, redundant, too many elements and choices | Strip to essence, remove what does not earn its place |\n| redesign | Generic across the board, multiple tells, a default look | Upgrade an existing surface to premium without breaking it |\n\nbolder, quieter and distill are single-axis moves on one surface. redesign is the broad upgrade pass that runs when the surface is generic in several dimensions at once and a single verb is not enough.\n\n---\n\n## 2. REGISTER GATE\n\nThe same observation routes to a different verb depending on posture. Read the register before assigning a remediation.\n\n| Observation | Brand verdict | Product verdict |\n|---|---|---|\n| Surface feels flat and safe | bolder, toward distinctiveness: committed scale, unexpected color, typographic risk | bolder, toward clarity only: stronger hierarchy, sharper single accent, more committed density. No theatrics, they undercut trust |\n| Surface feels loud and busy | quieter, but the point of view survives the cuts: drama reduced, not eliminated | quieter, toward disappearing into the task: fewer background accents, flatter cards, less color, less motion |\n| Surface feels cluttered | distill, toward one big move with room to breathe | distill, toward density that still reads: one primary action, progressive disclosure for the rest |\n| Surface feels generic everywhere | redesign, weighted to voice and a signature moment | redesign, weighted to affordance, consistency and accessibility |\n\nThe audit-severity dial follows from this. On a Brand surface a generic-but-functional result is a real finding, so bland scores against Anti-Patterns. On a Product surface an expressive-but-unclear result is a real finding, so theatrics score against Accessibility and consistency. A verdict that ignores the register will push a dashboard toward marketing drama or flatten a campaign into a tool.\n\n---\n\n## 3. FINDING TO VERB MAP\n\nMap the observed finding to a verb, then to the owner mode and the accepted path. None of these are implementation steps. They are the direction the owner mode will take.\n\n### 3.1 Bland signals to bolder\n\nSignals: system fonts, everything medium-sized with no drama, uniform visual weight, no focal point, predictable standard patterns.\n\n- Verb: bolder.\n- Owner: `interface` for the focal moment and overall direction, `foundations` for the type scale, weight contrast and color strategy.\n- Accepted path: pick one hero moment, widen the size and weight contrast, commit the color strategy a step up the commitment axis. The trap to avoid is the AI idea of bold: gradient text, glassmorphism, neon on dark, hero-metric templates. Those are the opposite of bold and are themselves findings.\n\n### 3.2 Loud signals to quieter\n\nSignals: oversaturated color, high-contrast everywhere, too many heavy elements competing, motion excess, no hierarchy because everything shouts.\n\n- Verb: quieter.\n- Owner: `foundations` for desaturation, neutral dominance and weight reduction, `motion` for cutting decorative animation.\n- Accepted path: reduce saturation, let neutrals carry more, raise contrast only where it matters, replace dramatic motion with gentle feedback. The trap is collapsing to grayscale or killing all character. Quiet is precision, not absence.\n\n### 3.3 Cluttered signals to distill\n\nSignals: competing buttons, repeated information, too many colors and fonts and sizes, everything visible at once, unclear hierarchy, feature creep.\n\n- Verb: distill.\n- Owner: `interface` for the information architecture and the single primary goal, `foundations` for cutting the palette and type variants.\n- Accepted path: find the one primary goal, hide complexity behind progressive disclosure, merge related actions, reduce to one primary action with the rest tertiary or hidden. The trap is removing necessary function or making the surface so sparse it turns unclear. Distill removes obstacles, not features.\n\n### 3.4 Generic-everywhere signals to redesign\n\nSignals: default or Inter-everywhere type, pure-black backgrounds, oversaturated or multiple accents, the purple-blue AI gradient, three equal feature cards, generic card look of border plus shadow plus white, no hover or active states, missing empty and error states.\n\n- Verb: redesign.\n- Owner: `interface` leads the upgrade direction, `foundations` carries type, color, layout and state tokens, `sk-code` implements without breaking the stack.\n- Accepted path: scan the existing stack, diagnose every generic pattern and missing state, then apply targeted upgrades that work with the current framework rather than a rewrite. Order the work for impact over risk: type first, then palette cleanup, then states, then layout and spacing, then component swaps, then the missing empty and error states.\n\n---\n\n## 4. CONTENT-REALISM AND MECHANICAL-LAYOUT CHECKS\n\nTwo recurring generic signals have their own authored gates on the interface side. Do not re-document them here. Reference the interface gate and report the review-side finding.\n\n- Content realism. Placeholder names like John Doe, round fake numbers, Acme-style company names, Lorem Ipsum, identical avatars and dates, AI copy cliches are a generic-content signal. The authored gate is `../../design-interface/references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md`. When the audit finds unrealistic mock content, file the finding against Anti-Patterns and route remediation through that gate, owned by `interface` for the content direction.\n\n- Mechanical layout. Everything centered and symmetrical, three equal columns as the feature row, uniform card grids, identical vertical padding top and bottom, snap-to-grid placement with no rhythm are a mechanical-default signal. The authored gate is `../../design-interface/references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md`. When the audit finds mechanical layout, file the finding against Anti-Patterns or Responsive as fits, and route remediation through that gate, owned by `foundations` for spacing and layout tokens and `interface` for the composition call.\n\nThese two checks are the review-side view of the interface authoring gates. The audit reports the defect and points at the gate. The interface and foundations modes own the actual transform.\n\n---\n\n## 5. ROUTING SUMMARY\n\n1. Resolve the register before assigning any verb.\n2. Match the finding to one verb, or step up to redesign when several findings stack.\n3. Name the owner mode: interface for direction, foundations for tokens, motion for choreography.\n4. State the accepted path as a direction, not an implementation.\n5. Hand implementation to `sk-code` only after the user accepts the recommendation.\n\nThe audit chooses and routes the direction. It does not turn the dial.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":108,"totalLines":108,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/transform_remediation.md","time":{"start":1782532340967,"end":1782532340985}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_045fe83177ea1858016a3f48f4d790819196e775e431d445eb"}},"id":"prt_f0734fce600131l996pgAdI8m4","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532341010,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_imsm1uxF251hD4IXu4mNnEET","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md","offset":1,"limit":1200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Audit Report Template\n3: description: Fill-in audit report skeleton. Findings-first, with a five-dimension score out of 20, an AI-default verdict, P0-P3 issues, owner mapping and evidence caveats.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"audit report template\"\n6:   - \"design audit report\"\n7:   - \"fill in audit report\"\n8:   - \"design quality report skeleton\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Audit Report Template\n15: \n16: Copy this skeleton and fill it in for one audited surface. Findings come first, the score is a summary of the findings, and the deliverable stops at reporting. The audit names what is wrong and who owns the fix. It does not implement the fix, which belongs to `sk-code` after the user accepts the recommendations. Severity and scoring rules live in `../references/audit_contract.md`. Resolve the surface register before scoring so dimension weighting is correct: `../../shared/assets/register_card.md`.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. SET THE FRAME\n21: \n22: Fill this before any finding so the reader knows what was looked at and what was not.\n23: \n24: | Field | Answer |\n25: |---|---|\n26: | Surface audited (page / route / file) | `__________` |\n27: | Register (Brand or Product) | [ ] Brand (design IS the product) [ ] Product (design SERVES the product) |\n28: | Evidence available | [ ] source code [ ] rendered page [ ] screenshot [ ] design plan only |\n29: | Evidence missing | `__________` (state what could not be checked) |\n30: | Audit date | `__________` |\n31: \n32: Register sets the audit-severity weighting. Brand weights distinctiveness and voice, so a generic-but-functional surface is a real finding. Product weights affordance, accessibility and consistency, so an expressive-but-unclear surface is a real finding.\n33: \n34: ---\n35: \n36: ## 2. ANTI-PATTERNS VERDICT\n37: \n38: Start here, because it is the question the rest of the report answers. Be blunt.\n39: \n40: | Question | Answer |\n41: |---|---|\n42: | Could someone say \"AI made that\" with no doubt? | [ ] yes (fail) [ ] borderline [ ] no (pass) |\n43: | Tell count | `____` tells |\n44: | Named tells observed | `__________` |\n45: \n46: Map tells to findings using `../references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md`. A clean verdict here is not proof of a strong design, only proof of no obvious tells. Distinctiveness, hierarchy and flow still need judgment.\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## 3. FINDINGS BY SEVERITY\n51: \n52: List findings before the score. Order P0, then P1, then P2, then P3. Use the findings schema from `../references/audit_contract.md`. One finding per issue. Do not bury a P0 under polish.\n53: \n54: ### P0 Critical\n55: \n56: ```markdown\n57: ### P0 - <short title>\n58: - Evidence: <file/line, rendered observation, design-artifact note>\n59: - Category: <Accessibility / Performance / Responsive / Theming / Anti-Patterns>\n60: - Impact: <how a real user fails, is blocked or abandons>\n61: - Recommended fix: <the change, not the implementation>\n62: - Owner: <foundations / motion / interface / sk-code>\n63: ```\n64: \n65: ### P1 High\n66: \n67: ```markdown\n68: ### P1 - <short title>\n69: - Evidence: <...>\n70: - Category: <...>\n71: - Impact: <...>\n72: - Recommended fix: <...>\n73: - Owner: <...>\n74: ```\n75: \n76: ### P2 Medium\n77: \n78: ```markdown\n79: ### P2 - <short title>\n80: - Evidence: <...>\n81: - Category: <...>\n82: - Impact: <...>\n83: - Recommended fix: <...>\n84: - Owner: <...>\n85: ```\n86: \n87: ### P3 Polish\n88: \n89: ```markdown\n90: ### P3 - <short title>\n91: - Evidence: <...>\n92: - Category: <...>\n93: - Impact: <...>\n94: - Recommended fix: <...>\n95: - Owner: <...>\n96: ```\n97: \n98: If a finding rests on an inference rather than direct observation, label it inferred and state what would confirm it. Do not claim a browser scan, overlay or detector ran unless it actually ran.\n99: \n100: ---\n101: \n102: ## 4. POSITIVE FINDINGS\n103: \n104: Name what works so the team knows what to keep. Two to four items is enough.\n105: \n106: - `__________`\n107: - `__________`\n108: - `__________`\n109: \n110: ---\n111: \n112: ## 5. FIVE-DIMENSION SCORE\n113: \n114: Score each dimension 0 to 4 from the findings above. The score summarizes the findings, it does not replace them. Full rubric is in `../references/audit_contract.md`.\n115: \n116: | # | Dimension | Score (0-4) | Key finding |\n117: |---|---|---|---|\n118: | 1 | Accessibility | `__` | `__________` |\n119: | 2 | Performance | `__` | `__________` |\n120: | 3 | Responsive Design | `__` | `__________` |\n121: | 4 | Theming | `__` | `__________` |\n122: | 5 | Anti-Patterns | `__` | `__________` |\n123: | | **Total** | **`__`/20** | **`__________`** (rating band) |\n124: \n125: Rating bands: `18-20` Excellent, `14-17` Good, `10-13` Acceptable, `6-9` Poor, `0-5` Critical. Do not score generously to soften the report. A 4 means genuinely excellent.\n126: \n127: ---\n128: \n129: ## 6. OWNER MAPPING\n130: \n131: Group the findings by who owns the fix. The audit routes work, it does not do the work.\n132: \n133: | Owner | What they own | Findings routed here |\n134: |---|---|---|\n135: | `interface` | Overall direction, signature visual concept | `__________` |\n136: | `foundations` | Color, type, spacing, layout, responsive, theming tokens | `__________` |\n137: | `motion` | Choreography, micro-interactions, reduced motion | `__________` |\n138: | `sk-code` | Implementation of every accepted fix | `__________` |\n139: \n140: Direction findings go to interface. Color, type, layout and theming findings go to foundations. Motion findings go to motion. All implementation goes to sk-code once the user accepts the recommendations. For directional remediation verbs (bolder, quieter, distill), route through `../references/transform_remediation.md` first, because the correct direction depends on the register.\n141: \n142: ---\n143: \n144: ## 7. RECOMMENDED NEXT ACTIONS\n145: \n146: List the actions in priority order, P0 first. Each action names one owner and one concrete next step.\n147: \n148: 1. `__________`\n149: 2. `__________`\n150: 3. `__________`\n151: \n152: ---\n153: \n154: ## 8. EVIDENCE LIMITS AND RESIDUAL RISK\n155: \n156: Close honestly. State what the audit could not verify and what would close the gap.\n157: \n158: - Could not verify: `__________`\n159: - Would confirm with: `__________`\n160: - Residual risk if shipped as-is: `__________`\n161: \n162: A report that hides its blind spots is worse than a report that names them.\n\n(End of file - total 162 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Audit Report Template\ndescription: Fill-in audit report skeleton. Findings-first, with a five-dimension score out of 20, an AI-default verdict, P0-P3 issues, owner mapping and evidence caveats.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"audit report template\"\n  - \"design audit report\"\n  - \"fill in audit report\"\n  - \"design quality report skeleton\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Audit Report Template\n\nCopy this skeleton and fill it in for one audited surface. Findings come first, the score is a summary of the findings, and the deliverable stops at reporting. The audit names what is wrong and who owns the fix. It does not implement the fix, which belongs to `sk-code` after the user accepts the recommendations. Severity and scoring rules live in `../references/audit_contract.md`. Resolve the surface register before scoring so dimension weighting is correct: `../../shared/assets/register_card.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. SET THE FRAME","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md","text":"---\ntitle: Audit Report Template\ndescription: Fill-in audit report skeleton. Findings-first, with a five-dimension score out of 20, an AI-default verdict, P0-P3 issues, owner mapping and evidence caveats.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"audit report template\"\n  - \"design audit report\"\n  - \"fill in audit report\"\n  - \"design quality report skeleton\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Audit Report Template\n\nCopy this skeleton and fill it in for one audited surface. Findings come first, the score is a summary of the findings, and the deliverable stops at reporting. The audit names what is wrong and who owns the fix. It does not implement the fix, which belongs to `sk-code` after the user accepts the recommendations. Severity and scoring rules live in `../references/audit_contract.md`. Resolve the surface register before scoring so dimension weighting is correct: `../../shared/assets/register_card.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. SET THE FRAME\n\nFill this before any finding so the reader knows what was looked at and what was not.\n\n| Field | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Surface audited (page / route / file) | `__________` |\n| Register (Brand or Product) | [ ] Brand (design IS the product) [ ] Product (design SERVES the product) |\n| Evidence available | [ ] source code [ ] rendered page [ ] screenshot [ ] design plan only |\n| Evidence missing | `__________` (state what could not be checked) |\n| Audit date | `__________` |\n\nRegister sets the audit-severity weighting. Brand weights distinctiveness and voice, so a generic-but-functional surface is a real finding. Product weights affordance, accessibility and consistency, so an expressive-but-unclear surface is a real finding.\n\n---\n\n## 2. ANTI-PATTERNS VERDICT\n\nStart here, because it is the question the rest of the report answers. Be blunt.\n\n| Question | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Could someone say \"AI made that\" with no doubt? | [ ] yes (fail) [ ] borderline [ ] no (pass) |\n| Tell count | `____` tells |\n| Named tells observed | `__________` |\n\nMap tells to findings using `../references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md`. A clean verdict here is not proof of a strong design, only proof of no obvious tells. Distinctiveness, hierarchy and flow still need judgment.\n\n---\n\n## 3. FINDINGS BY SEVERITY\n\nList findings before the score. Order P0, then P1, then P2, then P3. Use the findings schema from `../references/audit_contract.md`. One finding per issue. Do not bury a P0 under polish.\n\n### P0 Critical\n\n```markdown\n### P0 - <short title>\n- Evidence: <file/line, rendered observation, design-artifact note>\n- Category: <Accessibility / Performance / Responsive / Theming / Anti-Patterns>\n- Impact: <how a real user fails, is blocked or abandons>\n- Recommended fix: <the change, not the implementation>\n- Owner: <foundations / motion / interface / sk-code>\n```\n\n### P1 High\n\n```markdown\n### P1 - <short title>\n- Evidence: <...>\n- Category: <...>\n- Impact: <...>\n- Recommended fix: <...>\n- Owner: <...>\n```\n\n### P2 Medium\n\n```markdown\n### P2 - <short title>\n- Evidence: <...>\n- Category: <...>\n- Impact: <...>\n- Recommended fix: <...>\n- Owner: <...>\n```\n\n### P3 Polish\n\n```markdown\n### P3 - <short title>\n- Evidence: <...>\n- Category: <...>\n- Impact: <...>\n- Recommended fix: <...>\n- Owner: <...>\n```\n\nIf a finding rests on an inference rather than direct observation, label it inferred and state what would confirm it. Do not claim a browser scan, overlay or detector ran unless it actually ran.\n\n---\n\n## 4. POSITIVE FINDINGS\n\nName what works so the team knows what to keep. Two to four items is enough.\n\n- `__________`\n- `__________`\n- `__________`\n\n---\n\n## 5. FIVE-DIMENSION SCORE\n\nScore each dimension 0 to 4 from the findings above. The score summarizes the findings, it does not replace them. Full rubric is in `../references/audit_contract.md`.\n\n| # | Dimension | Score (0-4) | Key finding |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Accessibility | `__` | `__________` |\n| 2 | Performance | `__` | `__________` |\n| 3 | Responsive Design | `__` | `__________` |\n| 4 | Theming | `__` | `__________` |\n| 5 | Anti-Patterns | `__` | `__________` |\n| | **Total** | **`__`/20** | **`__________`** (rating band) |\n\nRating bands: `18-20` Excellent, `14-17` Good, `10-13` Acceptable, `6-9` Poor, `0-5` Critical. Do not score generously to soften the report. A 4 means genuinely excellent.\n\n---\n\n## 6. OWNER MAPPING\n\nGroup the findings by who owns the fix. The audit routes work, it does not do the work.\n\n| Owner | What they own | Findings routed here |\n|---|---|---|\n| `interface` | Overall direction, signature visual concept | `__________` |\n| `foundations` | Color, type, spacing, layout, responsive, theming tokens | `__________` |\n| `motion` | Choreography, micro-interactions, reduced motion | `__________` |\n| `sk-code` | Implementation of every accepted fix | `__________` |\n\nDirection findings go to interface. Color, type, layout and theming findings go to foundations. Motion findings go to motion. All implementation goes to sk-code once the user accepts the recommendations. For directional remediation verbs (bolder, quieter, distill), route through `../references/transform_remediation.md` first, because the correct direction depends on the register.\n\n---\n\n## 7. RECOMMENDED NEXT ACTIONS\n\nList the actions in priority order, P0 first. Each action names one owner and one concrete next step.\n\n1. `__________`\n2. `__________`\n3. `__________`\n\n---\n\n## 8. EVIDENCE LIMITS AND RESIDUAL RISK\n\nClose honestly. State what the audit could not verify and what would close the gap.\n\n- Could not verify: `__________`\n- Would confirm with: `__________`\n- Residual risk if shipped as-is: `__________`\n\nA report that hides its blind spots is worse than a report that names them.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":162,"totalLines":162,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md","time":{"start":1782532341006,"end":1782532341009}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_045fe83177ea1858016a3f48f4d7988191865d4c73d02c2acd"}},"id":"prt_f0734fce70012zFqv5g3fjKlDV","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532341028,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_PQG3d0aMejHGASclwaZ8ypIx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md","offset":1,"limit":1200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Accessibility Quick Fixes\n3: description: Snippet-level accessibility fixes the audit report cites by reference. Accessible names, keyboard, focus and dialogs, semantics, forms and errors, live-region announcements, contrast and motion.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"accessibility quick fixes\"\n6:   - \"a11y snippet fixes\"\n7:   - \"accessible name fix\"\n8:   - \"focus trap fix snippet\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Accessibility Quick Fixes\n15: \n16: This is a fix-reference card, not a workflow. When the audit files an accessibility finding, it points the owner here for the concrete shape of the fix, then `sk-code` makes the change once the user accepts it. The audit cites these snippets, it does not apply them. The priority order, the user-impact framing, plus the contrast and touch numbers all live in `../references/accessibility_performance.md`. This card is the snippet layer underneath that reference: the smallest correct change for each common defect.\n17: \n18: Two rules hold across every fix below. Prefer native HTML before adding ARIA, because a real `button` beats a div wearing a role. And keep the change minimal, because an accessibility fix is a targeted repair, not a license to refactor the surrounding component.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. ACCESSIBLE NAMES\n23: \n24: Every interactive control needs a name a screen reader can announce.\n25: \n26: | Defect | Fix |\n27: |---|---|\n28: | Icon-only button with no name | Add `aria-label`, hide the glyph with `aria-hidden=\"true\"` |\n29: | Input, select or textarea with no label | Associate a `<label for>`, or use `aria-label` when no visible label fits |\n30: | Link text that says \"click here\" or \"read more\" | Rewrite to name the destination |\n31: | Decorative icon announced as content | Add `aria-hidden=\"true\"` |\n32: \n33: ```html\n34: <button aria-label=\"Close\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\">...</svg></button>\n35: ```\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 2. KEYBOARD ACCESS\n40: \n41: Every action reachable by mouse must be reachable by keyboard.\n42: \n43: | Defect | Fix |\n44: |---|---|\n45: | `div` or `span` wired as a button | Use a native `button`, which brings focus and key handling for free |\n46: | Control not reachable by Tab | Make it a native interactive element or give it the correct role and tabindex of 0 |\n47: | `tabindex` greater than 0 | Remove it, fix the source order instead |\n48: | Overlay that traps the user | Make Escape close it |\n49: \n50: ```html\n51: <!-- before --> <div onclick=\"save()\">Save</div>\n52: <!-- after -->  <button type=\"button\" onclick=\"save()\">Save</button>\n53: ```\n54: \n55: ---\n56: \n57: ## 3. FOCUS AND DIALOGS\n58: \n59: A dialog that mismanages focus strands keyboard and screen-reader users.\n60: \n61: | Defect | Fix |\n62: |---|---|\n63: | Focus escapes an open modal | Trap focus inside the dialog while it is open |\n64: | Focus lost when a dialog closes | Restore focus to the trigger that opened it |\n65: | Dialog opens with focus nowhere useful | Set initial focus to the first control or the heading |\n66: | Page jumps when a dialog opens | Open without an unexpected scroll |\n67: \n68: ```html\n69: <div role=\"dialog\" aria-modal=\"true\" aria-labelledby=\"dlg-title\">\n70:   <h2 id=\"dlg-title\">Confirm</h2>\n71:   <!-- trap focus here, restore to trigger on close -->\n72: </div>\n73: ```\n74: \n75: ---\n76: \n77: ## 4. SEMANTICS\n78: \n79: Native semantics carry meaning that role hacks have to rebuild by hand.\n80: \n81: | Defect | Fix |\n82: |---|---|\n83: | Role-based widget where a native element exists | Use the native element first |\n84: | A role with its required attributes missing | Add the attributes the role demands, or drop the role |\n85: | List markup built from divs | Use `ul` or `ol` with `li` |\n86: | Heading levels skipped | Keep the heading order unbroken |\n87: | Data table without header cells | Use `th` for headers, with `scope` when needed |\n88: \n89: ---\n90: \n91: ## 5. FORMS AND ERRORS\n92: \n93: Form errors must reach the field, the screen reader and the user at the same moment.\n94: \n95: | Defect | Fix |\n96: |---|---|\n97: | Error text not linked to its field | Link it with `aria-describedby` |\n98: | Invalid field not flagged to assistive tech | Set `aria-invalid=\"true\"` on the field |\n99: | Required field not announced | Mark it required, not by color alone |\n100: | Helper text floating loose | Associate it with the input by id |\n101: | Disabled submit with no reason | Explain why the action is unavailable |\n102: \n103: ```html\n104: <input id=\"email\" aria-describedby=\"email-err\" aria-invalid=\"true\" />\n105: <span id=\"email-err\">Email addresses need an @ symbol.</span>\n106: ```\n107: \n108: ---\n109: \n110: ## 6. LIVE-REGION ANNOUNCEMENTS\n111: \n112: A change a sighted user sees must also be a change a screen-reader user hears.\n113: \n114: | Defect | Fix |\n115: |---|---|\n116: | Critical form error shown visually only | Place it in an `aria-live` region |\n117: | Loading state silent to assistive tech | Use `aria-busy` or status text |\n118: | Toast is the only channel for critical information | Add a persistent, non-toast path as well |\n119: | Expand and collapse state not announced | Add `aria-expanded` and `aria-controls` to the trigger |\n120: \n121: ```html\n122: <div aria-live=\"polite\" role=\"status\">Saving your changes...</div>\n123: ```\n124: \n125: ---\n126: \n127: ## 7. CONTRAST AND STATES\n128: \n129: Meaning must survive low vision, and it must not depend on color alone. The pass and fail ratios and the touch-target size live in `../references/accessibility_performance.md`. Measure against those numbers, do not eyeball a contrast fix.\n130: \n131: | Defect | Fix |\n132: |---|---|\n133: | Text or icon below the contrast floor | Raise the foreground or lower the background to meet the ratio in the reference |\n134: | Hover-only interaction with no keyboard path | Give the same affordance a focus and keyboard equivalent |\n135: | Disabled or status state shown by color alone | Add a label, an icon or text alongside the color |\n136: | Focus outline removed | Replace it with a visible focus style, never remove without a replacement |\n137: \n138: ---\n139: \n140: ## 8. MOTION\n141: \n142: Non-essential motion must yield to a user who has asked for less of it.\n143: \n144: | Defect | Fix |\n145: |---|---|\n146: | Non-essential animation ignores the user preference | Honor `prefers-reduced-motion` |\n147: | Media autoplays with sound | Remove autoplay, or start muted with a control |\n148: | Speech video with no captions | Provide captions when the speech carries meaning |\n149: \n150: ```css\n151: @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n152:   * {\n153:     animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n154:     transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n155:   }\n156: }\n157: ```\n158: \n159: ---\n160: \n161: ## 9. HOW THE REPORT USES THIS CARD\n162: \n163: 1. The audit files the accessibility finding with its evidence and severity from `../references/audit_contract.md`.\n164: 2. The finding points at the matching section here for the fix shape.\n165: 3. The owner is `foundations` for a token-level fix such as contrast, otherwise `sk-code` for the markup change.\n166: 4. The audit stops at naming the fix. Applying it is `sk-code` work after the user accepts the recommendation.\n\n(End of file - total 166 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Accessibility Quick Fixes\ndescription: Snippet-level accessibility fixes the audit report cites by reference. Accessible names, keyboard, focus and dialogs, semantics, forms and errors, live-region announcements, contrast and motion.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"accessibility quick fixes\"\n  - \"a11y snippet fixes\"\n  - \"accessible name fix\"\n  - \"focus trap fix snippet\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Accessibility Quick Fixes\n\nThis is a fix-reference card, not a workflow. When the audit files an accessibility finding, it points the owner here for the concrete shape of the fix, then `sk-code` makes the change once the user accepts it. The audit cites these snippets, it does not apply them. The priority order, the user-impact framing, plus the contrast and touch numbers all live in `../references/accessibility_performance.md`. This card is the snippet layer underneath that reference: the smallest correct change for each common defect.\n\nTwo rules hold across every fix below. Prefer native HTML before adding ARIA, because a real `button` beats a div wearing a role. And keep the change minimal, because an accessibility fix is a targeted repair, not a license to refactor the surrounding component.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md","text":"---\ntitle: Accessibility Quick Fixes\ndescription: Snippet-level accessibility fixes the audit report cites by reference. Accessible names, keyboard, focus and dialogs, semantics, forms and errors, live-region announcements, contrast and motion.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"accessibility quick fixes\"\n  - \"a11y snippet fixes\"\n  - \"accessible name fix\"\n  - \"focus trap fix snippet\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Accessibility Quick Fixes\n\nThis is a fix-reference card, not a workflow. When the audit files an accessibility finding, it points the owner here for the concrete shape of the fix, then `sk-code` makes the change once the user accepts it. The audit cites these snippets, it does not apply them. The priority order, the user-impact framing, plus the contrast and touch numbers all live in `../references/accessibility_performance.md`. This card is the snippet layer underneath that reference: the smallest correct change for each common defect.\n\nTwo rules hold across every fix below. Prefer native HTML before adding ARIA, because a real `button` beats a div wearing a role. And keep the change minimal, because an accessibility fix is a targeted repair, not a license to refactor the surrounding component.\n\n---\n\n## 1. ACCESSIBLE NAMES\n\nEvery interactive control needs a name a screen reader can announce.\n\n| Defect | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| Icon-only button with no name | Add `aria-label`, hide the glyph with `aria-hidden=\"true\"` |\n| Input, select or textarea with no label | Associate a `<label for>`, or use `aria-label` when no visible label fits |\n| Link text that says \"click here\" or \"read more\" | Rewrite to name the destination |\n| Decorative icon announced as content | Add `aria-hidden=\"true\"` |\n\n```html\n<button aria-label=\"Close\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\">...</svg></button>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. KEYBOARD ACCESS\n\nEvery action reachable by mouse must be reachable by keyboard.\n\n| Defect | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| `div` or `span` wired as a button | Use a native `button`, which brings focus and key handling for free |\n| Control not reachable by Tab | Make it a native interactive element or give it the correct role and tabindex of 0 |\n| `tabindex` greater than 0 | Remove it, fix the source order instead |\n| Overlay that traps the user | Make Escape close it |\n\n```html\n<!-- before --> <div onclick=\"save()\">Save</div>\n<!-- after -->  <button type=\"button\" onclick=\"save()\">Save</button>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. FOCUS AND DIALOGS\n\nA dialog that mismanages focus strands keyboard and screen-reader users.\n\n| Defect | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| Focus escapes an open modal | Trap focus inside the dialog while it is open |\n| Focus lost when a dialog closes | Restore focus to the trigger that opened it |\n| Dialog opens with focus nowhere useful | Set initial focus to the first control or the heading |\n| Page jumps when a dialog opens | Open without an unexpected scroll |\n\n```html\n<div role=\"dialog\" aria-modal=\"true\" aria-labelledby=\"dlg-title\">\n  <h2 id=\"dlg-title\">Confirm</h2>\n  <!-- trap focus here, restore to trigger on close -->\n</div>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. SEMANTICS\n\nNative semantics carry meaning that role hacks have to rebuild by hand.\n\n| Defect | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| Role-based widget where a native element exists | Use the native element first |\n| A role with its required attributes missing | Add the attributes the role demands, or drop the role |\n| List markup built from divs | Use `ul` or `ol` with `li` |\n| Heading levels skipped | Keep the heading order unbroken |\n| Data table without header cells | Use `th` for headers, with `scope` when needed |\n\n---\n\n## 5. FORMS AND ERRORS\n\nForm errors must reach the field, the screen reader and the user at the same moment.\n\n| Defect | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| Error text not linked to its field | Link it with `aria-describedby` |\n| Invalid field not flagged to assistive tech | Set `aria-invalid=\"true\"` on the field |\n| Required field not announced | Mark it required, not by color alone |\n| Helper text floating loose | Associate it with the input by id |\n| Disabled submit with no reason | Explain why the action is unavailable |\n\n```html\n<input id=\"email\" aria-describedby=\"email-err\" aria-invalid=\"true\" />\n<span id=\"email-err\">Email addresses need an @ symbol.</span>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. LIVE-REGION ANNOUNCEMENTS\n\nA change a sighted user sees must also be a change a screen-reader user hears.\n\n| Defect | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| Critical form error shown visually only | Place it in an `aria-live` region |\n| Loading state silent to assistive tech | Use `aria-busy` or status text |\n| Toast is the only channel for critical information | Add a persistent, non-toast path as well |\n| Expand and collapse state not announced | Add `aria-expanded` and `aria-controls` to the trigger |\n\n```html\n<div aria-live=\"polite\" role=\"status\">Saving your changes...</div>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. CONTRAST AND STATES\n\nMeaning must survive low vision, and it must not depend on color alone. The pass and fail ratios and the touch-target size live in `../references/accessibility_performance.md`. Measure against those numbers, do not eyeball a contrast fix.\n\n| Defect | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| Text or icon below the contrast floor | Raise the foreground or lower the background to meet the ratio in the reference |\n| Hover-only interaction with no keyboard path | Give the same affordance a focus and keyboard equivalent |\n| Disabled or status state shown by color alone | Add a label, an icon or text alongside the color |\n| Focus outline removed | Replace it with a visible focus style, never remove without a replacement |\n\n---\n\n## 8. MOTION\n\nNon-essential motion must yield to a user who has asked for less of it.\n\n| Defect | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| Non-essential animation ignores the user preference | Honor `prefers-reduced-motion` |\n| Media autoplays with sound | Remove autoplay, or start muted with a control |\n| Speech video with no captions | Provide captions when the speech carries meaning |\n\n```css\n@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n  * {\n    animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n    transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. HOW THE REPORT USES THIS CARD\n\n1. The audit files the accessibility finding with its evidence and severity from `../references/audit_contract.md`.\n2. The finding points at the matching section here for the fix shape.\n3. The owner is `foundations` for a token-level fix such as contrast, otherwise `sk-code` for the markup change.\n4. The audit stops at naming the fix. Applying it is `sk-code` work after the user accepts the recommendation.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":166,"totalLines":166,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md","time":{"start":1782532341022,"end":1782532341025}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_045fe83177ea1858016a3f48f4d79c8191a55ee65207d1d839"}},"id":"prt_f0734fd1b001NZjStnuLckTB1h","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532341031,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_XvcAIPwyh955VGeS45cC8HID","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md","offset":1,"limit":1000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"audit: Manual Testing Playbook\"\n3: description: \"Lean manual scenarios for verifying design audit scoring, accessibility/performance review, and anti-slop hardening behavior.\"\n4: version: 1.0.0.3\n5: ---\n6: \n7: # audit: Manual Testing Playbook\n8: \n9: > **EXECUTION POLICY**: Run scenarios against the live skill and on-disk references. Acceptable verdicts are PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP with a concrete blocker.\n10: \n11: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n12: \n13: | ID | Scenario | Intent | File |\n14: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n15: | AUDIT-SCORE-001 | Findings-first `/20` audit report | AUDIT_CONTRACT | [`01--score/002-findings-first-score.md`](01--score/002-findings-first-score.md) |\n16: | AUDIT-SCORE-002 | Transform remediation routing | TRANSFORM_REMEDIATION | [`01--score/003-transform-remediation-routing.md`](01--score/003-transform-remediation-routing.md) |\n17: | AUDIT-SCORE-003 | Evidence capture and labeling | EVIDENCE_CAPTURE | [`01--score/004-evidence-capture.md`](01--score/004-evidence-capture.md) |\n18: | AUDIT-SCORE-004 | Audit report template fill-in | AUDIT_CONTRACT | [`01--score/005-audit-report-template.md`](01--score/005-audit-report-template.md) |\n19: | AUDIT-A11Y-001 | Accessibility and performance gate | ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE | [`02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md`](02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md) |\n20: | AUDIT-A11Y-002 | Accessibility quick-fix references | ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE | [`02--a11y-performance/007-a11y-quick-fixes.md`](02--a11y-performance/007-a11y-quick-fixes.md) |\n21: | AUDIT-SLOP-001 | Anti-slop and production hardening | ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION | [`03--slop-hardening/008-anti-slop-production-hardening.md`](03--slop-hardening/008-anti-slop-production-hardening.md) |\n22: | AUDIT-SLOP-002 | AI fingerprint tell detection | ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION | [`03--slop-hardening/001-ai-fingerprint-tells.md`](03--slop-hardening/001-ai-fingerprint-tells.md) |\n23: | AUDIT-SLOP-003 | Hardening edge-case matrix | CRITIQUE_HARDENING | [`03--slop-hardening/009-hardening-edge-cases.md`](03--slop-hardening/009-hardening-edge-cases.md) |\n24: \n25: ## 2. GLOBAL PRECONDITIONS\n26: \n27: 1. The repository root is the working directory.\n28: 2. `SKILL.md` and all `references/` files under `audit` resolve.\n29: 3. Each scenario names its own `<TARGET>` slot. Supply one concrete artifact per scenario: a source file path, a rendered URL, a screenshot, or a design plan.\n30: \n31: ## 2a. SKIP RULE\n32: \n33: A scenario is SKIP only when no concrete `<TARGET>` artifact can be supplied for it. Record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\" rather than inventing UI, rendered, or measured evidence. A scenario with a supplied target may not be skipped.\n34: \n35: ## 3. EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS\n36: \n37: - Exact prompt used.\n38: - Target artifact and evidence available.\n39: - Resources loaded.\n40: - Findings, score, owner mapping, caveats, and final verdict.\n41: \n42: ## 4. RELEASE READINESS\n43: \n44: Release is ready when all scenarios PASS or are SKIP only under the SKIP RULE (no target artifact supplied), and no scenario omits severity, score, evidence, or owner mapping.\n\n(End of file - total 44 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"audit: Manual Testing Playbook\"\ndescription: \"Lean manual scenarios for verifying design audit scoring, accessibility/performance review, and anti-slop hardening behavior.\"\nversion: 1.0.0.3\n---\n\n# audit: Manual Testing Playbook\n\n> **EXECUTION POLICY**: Run scenarios against the live skill and on-disk references. Acceptable verdicts are PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP with a concrete blocker.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n| ID | Scenario | Intent | File |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| AUDIT-SCORE-001 | Findings-first `/20` audit report | AUDIT_CONTRACT | [`01--score/002-findings-first-score.md`](01--score/002-findings-first-score.md) |\n| AUDIT-SCORE-002 | Transform remediation routing | TRANSFORM_REMEDIATION | [`01--score/003-transform-remediation-routing.md`](01--score/003-transform-remediation-routing.md) |\n| AUDIT-SCORE-003 | Evidence capture and labeling | EVIDENCE_CAPTURE | [`01--score/004-evidence-capture.md`](01--score/004-evidence-capture.md) |\n| AUDIT-SCORE-004 | Audit report template fill-in | AUDIT_CONTRACT | [`01--score/005-audit-report-template.md`](01--score/005-audit-report-template.md) |\n| AUDIT-A11Y-001 | Accessibility and performance gate | ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE | [`02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md`](02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md) |\n| AUDIT-A11Y-002 | Accessibility quick-fix references | ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE | [`02--a11y-performance/007-a11y-quick-fixes.md`](02--a11y-performance/007-a11y-quick-fixes.md) |","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"audit: Manual Testing Playbook\"\ndescription: \"Lean manual scenarios for verifying design audit scoring, accessibility/performance review, and anti-slop hardening behavior.\"\nversion: 1.0.0.3\n---\n\n# audit: Manual Testing Playbook\n\n> **EXECUTION POLICY**: Run scenarios against the live skill and on-disk references. Acceptable verdicts are PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP with a concrete blocker.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n| ID | Scenario | Intent | File |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| AUDIT-SCORE-001 | Findings-first `/20` audit report | AUDIT_CONTRACT | [`01--score/002-findings-first-score.md`](01--score/002-findings-first-score.md) |\n| AUDIT-SCORE-002 | Transform remediation routing | TRANSFORM_REMEDIATION | [`01--score/003-transform-remediation-routing.md`](01--score/003-transform-remediation-routing.md) |\n| AUDIT-SCORE-003 | Evidence capture and labeling | EVIDENCE_CAPTURE | [`01--score/004-evidence-capture.md`](01--score/004-evidence-capture.md) |\n| AUDIT-SCORE-004 | Audit report template fill-in | AUDIT_CONTRACT | [`01--score/005-audit-report-template.md`](01--score/005-audit-report-template.md) |\n| AUDIT-A11Y-001 | Accessibility and performance gate | ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE | [`02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md`](02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md) |\n| AUDIT-A11Y-002 | Accessibility quick-fix references | ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE | [`02--a11y-performance/007-a11y-quick-fixes.md`](02--a11y-performance/007-a11y-quick-fixes.md) |\n| AUDIT-SLOP-001 | Anti-slop and production hardening | ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION | [`03--slop-hardening/008-anti-slop-production-hardening.md`](03--slop-hardening/008-anti-slop-production-hardening.md) |\n| AUDIT-SLOP-002 | AI fingerprint tell detection | ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION | [`03--slop-hardening/001-ai-fingerprint-tells.md`](03--slop-hardening/001-ai-fingerprint-tells.md) |\n| AUDIT-SLOP-003 | Hardening edge-case matrix | CRITIQUE_HARDENING | [`03--slop-hardening/009-hardening-edge-cases.md`](03--slop-hardening/009-hardening-edge-cases.md) |\n\n## 2. GLOBAL PRECONDITIONS\n\n1. The repository root is the working directory.\n2. `SKILL.md` and all `references/` files under `audit` resolve.\n3. Each scenario names its own `<TARGET>` slot. Supply one concrete artifact per scenario: a source file path, a rendered URL, a screenshot, or a design plan.\n\n## 2a. SKIP RULE\n\nA scenario is SKIP only when no concrete `<TARGET>` artifact can be supplied for it. Record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\" rather than inventing UI, rendered, or measured evidence. A scenario with a supplied target may not be skipped.\n\n## 3. EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Exact prompt used.\n- Target artifact and evidence available.\n- Resources loaded.\n- Findings, score, owner mapping, caveats, and final verdict.\n\n## 4. RELEASE READINESS\n\nRelease is ready when all scenarios PASS or are SKIP only under the SKIP RULE (no target artifact supplied), and no scenario omits severity, score, evidence, or owner mapping.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":44,"totalLines":44,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md","time":{"start":1782532341027,"end":1782532341030}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_045fe83177ea1858016a3f48f4d7a481918d166eaadec2cea7"}},"id":"prt_f0734fd22001dAVWGvcY1xKb68","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782532341417,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f0734fea7001cCZVpz9Yxp519S","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"ab87b191cf288cd2cf6e378b1a7cd773ba95a6e3","messageID":"msg_f07347f58001i3Ru23T3XaBp9I","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":116778,"input":750,"output":523,"reasoning":305,"cache":{"write":0,"read":115200}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782532343986,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f073508b1001ZGk7PZAZnVJmVG","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","snapshot":"ab87b191cf288cd2cf6e378b1a7cd773ba95a6e3","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532362941,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_xpcs9XeJHA6PQHiMJ3VRimu8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/accessibility_performance.md","offset":1,"limit":1400},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/accessibility_performance.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Accessibility And Performance\n3: description: Accessibility, WCAG, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms, motion performance, rendering, loading, and measurement checks.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"accessibility performance\"\n6:   - \"WCAG audit\"\n7:   - \"keyboard focus audit\"\n8:   - \"motion performance audit\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Accessibility And Performance\n15: \n16: Accessibility and performance are release gates. A beautiful UI that blocks keyboard users or janks on target devices is not ready.\n17: \n18: ## 1. Accessibility Priority Order\n19: \n20: | Priority | Category | Checks |\n21: | --- | --- | --- |\n22: | 1 | Accessible names | interactive controls named; icon buttons use `aria-label`; decorative icons hidden |\n23: | 2 | Keyboard access | all controls reachable; visible focus; no `tabindex > 0`; Escape closes overlays |\n24: | 3 | Focus and dialogs | trap focus in modals; restore focus to trigger; initial focus placed intentionally |\n25: | 4 | Semantics | native elements first; headings not skipped; tables use headers; lists use lists |\n26: | 5 | Forms and errors | labels, `aria-describedby`, `aria-invalid`, required indicators, helpful errors |\n27: | 6 | Announcements | loading/status/errors use live regions or status text where needed |\n28: | 7 | Contrast and states | text/icon contrast, focus contrast, no color-only meaning |\n29: | 8 | Media and motion | alt text, captions when relevant, reduced motion, no sound autoplay |\n30: \n31: Prefer native HTML before adding ARIA. Do not add ARIA to compensate for avoidable custom controls.\n32: \n33: ### Concrete Thresholds (verify, do not eyeball)\n34: \n35: These are the pass/fail numbers behind the contrast and touch checks. Cite a measured ratio or size in the finding; do not file a contrast or touch P0-P3 on a guess.\n36: \n37: | Check | WCAG AA (floor) | WCAG AAA |\n38: | --- | --- | --- |\n39: | Body text contrast | 4.5:1 | 7:1 |\n40: | Large text contrast (>=18.66px bold, or >=24px) | 3:1 | 4.5:1 |\n41: | UI components and graphical affordances (icons, focus ring, control borders) | 3:1 | n/a |\n42: | Touch target size | 44x44px (24x24px CSS is the WCAG 2.2 minimum) | n/a |\n43: \n44: ## 2. Accessibility Findings\n45: \n46: For each issue, report:\n47: - Exact element or snippet.\n48: - Why it matters to users.\n49: - Minimal fix.\n50: - Severity based on user impact.\n51: \n52: Common fixes:\n53: \n54: ```html\n55: <button aria-label=\"Close\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\">...</svg></button>\n56: <input id=\"email\" aria-describedby=\"email-error\" aria-invalid=\"true\" />\n57: <span id=\"email-error\">Email addresses need an @ symbol.</span>\n58: ```\n59: \n60: ## 3. Performance Checks\n61: \n62: Measure before and after when possible.\n63: \n64: | Area | Checks |\n65: | --- | --- |\n66: | Core Web Vitals | LCP under 2.5s, INP under 200ms, CLS under 0.1 when applicable |\n67: | Loading | image formats/sizes, lazy loading, code splitting, font display, critical resources |\n68: | Rendering | layout thrashing, DOM size, containment, content visibility, virtualized long lists |\n69: | Motion | transform/opacity default, bounded paint, no continuous layout animation |\n70: | Network | request count, payload size, caching, compression, slow-connection behavior |\n71: \n72: ## 4. Motion Performance\n73: \n74: Critical failures:\n75: - Interleaved layout reads and writes.\n76: - Scroll event polling for animation.\n77: - Endless `requestAnimationFrame` loops.\n78: - Large continuous blur/filter animation.\n79: - `will-change` applied broadly or permanently.\n80: - Mixing animation libraries inside one interaction surface.\n81: \n82: Recommended fixes:\n83: - Use FLIP for layout-like motion.\n84: - Use IntersectionObserver for visibility and pausing.\n85: - Scope paint-heavy effects to small surfaces.\n86: - Pause off-screen loops.\n87: - Downgrade technique before deleting useful state feedback.\n88: \n89: ## 5. Performance Evidence\n90: \n91: Use real metrics when available. If metrics are unavailable, label findings as static-risk findings and state the measurement needed to confirm.\n\n(End of file - total 91 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Accessibility And Performance\ndescription: Accessibility, WCAG, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms, motion performance, rendering, loading, and measurement checks.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"accessibility performance\"\n  - \"WCAG audit\"\n  - \"keyboard focus audit\"\n  - \"motion performance audit\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Accessibility And Performance\n\nAccessibility and performance are release gates. A beautiful UI that blocks keyboard users or janks on target devices is not ready.\n\n## 1. Accessibility Priority Order\n\n| Priority | Category | Checks |","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/accessibility_performance.md","text":"---\ntitle: Accessibility And Performance\ndescription: Accessibility, WCAG, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms, motion performance, rendering, loading, and measurement checks.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"accessibility performance\"\n  - \"WCAG audit\"\n  - \"keyboard focus audit\"\n  - \"motion performance audit\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Accessibility And Performance\n\nAccessibility and performance are release gates. A beautiful UI that blocks keyboard users or janks on target devices is not ready.\n\n## 1. Accessibility Priority Order\n\n| Priority | Category | Checks |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 1 | Accessible names | interactive controls named; icon buttons use `aria-label`; decorative icons hidden |\n| 2 | Keyboard access | all controls reachable; visible focus; no `tabindex > 0`; Escape closes overlays |\n| 3 | Focus and dialogs | trap focus in modals; restore focus to trigger; initial focus placed intentionally |\n| 4 | Semantics | native elements first; headings not skipped; tables use headers; lists use lists |\n| 5 | Forms and errors | labels, `aria-describedby`, `aria-invalid`, required indicators, helpful errors |\n| 6 | Announcements | loading/status/errors use live regions or status text where needed |\n| 7 | Contrast and states | text/icon contrast, focus contrast, no color-only meaning |\n| 8 | Media and motion | alt text, captions when relevant, reduced motion, no sound autoplay |\n\nPrefer native HTML before adding ARIA. Do not add ARIA to compensate for avoidable custom controls.\n\n### Concrete Thresholds (verify, do not eyeball)\n\nThese are the pass/fail numbers behind the contrast and touch checks. Cite a measured ratio or size in the finding; do not file a contrast or touch P0-P3 on a guess.\n\n| Check | WCAG AA (floor) | WCAG AAA |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Body text contrast | 4.5:1 | 7:1 |\n| Large text contrast (>=18.66px bold, or >=24px) | 3:1 | 4.5:1 |\n| UI components and graphical affordances (icons, focus ring, control borders) | 3:1 | n/a |\n| Touch target size | 44x44px (24x24px CSS is the WCAG 2.2 minimum) | n/a |\n\n## 2. Accessibility Findings\n\nFor each issue, report:\n- Exact element or snippet.\n- Why it matters to users.\n- Minimal fix.\n- Severity based on user impact.\n\nCommon fixes:\n\n```html\n<button aria-label=\"Close\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\">...</svg></button>\n<input id=\"email\" aria-describedby=\"email-error\" aria-invalid=\"true\" />\n<span id=\"email-error\">Email addresses need an @ symbol.</span>\n```\n\n## 3. Performance Checks\n\nMeasure before and after when possible.\n\n| Area | Checks |\n| --- | --- |\n| Core Web Vitals | LCP under 2.5s, INP under 200ms, CLS under 0.1 when applicable |\n| Loading | image formats/sizes, lazy loading, code splitting, font display, critical resources |\n| Rendering | layout thrashing, DOM size, containment, content visibility, virtualized long lists |\n| Motion | transform/opacity default, bounded paint, no continuous layout animation |\n| Network | request count, payload size, caching, compression, slow-connection behavior |\n\n## 4. Motion Performance\n\nCritical failures:\n- Interleaved layout reads and writes.\n- Scroll event polling for animation.\n- Endless `requestAnimationFrame` loops.\n- Large continuous blur/filter animation.\n- `will-change` applied broadly or permanently.\n- Mixing animation libraries inside one interaction surface.\n\nRecommended fixes:\n- Use FLIP for layout-like motion.\n- Use IntersectionObserver for visibility and pausing.\n- Scope paint-heavy effects to small surfaces.\n- Pause off-screen loops.\n- Downgrade technique before deleting useful state feedback.\n\n## 5. Performance Evidence\n\nUse real metrics when available. If metrics are unavailable, label findings as static-risk findings and state the measurement needed to confirm.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":91,"totalLines":91,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/accessibility_performance.md","time":{"start":1782532362935,"end":1782532362940}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0df4b7570568c22b016a3f490adcf4819183576e14cff938d2"}},"id":"prt_f0735528b001HTEHBZtz0tEjRZ","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532362972,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_X0TVYKMkZw5PapmFYRFcgof5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/critique_hardening.md","offset":1,"limit":1400},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/critique_hardening.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Critique And Hardening\n3: description: Holistic critique, cognitive load, Nielsen heuristics, personas, polish, edge cases, i18n, errors, empty/loading states, and resilience checks.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"design critique\"\n6:   - \"cognitive load\"\n7:   - \"Nielsen heuristics\"\n8:   - \"production hardening\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Critique And Hardening\n15: \n16: Use this reference when the task is broader than a technical scan: does the interface make sense, feel intentional, survive real data, and help the right users succeed?\n17: \n18: ## 1. Critique Workflow\n19: \n20: 1. Resolve the target to a concrete source path, URL, screenshot, or design plan.\n21: 2. Review the design holistically before reading deterministic findings if both are available.\n22: 3. Evaluate AI slop, hierarchy, information architecture, emotional fit, states, copy, accessibility, and edge cases.\n23: 4. Synthesize; do not concatenate independent notes.\n24: \n25: ## 2. Cognitive Load\n26: \n27: Check:\n28: - Single focus: one primary task visible.\n29: - Chunking: groups of four or fewer where possible.\n30: - Grouping: related items visually close or in a common region.\n31: - Visual hierarchy: primary, secondary, and supporting content are clear.\n32: - One decision at a time.\n33: - Minimal visible choices.\n34: - No memory bridge across screens.\n35: - Progressive disclosure where complexity is not immediately needed.\n36: \n37: Map failures to severity on a two-band scale: 2-3 failures = P2 (address soon); 4 or more failures = P1 (high cognitive load).\n38: \n39: ## 3. Nielsen Heuristic Lens\n40: \n41: Walk the 10 heuristics as a checklist; for each clear violation, file a P0-P3 finding with evidence. Do not assign per-heuristic numeric scores.\n42: 1. Visibility of system status.\n43: 2. Match between system and real world.\n44: 3. User control and freedom.\n45: 4. Consistency and standards.\n46: 5. Error prevention.\n47: 6. Recognition rather than recall.\n48: 7. Flexibility and efficiency.\n49: 8. Aesthetic and minimalist design.\n50: 9. Error recovery.\n51: 10. Help and documentation.\n52: \n53: The Nielsen lens is a diagnostic to surface findings; it is NOT separately totaled. Each heuristic violation becomes a P0-P3 finding feeding the relevant /20 dimension (mostly Accessibility, Responsive, or Anti-Patterns). There is no /40 score in this skill.\n54: \n55: ## 4. Persona Checks\n56: \n57: Select two or three relevant personas:\n58: - Power user: shortcuts, batch work, no forced hand-holding.\n59: - First-timer: clear first action, labels, help, no unexplained jargon.\n60: - Accessibility-dependent user: keyboard, screen reader, focus, contrast.\n61: - Stress tester: edge inputs, refresh, long data, errors.\n62: - Distracted mobile user: thumb reach, interruptions, slow connection, tap targets.\n63: \n64: Report red flags tied to actual elements, not generic persona descriptions.\n65: \n66: ## 5. Hardening Checks\n67: \n68: Real interfaces need hostile data tests:\n69: - Very long/short text.\n70: - Empty states and no results.\n71: - 1000+ items and pagination or virtualization.\n72: - Emoji, accents, CJK, RTL.\n73: - German or Finnish text expansion.\n74: - Offline, timeout, 401/403/404/429/500.\n75: - Concurrent submissions and double-clicks.\n76: - Permission states and read-only mode.\n77: \n78: ## 6. Polish Checks\n79: \n80: Polish starts with design-system discovery. For drift, name the root cause:\n81: - Missing token.\n82: - One-off implementation.\n83: - Conceptual misalignment.\n84: \n85: Then check spacing, optical alignment, typography, states, copy, icons, forms, edge cases, responsiveness, performance, and code cleanliness.\n86: \n87: ## 7. Evidence Limits\n88: \n89: A clean detector result is not proof of a strong design. Browser/rendered evidence and human judgment still matter for hierarchy, emotional fit, slop, and flow shape.\n\n(End of file - total 89 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Critique And Hardening\ndescription: Holistic critique, cognitive load, Nielsen heuristics, personas, polish, edge cases, i18n, errors, empty/loading states, and resilience checks.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"design critique\"\n  - \"cognitive load\"\n  - \"Nielsen heuristics\"\n  - \"production hardening\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Critique And Hardening\n\nUse this reference when the task is broader than a technical scan: does the interface make sense, feel intentional, survive real data, and help the right users succeed?\n\n## 1. Critique Workflow\n\n1. Resolve the target to a concrete source path, URL, screenshot, or design plan.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/critique_hardening.md","text":"---\ntitle: Critique And Hardening\ndescription: Holistic critique, cognitive load, Nielsen heuristics, personas, polish, edge cases, i18n, errors, empty/loading states, and resilience checks.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"design critique\"\n  - \"cognitive load\"\n  - \"Nielsen heuristics\"\n  - \"production hardening\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Critique And Hardening\n\nUse this reference when the task is broader than a technical scan: does the interface make sense, feel intentional, survive real data, and help the right users succeed?\n\n## 1. Critique Workflow\n\n1. Resolve the target to a concrete source path, URL, screenshot, or design plan.\n2. Review the design holistically before reading deterministic findings if both are available.\n3. Evaluate AI slop, hierarchy, information architecture, emotional fit, states, copy, accessibility, and edge cases.\n4. Synthesize; do not concatenate independent notes.\n\n## 2. Cognitive Load\n\nCheck:\n- Single focus: one primary task visible.\n- Chunking: groups of four or fewer where possible.\n- Grouping: related items visually close or in a common region.\n- Visual hierarchy: primary, secondary, and supporting content are clear.\n- One decision at a time.\n- Minimal visible choices.\n- No memory bridge across screens.\n- Progressive disclosure where complexity is not immediately needed.\n\nMap failures to severity on a two-band scale: 2-3 failures = P2 (address soon); 4 or more failures = P1 (high cognitive load).\n\n## 3. Nielsen Heuristic Lens\n\nWalk the 10 heuristics as a checklist; for each clear violation, file a P0-P3 finding with evidence. Do not assign per-heuristic numeric scores.\n1. Visibility of system status.\n2. Match between system and real world.\n3. User control and freedom.\n4. Consistency and standards.\n5. Error prevention.\n6. Recognition rather than recall.\n7. Flexibility and efficiency.\n8. Aesthetic and minimalist design.\n9. Error recovery.\n10. Help and documentation.\n\nThe Nielsen lens is a diagnostic to surface findings; it is NOT separately totaled. Each heuristic violation becomes a P0-P3 finding feeding the relevant /20 dimension (mostly Accessibility, Responsive, or Anti-Patterns). There is no /40 score in this skill.\n\n## 4. Persona Checks\n\nSelect two or three relevant personas:\n- Power user: shortcuts, batch work, no forced hand-holding.\n- First-timer: clear first action, labels, help, no unexplained jargon.\n- Accessibility-dependent user: keyboard, screen reader, focus, contrast.\n- Stress tester: edge inputs, refresh, long data, errors.\n- Distracted mobile user: thumb reach, interruptions, slow connection, tap targets.\n\nReport red flags tied to actual elements, not generic persona descriptions.\n\n## 5. Hardening Checks\n\nReal interfaces need hostile data tests:\n- Very long/short text.\n- Empty states and no results.\n- 1000+ items and pagination or virtualization.\n- Emoji, accents, CJK, RTL.\n- German or Finnish text expansion.\n- Offline, timeout, 401/403/404/429/500.\n- Concurrent submissions and double-clicks.\n- Permission states and read-only mode.\n\n## 6. Polish Checks\n\nPolish starts with design-system discovery. For drift, name the root cause:\n- Missing token.\n- One-off implementation.\n- Conceptual misalignment.\n\nThen check spacing, optical alignment, typography, states, copy, icons, forms, edge cases, responsiveness, performance, and code cleanliness.\n\n## 7. Evidence Limits\n\nA clean detector result is not proof of a strong design. Browser/rendered evidence and human judgment still matter for hierarchy, emotional fit, slop, and flow shape.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":89,"totalLines":89,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/critique_hardening.md","time":{"start":1782532362954,"end":1782532362970}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0df4b7570568c22b016a3f490add0881919f86e44ff1fc065f"}},"id":"prt_f073552c5001jdMVI70S0RxHzw","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532362974,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_RAsqH5sXvDLRAXMk4GIX0aVv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti_patterns_production.md","offset":1,"limit":1400},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti_patterns_production.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Anti-Patterns And Production Details\n3: description: Anti-slop detection, theming drift, token misuse, copy clarity, pseudo-elements, View Transitions, and production-readiness details.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"anti-pattern detection\"\n6:   - \"AI slop audit\"\n7:   - \"theming drift\"\n8:   - \"pseudo-element audit\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Anti-Patterns And Production Details\n15: \n16: This reference catches details that make a UI look generic, fragile, or production-unready.\n17: \n18: ## 1. Anti-Slop Signals\n19: \n20: Use parent `sk-design/references/anti_slop_principles.md` as the shared vocabulary. Common findings:\n21: - Generic cream + serif + terracotta with no subject reason.\n22: - Near-black + one acid accent as the whole identity.\n23: - Hairline broadsheet layout with no editorial premise.\n24: - Repeated glass, blur, glow, mesh gradients, or hero metrics.\n25: - Uniform card grids everywhere.\n26: - Decorative `01 / 02 / 03` labels without sequence.\n27: - Scattered motion instead of one choreographed moment.\n28: \n29: ## 2. Theming And Tokens\n30: \n31: Report:\n32: - Hard-coded colors where semantic tokens exist.\n33: - Dark mode variants missing or failing contrast.\n34: - Primitive tokens used directly in components instead of semantic tokens.\n35: - One-off spacing, radius, shadow, or z-index values.\n36: - Theme switching that leaves stale colors or surfaces.\n37: \n38: Map token fixes to `foundations` and implementation to `sk-code`.\n39: \n40: ## 3. UX Copy Clarity\n41: \n42: Check interface text:\n43: - Buttons use verb + object (`Save changes`, not `OK`).\n44: - Error messages answer what happened, why, and how to fix.\n45: - Empty states explain value and next action.\n46: - Loading states say what is happening when waits are long.\n47: - Terminology stays consistent.\n48: - Placeholders are not the only labels.\n49: - Humor is avoided in errors.\n50: \n51: ## 4. Pseudo-Elements\n52: \n53: Pseudo-elements should reduce DOM clutter and improve native behavior when used correctly.\n54: \n55: Rules (map each finding to P0-P3 by user impact; a broken `content` declaration that hides functional UI is P1, a missed DOM-reduction opportunity is typically P3):\n56: - `::before` and `::after` need `content`.\n57: - Parent needs `position: relative` for absolute pseudo-elements.\n58: - Layering needs z-index discipline so decoration does not cover content.\n59: - Decorative layers should prefer pseudo-elements over extra DOM nodes.\n60: - Pseudo-elements can expand hit targets with negative inset.\n61: \n62: ## 5. View Transitions\n63: \n64: Use native View Transitions for navigation-level shared element changes when supported and when interruption/cancellation constraints fit.\n65: \n66: Rules (map each finding to P0-P3 by user impact; an uncancellable transition that traps an interaction-heavy flow is P0-P1, a default crossfade that could be richer is P3):\n67: - Elements need unique `view-transition-name` during the transition.\n68: - Clean up names after transition.\n69: - Style `::view-transition-*` pseudo-elements when default crossfade is not enough.\n70: - Avoid View Transitions for interaction-heavy UI requiring cancellation.\n71: \n72: ## 6. Production Readiness\n73: \n74: Production-readiness findings include:\n75: - Missing empty/loading/error/success states.\n76: - Long text overflow or missing `min-width: 0` in flex/grid.\n77: - Fixed text containers that fail translation expansion.\n78: - RTL issues from physical properties instead of logical properties.\n79: - Offline and slow-network paths missing.\n80: - Client-only validation for server-required constraints.\n81: - Missing alt text, captions, or media controls.\n82: \n83: ## 7. Finding Owner Map\n84: \n85: | Finding type | Owner |\n86: | --- | --- |\n87: | Palette, type, spacing, responsive, theme tokens | `foundations` |\n88: | Choreography, micro-interactions, reduced motion | `motion` |\n89: | Overall direction or signature visual concept | `interface` |\n90: | Implementation changes | `sk-code` |\n91: | Broader correctness/security/test review | `sk-code-review` |\n\n(End of file - total 91 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Anti-Patterns And Production Details\ndescription: Anti-slop detection, theming drift, token misuse, copy clarity, pseudo-elements, View Transitions, and production-readiness details.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"anti-pattern detection\"\n  - \"AI slop audit\"\n  - \"theming drift\"\n  - \"pseudo-element audit\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Anti-Patterns And Production Details\n\nThis reference catches details that make a UI look generic, fragile, or production-unready.\n\n## 1. Anti-Slop Signals\n\nUse parent `sk-design/references/anti_slop_principles.md` as the shared vocabulary. Common findings:","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti_patterns_production.md","text":"---\ntitle: Anti-Patterns And Production Details\ndescription: Anti-slop detection, theming drift, token misuse, copy clarity, pseudo-elements, View Transitions, and production-readiness details.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"anti-pattern detection\"\n  - \"AI slop audit\"\n  - \"theming drift\"\n  - \"pseudo-element audit\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Anti-Patterns And Production Details\n\nThis reference catches details that make a UI look generic, fragile, or production-unready.\n\n## 1. Anti-Slop Signals\n\nUse parent `sk-design/references/anti_slop_principles.md` as the shared vocabulary. Common findings:\n- Generic cream + serif + terracotta with no subject reason.\n- Near-black + one acid accent as the whole identity.\n- Hairline broadsheet layout with no editorial premise.\n- Repeated glass, blur, glow, mesh gradients, or hero metrics.\n- Uniform card grids everywhere.\n- Decorative `01 / 02 / 03` labels without sequence.\n- Scattered motion instead of one choreographed moment.\n\n## 2. Theming And Tokens\n\nReport:\n- Hard-coded colors where semantic tokens exist.\n- Dark mode variants missing or failing contrast.\n- Primitive tokens used directly in components instead of semantic tokens.\n- One-off spacing, radius, shadow, or z-index values.\n- Theme switching that leaves stale colors or surfaces.\n\nMap token fixes to `foundations` and implementation to `sk-code`.\n\n## 3. UX Copy Clarity\n\nCheck interface text:\n- Buttons use verb + object (`Save changes`, not `OK`).\n- Error messages answer what happened, why, and how to fix.\n- Empty states explain value and next action.\n- Loading states say what is happening when waits are long.\n- Terminology stays consistent.\n- Placeholders are not the only labels.\n- Humor is avoided in errors.\n\n## 4. Pseudo-Elements\n\nPseudo-elements should reduce DOM clutter and improve native behavior when used correctly.\n\nRules (map each finding to P0-P3 by user impact; a broken `content` declaration that hides functional UI is P1, a missed DOM-reduction opportunity is typically P3):\n- `::before` and `::after` need `content`.\n- Parent needs `position: relative` for absolute pseudo-elements.\n- Layering needs z-index discipline so decoration does not cover content.\n- Decorative layers should prefer pseudo-elements over extra DOM nodes.\n- Pseudo-elements can expand hit targets with negative inset.\n\n## 5. View Transitions\n\nUse native View Transitions for navigation-level shared element changes when supported and when interruption/cancellation constraints fit.\n\nRules (map each finding to P0-P3 by user impact; an uncancellable transition that traps an interaction-heavy flow is P0-P1, a default crossfade that could be richer is P3):\n- Elements need unique `view-transition-name` during the transition.\n- Clean up names after transition.\n- Style `::view-transition-*` pseudo-elements when default crossfade is not enough.\n- Avoid View Transitions for interaction-heavy UI requiring cancellation.\n\n## 6. Production Readiness\n\nProduction-readiness findings include:\n- Missing empty/loading/error/success states.\n- Long text overflow or missing `min-width: 0` in flex/grid.\n- Fixed text containers that fail translation expansion.\n- RTL issues from physical properties instead of logical properties.\n- Offline and slow-network paths missing.\n- Client-only validation for server-required constraints.\n- Missing alt text, captions, or media controls.\n\n## 7. Finding Owner Map\n\n| Finding type | Owner |\n| --- | --- |\n| Palette, type, spacing, responsive, theme tokens | `foundations` |\n| Choreography, micro-interactions, reduced motion | `motion` |\n| Overall direction or signature visual concept | `interface` |\n| Implementation changes | `sk-code` |\n| Broader correctness/security/test review | `sk-code-review` |","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":91,"totalLines":91,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti_patterns_production.md","time":{"start":1782532362963,"end":1782532362972}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0df4b7570568c22b016a3f490add10819190beece2bdfc1063"}},"id":"prt_f073552cc001Z8eM2c7hP2tCjZ","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532362974,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_dWvP3oJMSAp1XJH3gDQpNmh0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md","offset":1,"limit":1200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: AI Fingerprint Tells\n3: description: Model-specific defect catalog turned into checkable P0-P3 findings. Codex tells, Gemini tells and 2026-general tells that prove a surface was AI-generated.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"AI fingerprint tells\"\n6:   - \"model specific design defect\"\n7:   - \"codex design tell\"\n8:   - \"looks AI generated audit\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # AI Fingerprint Tells\n15: \n16: This reference turns \"it feels AI-made\" into named, checkable findings. Each tell below is a structural pattern that an image generator or coding model reaches for by reflex, so its presence is strong evidence the surface was machine-authored without revision. Detect the pattern, file a P0-P3 finding and route it to an owner.\n17: \n18: The shared anti-slop vocabulary and the general slop signals live in `anti_patterns_production.md` section 1. Do not re-list those here. This file is the model-specific layer underneath them: the tells that point at a particular generator and that a reviewer can grep or eyeball with a concrete rule. The severity model and findings schema are in `audit_contract.md`. The audit reports these tells, it does not rewrite the element, which is `sk-code` work once the user accepts the fix.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. HOW TO USE THIS CATALOG\n23: \n24: 1. Resolve the surface to source or rendered evidence.\n25: 2. Walk each tell below and check the concrete rule.\n26: 3. For every hit, write a finding with the exact element as evidence, the user impact and the owner.\n27: 4. Most tells land in the Anti-Patterns dimension of the five-dimension score. A few touch Theming or Performance, noted per tell.\n28: 5. A single tell is usually P2 or P3. A gallery of three or more tells on one surface is the Anti-Patterns dimension failing, which is at least P1.\n29: \n30: Severity rule of thumb: one isolated tell with a clean rest-of-surface is P3 polish. A tell that defines the whole identity, or three or more tells together, is P1. A tell that also breaks a real user task (an over-rounded control that clips its own label, a stripe background that tanks contrast) climbs to P0 on the task-failure, not on the tell alone.\n31: \n32: ---\n33: \n34: ## 2. CODEX TELLS\n35: \n36: These are the most frequent giveaways from the Codex lineage. Each one is match-and-refuse in authoring, which makes it match-and-file in audit.\n37: \n38: ### 2.1 Ghost-card border plus shadow\n39: \n40: The pattern is a `1px solid` border and a soft wide drop shadow on the same element, usually a card or a button. The two treatments fight: a border says hard edge, a wide blur says floating, and pairing both as decoration is the tell.\n41: \n42: - Check: any element with `border: 1px solid` and `box-shadow` whose blur radius is 16px or more, together on one element.\n43: - Owner: `foundations` for the token decision, `sk-code` for the change.\n44: - Severity: P2 in isolation, P1 when it repeats across a card grid.\n45: \n46: ### 2.2 Over-rounded cards\n47: \n48: Cards, sections and inputs at `border-radius` 24px and above. Cards top out around 12 to 16px. Full-pill is fine on tags and buttons, but a 28px or 32px or 40px radius on a card is the over-round reflex, and no real brand asks for \"insanely rounded.\"\n49: \n50: - Check: `border-radius` of 24px or more on a card, section, panel or text input.\n51: - Owner: `foundations`.\n52: - Severity: P3 in isolation, P2 when systemic. Climbs to P1 if the radius clips content or a focus ring.\n53: \n54: ### 2.3 Sketchy SVG illustration\n55: \n56: Hand-drawn or doodle-style SVG meant to depict a real subject. Tells include class names like `loose-sketch`, `doodle` or `wavy`, paper-grain filters built from `feTurbulence` or `feDisplacementMap`, plus crude five-to-thirty-path scenes standing in for a tangible object. These read as amateurish, not whimsical.\n57: \n58: - Check: SVG with sketch or doodle class names, turbulence or displacement filters used as grain, low-path crude scene illustrations.\n59: - Owner: `interface` for the direction call (ship a real asset or ship none), `sk-code` to remove.\n60: - Severity: P2, because it undercuts trust in the whole surface.\n61: \n62: ### 2.4 Diagonal stripe background\n63: \n64: Repeating diagonal stripes painted into a `body` pseudo-element or a section background, usually through `repeating-linear-gradient`. Pure decoration with no information and a Codex signature.\n65: \n66: - Check: `repeating-linear-gradient` used as a section or body background.\n67: - Owner: `interface` for direction, `sk-code` to remove.\n68: - Severity: P3, unless the stripes drop text contrast below the threshold in `accessibility_performance.md`, which makes it P1 on contrast.\n69: \n70: ### 2.5 Element-tracking on display type\n71: \n72: Display headings with letter-spacing tighter than -0.04em. The Codex default drifts to -0.05em through -0.085em on display H1s, which makes the letters touch and reads as cramped rather than designed. The floor is -0.04em, and -0.02em to -0.03em is plenty for tight grotesque display.\n73: \n74: - Check: `letter-spacing` tighter than -0.04em on a display or hero heading.\n75: - Owner: `foundations`.\n76: - Severity: P3, or P2 when it forces letters to collide and hurts legibility.\n77: \n78: ---\n79: \n80: ## 3. GEMINI TELLS\n81: \n82: ### 3.1 Image-hover animation\n83: \n84: Any `transform` on the `:hover` of an `<img>`, or a parent-hover pattern that scales, rotates or translates a child image. This is the most common Gemini motion tell. It adds no information because the image is not an action target, and it reads as motion added because the tool could. Card hover feedback belongs on the card background, border or shadow, never on the image and never through the image's parent.\n85: \n86: - Check: `:hover` transforms on `img`, or any parent-hover utility that animates a child image.\n87: - Owner: `motion` for the interaction decision, `sk-code` to change.\n88: - Severity: P2, because it signals reflex motion across the surface.\n89: \n90: ---\n91: \n92: ## 4. 2026-GENERAL TELLS\n93: \n94: These are not tied to one model. They are the saturated defaults of the current generation, so they appear across generators regardless of the brief. That cross-brief uniformity is what makes them tells.\n95: \n96: ### 4.1 Cream or sand body background\n97: \n98: The warm-neutral near-white body background is the saturated default of 2026. The whole band of light warm-tinted neutrals reads as cream, sand, paper or parchment no matter what the token is named, and token names like `--paper`, `--cream`, `--sand`, `--bone`, `--linen` or `--ivory` are tells in themselves. A brief that asks for warm, traditional or magazine-warm does not justify it. Warmth belongs in the accent, the type and the imagery, not in a default warm-tinted body.\n99: \n100: - Check: a body or page background in the light warm-neutral band, or a warm-paper token name used as the page background.\n101: - Owner: `foundations`.\n102: - Severity: P2, because it sets the generic tone for the entire surface. P1 when paired with two or more other tells.\n103: \n104: ### 4.2 Eyebrow above every section\n105: \n106: A tiny uppercase tracked label sitting above every section heading. The small all-caps kicker with wide tracking was a 2023 device and is now the saturated AI scaffold, appearing above most generated sections regardless of brief. One named kicker as a deliberate brand system is voice. An eyebrow on every section is AI grammar.\n107: \n108: - Check: a small uppercase tracked label repeated above three or more section headings.\n109: - Owner: `interface` for the cadence decision, `foundations` if it is a token-level type style.\n110: - Severity: P2.\n111: \n112: The numbered variant (`01 / 02 / 03` markers above every section) is the same reflex one tier deeper. Numbers earn their place only when the section genuinely is an ordered sequence and the order carries information. Numbered eyebrows on every section are AI grammar, same severity as the plain eyebrow.\n113: \n114: ### 4.3 Uniform section fade-and-rise\n115: \n116: One identical entrance animation applied to every section: fade in and rise on scroll, same distance, same easing, same trigger, top to bottom. The tell is the uniform reflex, not motion itself. Staggering items within one list is legitimate, and each reveal should fit what it reveals. Suppressing the reflex is never a reason to ship a page with no motion at all.\n117: \n118: - Check: the same scroll-triggered fade-and-rise applied uniformly to most or all top-level sections.\n119: - Owner: `motion`.\n120: - Severity: P2. Climbs to P1 if the reveal gates content visibility so the section ships blank on a hidden tab or a headless render, because that is a content-delivery failure, not a motion taste issue.\n121: \n122: ---\n123: \n124: ## 5. EVIDENCE AND LABELING\n125: \n126: - Cite the exact element, selector, file and line, rendered observation for each tell.\n127: - A tell found by reading source is a confirmed finding. A tell suspected from a screenshot without the underlying code is an inferred finding, so label it inferred and state that the source would confirm it.\n128: - Do not claim a detector, overlay or browser scan ran unless it actually ran.\n129: - A clean pass on this catalog means no model-specific tells were found. It does not mean the design is distinctive. Pair it with the critique lens in `critique_hardening.md` for the judgment call on hierarchy, voice and flow.\n\n(End of file - total 129 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: AI Fingerprint Tells\ndescription: Model-specific defect catalog turned into checkable P0-P3 findings. Codex tells, Gemini tells and 2026-general tells that prove a surface was AI-generated.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"AI fingerprint tells\"\n  - \"model specific design defect\"\n  - \"codex design tell\"\n  - \"looks AI generated audit\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# AI Fingerprint Tells\n\nThis reference turns \"it feels AI-made\" into named, checkable findings. Each tell below is a structural pattern that an image generator or coding model reaches for by reflex, so its presence is strong evidence the surface was machine-authored without revision. Detect the pattern, file a P0-P3 finding and route it to an owner.\n\nThe shared anti-slop vocabulary and the general slop signals live in `anti_patterns_production.md` section 1. Do not re-list those here. This file is the model-specific layer underneath them: the tells that point at a particular generator and that a reviewer can grep or eyeball with a concrete rule. The severity model and findings schema are in `audit_contract.md`. The audit reports these tells, it does not rewrite the element, which is `sk-code` work once the user accepts the fix.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md","text":"---\ntitle: AI Fingerprint Tells\ndescription: Model-specific defect catalog turned into checkable P0-P3 findings. Codex tells, Gemini tells and 2026-general tells that prove a surface was AI-generated.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"AI fingerprint tells\"\n  - \"model specific design defect\"\n  - \"codex design tell\"\n  - \"looks AI generated audit\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# AI Fingerprint Tells\n\nThis reference turns \"it feels AI-made\" into named, checkable findings. Each tell below is a structural pattern that an image generator or coding model reaches for by reflex, so its presence is strong evidence the surface was machine-authored without revision. Detect the pattern, file a P0-P3 finding and route it to an owner.\n\nThe shared anti-slop vocabulary and the general slop signals live in `anti_patterns_production.md` section 1. Do not re-list those here. This file is the model-specific layer underneath them: the tells that point at a particular generator and that a reviewer can grep or eyeball with a concrete rule. The severity model and findings schema are in `audit_contract.md`. The audit reports these tells, it does not rewrite the element, which is `sk-code` work once the user accepts the fix.\n\n---\n\n## 1. HOW TO USE THIS CATALOG\n\n1. Resolve the surface to source or rendered evidence.\n2. Walk each tell below and check the concrete rule.\n3. For every hit, write a finding with the exact element as evidence, the user impact and the owner.\n4. Most tells land in the Anti-Patterns dimension of the five-dimension score. A few touch Theming or Performance, noted per tell.\n5. A single tell is usually P2 or P3. A gallery of three or more tells on one surface is the Anti-Patterns dimension failing, which is at least P1.\n\nSeverity rule of thumb: one isolated tell with a clean rest-of-surface is P3 polish. A tell that defines the whole identity, or three or more tells together, is P1. A tell that also breaks a real user task (an over-rounded control that clips its own label, a stripe background that tanks contrast) climbs to P0 on the task-failure, not on the tell alone.\n\n---\n\n## 2. CODEX TELLS\n\nThese are the most frequent giveaways from the Codex lineage. Each one is match-and-refuse in authoring, which makes it match-and-file in audit.\n\n### 2.1 Ghost-card border plus shadow\n\nThe pattern is a `1px solid` border and a soft wide drop shadow on the same element, usually a card or a button. The two treatments fight: a border says hard edge, a wide blur says floating, and pairing both as decoration is the tell.\n\n- Check: any element with `border: 1px solid` and `box-shadow` whose blur radius is 16px or more, together on one element.\n- Owner: `foundations` for the token decision, `sk-code` for the change.\n- Severity: P2 in isolation, P1 when it repeats across a card grid.\n\n### 2.2 Over-rounded cards\n\nCards, sections and inputs at `border-radius` 24px and above. Cards top out around 12 to 16px. Full-pill is fine on tags and buttons, but a 28px or 32px or 40px radius on a card is the over-round reflex, and no real brand asks for \"insanely rounded.\"\n\n- Check: `border-radius` of 24px or more on a card, section, panel or text input.\n- Owner: `foundations`.\n- Severity: P3 in isolation, P2 when systemic. Climbs to P1 if the radius clips content or a focus ring.\n\n### 2.3 Sketchy SVG illustration\n\nHand-drawn or doodle-style SVG meant to depict a real subject. Tells include class names like `loose-sketch`, `doodle` or `wavy`, paper-grain filters built from `feTurbulence` or `feDisplacementMap`, plus crude five-to-thirty-path scenes standing in for a tangible object. These read as amateurish, not whimsical.\n\n- Check: SVG with sketch or doodle class names, turbulence or displacement filters used as grain, low-path crude scene illustrations.\n- Owner: `interface` for the direction call (ship a real asset or ship none), `sk-code` to remove.\n- Severity: P2, because it undercuts trust in the whole surface.\n\n### 2.4 Diagonal stripe background\n\nRepeating diagonal stripes painted into a `body` pseudo-element or a section background, usually through `repeating-linear-gradient`. Pure decoration with no information and a Codex signature.\n\n- Check: `repeating-linear-gradient` used as a section or body background.\n- Owner: `interface` for direction, `sk-code` to remove.\n- Severity: P3, unless the stripes drop text contrast below the threshold in `accessibility_performance.md`, which makes it P1 on contrast.\n\n### 2.5 Element-tracking on display type\n\nDisplay headings with letter-spacing tighter than -0.04em. The Codex default drifts to -0.05em through -0.085em on display H1s, which makes the letters touch and reads as cramped rather than designed. The floor is -0.04em, and -0.02em to -0.03em is plenty for tight grotesque display.\n\n- Check: `letter-spacing` tighter than -0.04em on a display or hero heading.\n- Owner: `foundations`.\n- Severity: P3, or P2 when it forces letters to collide and hurts legibility.\n\n---\n\n## 3. GEMINI TELLS\n\n### 3.1 Image-hover animation\n\nAny `transform` on the `:hover` of an `<img>`, or a parent-hover pattern that scales, rotates or translates a child image. This is the most common Gemini motion tell. It adds no information because the image is not an action target, and it reads as motion added because the tool could. Card hover feedback belongs on the card background, border or shadow, never on the image and never through the image's parent.\n\n- Check: `:hover` transforms on `img`, or any parent-hover utility that animates a child image.\n- Owner: `motion` for the interaction decision, `sk-code` to change.\n- Severity: P2, because it signals reflex motion across the surface.\n\n---\n\n## 4. 2026-GENERAL TELLS\n\nThese are not tied to one model. They are the saturated defaults of the current generation, so they appear across generators regardless of the brief. That cross-brief uniformity is what makes them tells.\n\n### 4.1 Cream or sand body background\n\nThe warm-neutral near-white body background is the saturated default of 2026. The whole band of light warm-tinted neutrals reads as cream, sand, paper or parchment no matter what the token is named, and token names like `--paper`, `--cream`, `--sand`, `--bone`, `--linen` or `--ivory` are tells in themselves. A brief that asks for warm, traditional or magazine-warm does not justify it. Warmth belongs in the accent, the type and the imagery, not in a default warm-tinted body.\n\n- Check: a body or page background in the light warm-neutral band, or a warm-paper token name used as the page background.\n- Owner: `foundations`.\n- Severity: P2, because it sets the generic tone for the entire surface. P1 when paired with two or more other tells.\n\n### 4.2 Eyebrow above every section\n\nA tiny uppercase tracked label sitting above every section heading. The small all-caps kicker with wide tracking was a 2023 device and is now the saturated AI scaffold, appearing above most generated sections regardless of brief. One named kicker as a deliberate brand system is voice. An eyebrow on every section is AI grammar.\n\n- Check: a small uppercase tracked label repeated above three or more section headings.\n- Owner: `interface` for the cadence decision, `foundations` if it is a token-level type style.\n- Severity: P2.\n\nThe numbered variant (`01 / 02 / 03` markers above every section) is the same reflex one tier deeper. Numbers earn their place only when the section genuinely is an ordered sequence and the order carries information. Numbered eyebrows on every section are AI grammar, same severity as the plain eyebrow.\n\n### 4.3 Uniform section fade-and-rise\n\nOne identical entrance animation applied to every section: fade in and rise on scroll, same distance, same easing, same trigger, top to bottom. The tell is the uniform reflex, not motion itself. Staggering items within one list is legitimate, and each reveal should fit what it reveals. Suppressing the reflex is never a reason to ship a page with no motion at all.\n\n- Check: the same scroll-triggered fade-and-rise applied uniformly to most or all top-level sections.\n- Owner: `motion`.\n- Severity: P2. Climbs to P1 if the reveal gates content visibility so the section ships blank on a hidden tab or a headless render, because that is a content-delivery failure, not a motion taste issue.\n\n---\n\n## 5. EVIDENCE AND LABELING\n\n- Cite the exact element, selector, file and line, rendered observation for each tell.\n- A tell found by reading source is a confirmed finding. A tell suspected from a screenshot without the underlying code is an inferred finding, so label it inferred and state that the source would confirm it.\n- Do not claim a detector, overlay or browser scan ran unless it actually ran.\n- A clean pass on this catalog means no model-specific tells were found. It does not mean the design is distinctive. Pair it with the critique lens in `critique_hardening.md` for the judgment call on hierarchy, voice and flow.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":129,"totalLines":129,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md","time":{"start":1782532362965,"end":1782532362973}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0df4b7570568c22b016a3f490add188191b9d0cc6ff6c6c653"}},"id":"prt_f073552d4001oe4DHlXFSC7hU4","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532362977,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_EIjppFxoZJnYsxNIv6Dv8a63","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/hardening_edge_cases.md","offset":1,"limit":1200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/hardening_edge_cases.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Hardening Edge Cases\n3: description: A production-readiness matrix for audit. Extreme inputs, API and network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, internationalization and RTL, text expansion, plus CJK and emoji, each as a checkable finding.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"hardening edge cases\"\n6:   - \"production readiness matrix\"\n7:   - \"extreme input audit\"\n8:   - \"rate limit concurrency audit\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Hardening Edge Cases\n15: \n16: A surface that only works with perfect data is not production-ready. This reference is the edge-case matrix the audit walks to prove a surface survives the inputs, failures and languages that real users bring. Each row is a probe, an expected symptom when the surface is unhardened, and the finding to file when the symptom appears.\n17: \n18: The narrative hardening workflow and the persona, cognitive-load and polish lenses live in `critique_hardening.md`. The production-readiness summary and the finding-owner map live in `anti_patterns_production.md`. This file does not repeat that prose. It is the concrete matrix underneath them: the specific probes to run and what each failure proves. The severity model and the findings schema come from `audit_contract.md`, and accessibility resilience stays in `accessibility_performance.md`. The audit reports these gaps and routes them, it does not implement the hardening, which is `sk-code` work after the user accepts the fix.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. HOW TO USE THE MATRIX\n23: \n24: 1. Resolve the surface to source or rendered evidence, following `evidence_capture.md`.\n25: 2. Walk each probe below against the surface. A probe you cannot run on the available evidence is an inferred finding, so label it inferred and state what would confirm it.\n26: 3. For every failure, file a finding with the exact element, the user impact, the severity and the owner.\n27: 4. Severity follows user impact. A failure that loses user work or strands a flow is P0 or P1. A cosmetic overflow with a workaround is P2 or P3. The default question from `audit_contract.md` applies: would a real user fail, contact support or abandon?\n28: 5. Most hardening findings land in the Responsive, Theming or Anti-Patterns dimensions of the five-dimension score. Resilience gaps that block assistive use route to Accessibility instead.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## 2. EXTREME INPUTS\n33: \n34: Real content is longer, shorter and stranger than the mockup. Probe the edges of every text and data field.\n35: \n36: | Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n37: |---|---|---|\n38: | Very long text in names, titles, descriptions | Overflow, clipped layout, broken alignment | Missing overflow handling, or a flex or grid child without `min-width: 0` |\n39: | Single character or empty text | Collapsed container, broken baseline, orphaned label | No minimum sizing or empty-value handling |\n40: | Very large numbers, millions and billions | Truncation, overlap, misaligned columns | No formatting or container budget for large values |\n41: | A list of 1000 or more items | Slow render, scroll jank, frozen interaction | No pagination, virtualization or list bound |\n42: | No data at all | A blank region with no guidance | Missing empty state with a next action |\n43: \n44: Empty, loading and error states are part of this probe. A surface missing any of the three is a production-readiness finding even when the happy path is flawless.\n45: \n46: ---\n47: \n48: ## 3. API AND NETWORK ERRORS\n49: \n50: The network fails, and the surface has to say so without breaking. Force each error and watch the response.\n51: \n52: | Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n53: |---|---|---|\n54: | Offline or dropped connection | Spinner forever, silent failure, lost input | No offline or failure path, no retry |\n55: | Slow response or timeout | Frozen UI with no feedback during the wait | No timeout handling, no progress signal |\n56: | 400 validation error | Generic failure with no field-level detail | Validation errors not surfaced to the fields |\n57: | 401 unauthorized | Dead end with no route back to sign-in | No redirect or re-auth path |\n58: | 403 forbidden | Confusing failure with no explanation | No permission-denied state |\n59: | 404 not found | Raw error or blank screen | No not-found state with a way forward |\n60: | 429 rate limited | Silent failure or an unhelpful retry storm | No rate-limit message, no backoff cue |\n61: | 500 server error | Cryptic message, or the whole UI breaks | No generic error state, no support path, failure not contained |\n62: \n63: The contract for error copy itself, what happened, why and how to recover, lives in `anti_patterns_production.md`. This matrix proves the error path exists and stays contained. One component erroring must not take the whole interface down.\n64: \n65: ---\n66: \n67: ## 4. PERMISSIONS AND RATE LIMITS\n68: \n69: State that depends on who the user is, and on how often they act, needs its own probes.\n70: \n71: | Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n72: |---|---|---|\n73: | No permission to view | Empty screen, or a broken attempt to render forbidden data | No view-permission state |\n74: | No permission to edit | Editable controls that fail silently on submit | No read-only mode, no disabled affordance with a reason |\n75: | Read-only context | The UI looks editable but is not | Read-only state not visually distinct |\n76: | Repeated rapid actions hit a limit | Silent drop, or an error with no recovery guidance | No rate-limit feedback, no cue for when to retry |\n77: \n78: A disabled control still needs an accessible explanation of why it is disabled. That snippet lives in `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md`. Route the accessibility half of a permission finding there.\n79: \n80: ---\n81: \n82: ## 5. CONCURRENCY\n83: \n84: Users double-click, open two tabs and act while a request is still in flight. Probe the races.\n85: \n86: | Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n87: |---|---|---|\n88: | Submit pressed many times fast | Duplicate records, duplicate charges, duplicate requests | Submit not disabled while the request is in flight |\n89: | Same record edited in two tabs | Last write silently wins, the other user's work vanishes | No conflict detection or resolution |\n90: | An optimistic update that the server rejects | UI shows success that never actually happened | No rollback when the update fails |\n91: | Refresh in the middle of a flow | Progress and entered data lost | No state preservation across reload |\n92: \n93: Preventing double submission is the highest-frequency concurrency defect. Disable the action while it runs, and re-enable it on completion or failure.\n94: \n95: ---\n96: \n97: ## 6. INTERNATIONALIZATION AND RTL\n98: \n99: The interface ships in one language and gets used in many. Probe the surface in scripts and directions it was not drawn for.\n100: \n101: | Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n102: |---|---|---|\n103: | Right-to-left language, Arabic or Hebrew | Mirrored layout breaks, arrows and icons point the wrong way | Physical CSS properties used where logical properties belong |\n104: | Locale date, time, number and currency formats | Ambiguous or wrong values for the user's locale | Hard-coded formats instead of locale-aware formatting |\n105: | Pluralization across languages | Wrong plural forms, an English-only plural rule | Plurals assembled by hand instead of a real i18n path |\n106: \n107: RTL failures almost always trace to physical properties. Logical properties such as the inline and block margin, padding and border keywords adapt to direction, where left and right keywords do not. File the finding against physical-property use and route it to `foundations`.\n108: \n109: ---\n110: \n111: ## 7. TEXT EXPANSION\n112: \n113: Translation makes text longer, often much longer. A layout tuned to English clips or overflows in other languages.\n114: \n115: | Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n116: |---|---|---|\n117: | The longest realistic translation, German is often a third longer | Clipped buttons, wrapped labels breaking layout, overflow | Fixed-width text containers that cannot grow |\n118: | Browser zoom to 200 percent | Overlapping or cut-off text | Containers that do not expand with text |\n119: \n120: Budget roughly a third more space for translated text, and let containers size to content rather than to a fixed width. A button sized to fit the English word breaks the moment the German word arrives.\n121: \n122: ---\n123: \n124: ## 8. CJK AND EMOJI\n125: \n126: Chinese, Japanese, Korean and emoji stress assumptions baked into Latin-only layouts.\n127: \n128: | Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n129: |---|---|---|\n130: | CJK characters in every text field | Wrong line breaking, cramped line height, clipped glyphs | Line height and wrapping tuned only for Latin text |\n131: | Emoji in names, messages and inputs | Broken truncation, misaligned baselines, encoding artifacts | Encoding or measurement that assumes one byte per character |\n132: | Mixed scripts in one string | Inconsistent rendering across the mix | No multi-script handling |\n133: \n134: Emoji and CJK characters are multi-byte, so any logic that counts characters as bytes, or truncates by a byte budget, mangles them. Probe truncation and length limits with emoji specifically.\n135: \n136: ---\n137: \n138: ## 9. ROUTING SUMMARY\n139: \n140: 1. Walk the matrix against real evidence, labeling any probe you could not run as inferred.\n141: 2. File each failure with the exact element, the user impact and a severity from `audit_contract.md`.\n142: 3. Route the owner: `foundations` for layout, spacing, logical-property and token fixes, `interface` for empty-state and error-state direction, `sk-code` for implementation.\n143: 4. Keep the boundary. The audit proves the gap and names the owner. It does not harden the surface itself.\n\n(End of file - total 143 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Hardening Edge Cases\ndescription: A production-readiness matrix for audit. Extreme inputs, API and network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, internationalization and RTL, text expansion, plus CJK and emoji, each as a checkable finding.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"hardening edge cases\"\n  - \"production readiness matrix\"\n  - \"extreme input audit\"\n  - \"rate limit concurrency audit\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Hardening Edge Cases\n\nA surface that only works with perfect data is not production-ready. This reference is the edge-case matrix the audit walks to prove a surface survives the inputs, failures and languages that real users bring. Each row is a probe, an expected symptom when the surface is unhardened, and the finding to file when the symptom appears.\n\nThe narrative hardening workflow and the persona, cognitive-load and polish lenses live in `critique_hardening.md`. The production-readiness summary and the finding-owner map live in `anti_patterns_production.md`. This file does not repeat that prose. It is the concrete matrix underneath them: the specific probes to run and what each failure proves. The severity model and the findings schema come from `audit_contract.md`, and accessibility resilience stays in `accessibility_performance.md`. The audit reports these gaps and routes them, it does not implement the hardening, which is `sk-code` work after the user accepts the fix.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/hardening_edge_cases.md","text":"---\ntitle: Hardening Edge Cases\ndescription: A production-readiness matrix for audit. Extreme inputs, API and network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, internationalization and RTL, text expansion, plus CJK and emoji, each as a checkable finding.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"hardening edge cases\"\n  - \"production readiness matrix\"\n  - \"extreme input audit\"\n  - \"rate limit concurrency audit\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Hardening Edge Cases\n\nA surface that only works with perfect data is not production-ready. This reference is the edge-case matrix the audit walks to prove a surface survives the inputs, failures and languages that real users bring. Each row is a probe, an expected symptom when the surface is unhardened, and the finding to file when the symptom appears.\n\nThe narrative hardening workflow and the persona, cognitive-load and polish lenses live in `critique_hardening.md`. The production-readiness summary and the finding-owner map live in `anti_patterns_production.md`. This file does not repeat that prose. It is the concrete matrix underneath them: the specific probes to run and what each failure proves. The severity model and the findings schema come from `audit_contract.md`, and accessibility resilience stays in `accessibility_performance.md`. The audit reports these gaps and routes them, it does not implement the hardening, which is `sk-code` work after the user accepts the fix.\n\n---\n\n## 1. HOW TO USE THE MATRIX\n\n1. Resolve the surface to source or rendered evidence, following `evidence_capture.md`.\n2. Walk each probe below against the surface. A probe you cannot run on the available evidence is an inferred finding, so label it inferred and state what would confirm it.\n3. For every failure, file a finding with the exact element, the user impact, the severity and the owner.\n4. Severity follows user impact. A failure that loses user work or strands a flow is P0 or P1. A cosmetic overflow with a workaround is P2 or P3. The default question from `audit_contract.md` applies: would a real user fail, contact support or abandon?\n5. Most hardening findings land in the Responsive, Theming or Anti-Patterns dimensions of the five-dimension score. Resilience gaps that block assistive use route to Accessibility instead.\n\n---\n\n## 2. EXTREME INPUTS\n\nReal content is longer, shorter and stranger than the mockup. Probe the edges of every text and data field.\n\n| Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n|---|---|---|\n| Very long text in names, titles, descriptions | Overflow, clipped layout, broken alignment | Missing overflow handling, or a flex or grid child without `min-width: 0` |\n| Single character or empty text | Collapsed container, broken baseline, orphaned label | No minimum sizing or empty-value handling |\n| Very large numbers, millions and billions | Truncation, overlap, misaligned columns | No formatting or container budget for large values |\n| A list of 1000 or more items | Slow render, scroll jank, frozen interaction | No pagination, virtualization or list bound |\n| No data at all | A blank region with no guidance | Missing empty state with a next action |\n\nEmpty, loading and error states are part of this probe. A surface missing any of the three is a production-readiness finding even when the happy path is flawless.\n\n---\n\n## 3. API AND NETWORK ERRORS\n\nThe network fails, and the surface has to say so without breaking. Force each error and watch the response.\n\n| Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n|---|---|---|\n| Offline or dropped connection | Spinner forever, silent failure, lost input | No offline or failure path, no retry |\n| Slow response or timeout | Frozen UI with no feedback during the wait | No timeout handling, no progress signal |\n| 400 validation error | Generic failure with no field-level detail | Validation errors not surfaced to the fields |\n| 401 unauthorized | Dead end with no route back to sign-in | No redirect or re-auth path |\n| 403 forbidden | Confusing failure with no explanation | No permission-denied state |\n| 404 not found | Raw error or blank screen | No not-found state with a way forward |\n| 429 rate limited | Silent failure or an unhelpful retry storm | No rate-limit message, no backoff cue |\n| 500 server error | Cryptic message, or the whole UI breaks | No generic error state, no support path, failure not contained |\n\nThe contract for error copy itself, what happened, why and how to recover, lives in `anti_patterns_production.md`. This matrix proves the error path exists and stays contained. One component erroring must not take the whole interface down.\n\n---\n\n## 4. PERMISSIONS AND RATE LIMITS\n\nState that depends on who the user is, and on how often they act, needs its own probes.\n\n| Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n|---|---|---|\n| No permission to view | Empty screen, or a broken attempt to render forbidden data | No view-permission state |\n| No permission to edit | Editable controls that fail silently on submit | No read-only mode, no disabled affordance with a reason |\n| Read-only context | The UI looks editable but is not | Read-only state not visually distinct |\n| Repeated rapid actions hit a limit | Silent drop, or an error with no recovery guidance | No rate-limit feedback, no cue for when to retry |\n\nA disabled control still needs an accessible explanation of why it is disabled. That snippet lives in `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md`. Route the accessibility half of a permission finding there.\n\n---\n\n## 5. CONCURRENCY\n\nUsers double-click, open two tabs and act while a request is still in flight. Probe the races.\n\n| Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n|---|---|---|\n| Submit pressed many times fast | Duplicate records, duplicate charges, duplicate requests | Submit not disabled while the request is in flight |\n| Same record edited in two tabs | Last write silently wins, the other user's work vanishes | No conflict detection or resolution |\n| An optimistic update that the server rejects | UI shows success that never actually happened | No rollback when the update fails |\n| Refresh in the middle of a flow | Progress and entered data lost | No state preservation across reload |\n\nPreventing double submission is the highest-frequency concurrency defect. Disable the action while it runs, and re-enable it on completion or failure.\n\n---\n\n## 6. INTERNATIONALIZATION AND RTL\n\nThe interface ships in one language and gets used in many. Probe the surface in scripts and directions it was not drawn for.\n\n| Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n|---|---|---|\n| Right-to-left language, Arabic or Hebrew | Mirrored layout breaks, arrows and icons point the wrong way | Physical CSS properties used where logical properties belong |\n| Locale date, time, number and currency formats | Ambiguous or wrong values for the user's locale | Hard-coded formats instead of locale-aware formatting |\n| Pluralization across languages | Wrong plural forms, an English-only plural rule | Plurals assembled by hand instead of a real i18n path |\n\nRTL failures almost always trace to physical properties. Logical properties such as the inline and block margin, padding and border keywords adapt to direction, where left and right keywords do not. File the finding against physical-property use and route it to `foundations`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. TEXT EXPANSION\n\nTranslation makes text longer, often much longer. A layout tuned to English clips or overflows in other languages.\n\n| Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n|---|---|---|\n| The longest realistic translation, German is often a third longer | Clipped buttons, wrapped labels breaking layout, overflow | Fixed-width text containers that cannot grow |\n| Browser zoom to 200 percent | Overlapping or cut-off text | Containers that do not expand with text |\n\nBudget roughly a third more space for translated text, and let containers size to content rather than to a fixed width. A button sized to fit the English word breaks the moment the German word arrives.\n\n---\n\n## 8. CJK AND EMOJI\n\nChinese, Japanese, Korean and emoji stress assumptions baked into Latin-only layouts.\n\n| Probe | Expected symptom when unhardened | Finding to file |\n|---|---|---|\n| CJK characters in every text field | Wrong line breaking, cramped line height, clipped glyphs | Line height and wrapping tuned only for Latin text |\n| Emoji in names, messages and inputs | Broken truncation, misaligned baselines, encoding artifacts | Encoding or measurement that assumes one byte per character |\n| Mixed scripts in one string | Inconsistent rendering across the mix | No multi-script handling |\n\nEmoji and CJK characters are multi-byte, so any logic that counts characters as bytes, or truncates by a byte budget, mangles them. Probe truncation and length limits with emoji specifically.\n\n---\n\n## 9. ROUTING SUMMARY\n\n1. Walk the matrix against real evidence, labeling any probe you could not run as inferred.\n2. File each failure with the exact element, the user impact and a severity from `audit_contract.md`.\n3. Route the owner: `foundations` for layout, spacing, logical-property and token fixes, `interface` for empty-state and error-state direction, `sk-code` for implementation.\n4. Keep the boundary. The audit proves the gap and names the owner. It does not harden the surface itself.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":143,"totalLines":143,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/hardening_edge_cases.md","time":{"start":1782532362968,"end":1782532362975}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0df4b7570568c22b016a3f490add208191ac29586ebc588fa0"}},"id":"prt_f073552d6001eCA3ofxnLe1ZA5","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532362979,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_0tZ8VRT34O1L2QNFi8xHUtB6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/corpus_map.md","offset":1,"limit":1000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/corpus_map.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Audit Corpus Map\n3: description: Source-to-guidance map for QA, critique, hardening, and production-readiness material distilled into audit.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"audit corpus\"\n6:   - \"critique source map\"\n7:   - \"design QA sources\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: implementation\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: ---\n12: \n13: # Audit Corpus Map\n14: \n15: This skill distills QA and critique sources into one cross-cutting mode child.\n16: \n17: ## Source Files\n18: \n19: | Corpus file | Distilled into | Practical guidance kept |\n20: | --- | --- | --- |\n21: | `external/audit.md` | `audit_contract.md` | 5-dimension `/20` score, P0-P3 severities, findings schema |\n22: | `external/critique.md` | `critique_hardening.md` | independent assessment, anti-pattern verdict, heuristics, cognitive load, personas |\n23: | `external/polish.md` | `critique_hardening.md`, `anti_patterns_production.md` | design-system discovery, drift root cause, polish checklist, real evidence |\n24: | `external/harden.md` | `critique_hardening.md` | edge cases, errors, i18n, empty/loading states, resilience |\n25: | `external/optimize.md` | `accessibility_performance.md` | Core Web Vitals, loading, rendering, runtime and network performance (CWV modernized FID->INP on distillation) |\n26: | `external/fixing-accessibility.md` | `accessibility_performance.md` | accessible names, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms, announcements, contrast |\n27: | `external/fixing-motion-performance.md` | `accessibility_performance.md` | animation performance, scroll, paint, layers, blur, tool boundaries |\n28: | `external/clarify.md` | `anti_patterns_production.md` | UX writing, error copy, CTAs, empty states, terminology, localization |\n29: | `external/pseudo-elements.md` | `anti_patterns_production.md` | pseudo-element and View Transitions review rules |\n30: \n31: ## Distillation Notes\n32: \n33: - Core Web Vitals were modernized during distillation: `external/optimize.md` still lists the deprecated First Input Delay (FID < 100ms), but `accessibility_performance.md` intentionally uses Interaction to Next Paint (INP < 200ms). Do not revert to FID from the stale corpus source.\n34: \n35: ## Distillation Boundary\n36: \n37: This child reports and scores issues. Sibling skills own creation and repair guidance; implementation belongs to `sk-code` after the user accepts fixes.\n\n(End of file - total 37 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Audit Corpus Map\ndescription: Source-to-guidance map for QA, critique, hardening, and production-readiness material distilled into audit.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"audit corpus\"\n  - \"critique source map\"\n  - \"design QA sources\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Audit Corpus Map\n\nThis skill distills QA and critique sources into one cross-cutting mode child.\n\n## Source Files\n\n| Corpus file | Distilled into | Practical guidance kept |\n| --- | --- | --- |","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/corpus_map.md","text":"---\ntitle: Audit Corpus Map\ndescription: Source-to-guidance map for QA, critique, hardening, and production-readiness material distilled into audit.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"audit corpus\"\n  - \"critique source map\"\n  - \"design QA sources\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Audit Corpus Map\n\nThis skill distills QA and critique sources into one cross-cutting mode child.\n\n## Source Files\n\n| Corpus file | Distilled into | Practical guidance kept |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| `external/audit.md` | `audit_contract.md` | 5-dimension `/20` score, P0-P3 severities, findings schema |\n| `external/critique.md` | `critique_hardening.md` | independent assessment, anti-pattern verdict, heuristics, cognitive load, personas |\n| `external/polish.md` | `critique_hardening.md`, `anti_patterns_production.md` | design-system discovery, drift root cause, polish checklist, real evidence |\n| `external/harden.md` | `critique_hardening.md` | edge cases, errors, i18n, empty/loading states, resilience |\n| `external/optimize.md` | `accessibility_performance.md` | Core Web Vitals, loading, rendering, runtime and network performance (CWV modernized FID->INP on distillation) |\n| `external/fixing-accessibility.md` | `accessibility_performance.md` | accessible names, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms, announcements, contrast |\n| `external/fixing-motion-performance.md` | `accessibility_performance.md` | animation performance, scroll, paint, layers, blur, tool boundaries |\n| `external/clarify.md` | `anti_patterns_production.md` | UX writing, error copy, CTAs, empty states, terminology, localization |\n| `external/pseudo-elements.md` | `anti_patterns_production.md` | pseudo-element and View Transitions review rules |\n\n## Distillation Notes\n\n- Core Web Vitals were modernized during distillation: `external/optimize.md` still lists the deprecated First Input Delay (FID < 100ms), but `accessibility_performance.md` intentionally uses Interaction to Next Paint (INP < 200ms). Do not revert to FID from the stale corpus source.\n\n## Distillation Boundary\n\nThis child reports and scores issues. Sibling skills own creation and repair guidance; implementation belongs to `sk-code` after the user accepts fixes.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":37,"totalLines":37,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/corpus_map.md","time":{"start":1782532362976,"end":1782532362979}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0df4b7570568c22b016a3f490add2481919ce3ba88caf1c3ff"}},"id":"prt_f073552d900179KF8Lqd1PrjEq","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532362992,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_v9inbSUefmWPNEdWykS2QsAK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md","offset":1,"limit":1200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n3: description: The shared sk-design operating register. Declare whether a design IS the product or SERVES it, then read the six downstream dials that decision sets.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"brand vs product register\"\n6:   - \"design operating register\"\n7:   - \"design is the product\"\n8:   - \"design serves the product\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n15: \n16: The first design decision, before color, type, layout, or motion: is this surface a Brand surface or a Product surface? That one call sets six downstream dials. Skipping it is the most common reason design output drifts to a generic default.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Give every design mode one shared, up-front decision that calibrates the rest of the work. \"Brand\" and \"Product\" are not styles, they are operating postures. The register names the posture once and the six dials inherit it, so a landing page and an admin dashboard never get the same defaults by accident.\n25: \n26: ### Usage\n27: \n28: Set the register at the start of any design task, before the mode-specific workflow runs. Each mode (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) reads the register and applies the dial settings for the chosen posture. The register is shared vocabulary, not a sixth mode and not a replacement for mode workflows.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## 2. THE REGISTER DECISION\n33: \n34: A surface takes one of two postures:\n35: \n36: - **Brand (design IS the product).** Marketing sites, landing pages, campaigns, long-form content, portfolios. The design is the thing being consumed, so expression, identity and a memorable moment are the job.\n37: - **Product (design SERVES the product).** App UI, admin, dashboards, tools, settings, forms. The design carries the user to a task, so clarity, density and consistency are the job.\n38: \n39: ### How to pick (first match wins)\n40: \n41: 1. **Task cue.** Words in the request like \"landing page\", \"campaign\" and \"portfolio\" point to Brand. Words like \"dashboard\", \"admin\", \"settings\" and \"tool\" point to Product.\n42: 2. **Surface in focus.** The actual page, route, or file being worked on, even inside a mixed app. A marketing page inside a product app is still Brand.\n43: 3. **Declared register.** A `register` field in the project's PRODUCT.md or DESIGN.md, when present, is authoritative.\n44: \n45: A mixed product has both postures: the marketing surface is Brand, the app shell is Product. Set the register per surface, not per project.\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ## 3. THE SIX DIALS\n50: \n51: The register sets these six. When the surface is unlabeled and internal, Product is the safer default. Brand is the default only when the surface is clearly the thing being sold.\n52: \n53: | Dial | Brand (design IS the product) | Product (design SERVES the product) |\n54: |---|---|---|\n55: | **Density** | Generous and expressive, with room for one big move | Information-dense and efficient, whitespace earns its place |\n56: | **Motion budget** | Motion is voice: one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered reveals, with scroll motion reserved for moments that earn it | 150 to 250 ms state transitions only, no page-load choreography, motion conveys feedback, reveal, loading and view changes |\n57: | **Color dosage** | Palette is voice: Committed, Full, or Drenched strategies may exceed the 10% accent rule | Semantic-first and almost always Restrained, accent reserved for primary action, selection and state, never decoration |\n58: | **Copy register** | Expressive and voice-led, the words carry identity | Plain, functional and consistent, one copy register across every screen |\n59: | **Anti-slop strictness** | Reject the brand defaults: cream or sand body background, an eyebrow above every section, numbered section scaffolding, over-rounded cards | Reject the product defaults: low-contrast muted-gray text, color used as decoration, undifferentiated card grids |\n60: | **Audit severity** | Weight distinctiveness and voice, a generic-but-functional brand surface is a real finding | Weight affordance, accessibility and consistency, an expressive-but-unclear product surface is a real finding |\n61: \n62: ### The color-strategy axis\n63: \n64: Color dosage resolves to one of four strategies, ordered by how much color carries the surface:\n65: \n66: - **Restrained**: tinted neutrals plus one accent at 10% or less. The Product default.\n67: - **Committed**: one saturated color carries 30 to 60% of the surface. The Brand default for identity-driven pages.\n68: - **Full palette**: three to four named color roles, each used deliberately. Brand campaigns and Product data visualization.\n69: - **Drenched**: the surface itself is the color. Brand heroes and campaign pages only.\n70: \n71: ---\n72: \n73: ## 4. MODE USAGE\n74: \n75: - **interface** reads the register first, then sets density, the motion budget and the color strategy for direction and build.\n76: - **foundations** reads the register to choose the color strategy and the density of the token system (spacing rhythm, type scale).\n77: - **motion** reads the motion-budget dial to decide whether a surface gets choreography or only state transitions.\n78: - **audit** reads the audit-severity dial so a finding is weighted by posture: distinctiveness for Brand, affordance and consistency for Product.\n79: - **md-generator** records the register of the site it extracts, so a captured Style Reference carries the posture forward.\n\n(End of file - total 79 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\ndescription: The shared sk-design operating register. Declare whether a design IS the product or SERVES it, then read the six downstream dials that decision sets.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"brand vs product register\"\n  - \"design operating register\"\n  - \"design is the product\"\n  - \"design serves the product\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n\nThe first design decision, before color, type, layout, or motion: is this surface a Brand surface or a Product surface? That one call sets six downstream dials. Skipping it is the most common reason design output drifts to a generic default.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md","text":"---\ntitle: Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\ndescription: The shared sk-design operating register. Declare whether a design IS the product or SERVES it, then read the six downstream dials that decision sets.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"brand vs product register\"\n  - \"design operating register\"\n  - \"design is the product\"\n  - \"design serves the product\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n\nThe first design decision, before color, type, layout, or motion: is this surface a Brand surface or a Product surface? That one call sets six downstream dials. Skipping it is the most common reason design output drifts to a generic default.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nGive every design mode one shared, up-front decision that calibrates the rest of the work. \"Brand\" and \"Product\" are not styles, they are operating postures. The register names the posture once and the six dials inherit it, so a landing page and an admin dashboard never get the same defaults by accident.\n\n### Usage\n\nSet the register at the start of any design task, before the mode-specific workflow runs. Each mode (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) reads the register and applies the dial settings for the chosen posture. The register is shared vocabulary, not a sixth mode and not a replacement for mode workflows.\n\n---\n\n## 2. THE REGISTER DECISION\n\nA surface takes one of two postures:\n\n- **Brand (design IS the product).** Marketing sites, landing pages, campaigns, long-form content, portfolios. The design is the thing being consumed, so expression, identity and a memorable moment are the job.\n- **Product (design SERVES the product).** App UI, admin, dashboards, tools, settings, forms. The design carries the user to a task, so clarity, density and consistency are the job.\n\n### How to pick (first match wins)\n\n1. **Task cue.** Words in the request like \"landing page\", \"campaign\" and \"portfolio\" point to Brand. Words like \"dashboard\", \"admin\", \"settings\" and \"tool\" point to Product.\n2. **Surface in focus.** The actual page, route, or file being worked on, even inside a mixed app. A marketing page inside a product app is still Brand.\n3. **Declared register.** A `register` field in the project's PRODUCT.md or DESIGN.md, when present, is authoritative.\n\nA mixed product has both postures: the marketing surface is Brand, the app shell is Product. Set the register per surface, not per project.\n\n---\n\n## 3. THE SIX DIALS\n\nThe register sets these six. When the surface is unlabeled and internal, Product is the safer default. Brand is the default only when the surface is clearly the thing being sold.\n\n| Dial | Brand (design IS the product) | Product (design SERVES the product) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Density** | Generous and expressive, with room for one big move | Information-dense and efficient, whitespace earns its place |\n| **Motion budget** | Motion is voice: one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered reveals, with scroll motion reserved for moments that earn it | 150 to 250 ms state transitions only, no page-load choreography, motion conveys feedback, reveal, loading and view changes |\n| **Color dosage** | Palette is voice: Committed, Full, or Drenched strategies may exceed the 10% accent rule | Semantic-first and almost always Restrained, accent reserved for primary action, selection and state, never decoration |\n| **Copy register** | Expressive and voice-led, the words carry identity | Plain, functional and consistent, one copy register across every screen |\n| **Anti-slop strictness** | Reject the brand defaults: cream or sand body background, an eyebrow above every section, numbered section scaffolding, over-rounded cards | Reject the product defaults: low-contrast muted-gray text, color used as decoration, undifferentiated card grids |\n| **Audit severity** | Weight distinctiveness and voice, a generic-but-functional brand surface is a real finding | Weight affordance, accessibility and consistency, an expressive-but-unclear product surface is a real finding |\n\n### The color-strategy axis\n\nColor dosage resolves to one of four strategies, ordered by how much color carries the surface:\n\n- **Restrained**: tinted neutrals plus one accent at 10% or less. The Product default.\n- **Committed**: one saturated color carries 30 to 60% of the surface. The Brand default for identity-driven pages.\n- **Full palette**: three to four named color roles, each used deliberately. Brand campaigns and Product data visualization.\n- **Drenched**: the surface itself is the color. Brand heroes and campaign pages only.\n\n---\n\n## 4. MODE USAGE\n\n- **interface** reads the register first, then sets density, the motion budget and the color strategy for direction and build.\n- **foundations** reads the register to choose the color strategy and the density of the token system (spacing rhythm, type scale).\n- **motion** reads the motion-budget dial to decide whether a surface gets choreography or only state transitions.\n- **audit** reads the audit-severity dial so a finding is weighted by posture: distinctiveness for Brand, affordance and consistency for Product.\n- **md-generator** records the register of the site it extracts, so a captured Style Reference carries the posture forward.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":79,"totalLines":79,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md","time":{"start":1782532362981,"end":1782532362991}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0df4b7570568c22b016a3f490add2c8191b72ef3a9396a8dec"}},"id":"prt_f073552e1001Myuo1W1CTYbFZ0","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532362993,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_kjXjrbD0pdVjbAfkYdCr60I8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/assets/register_card.md","offset":1,"limit":800},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/assets/register_card.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Register Card\n3: description: One-page fill-in card to set the Brand-vs-Product register for a surface and read off the six dial defaults each design mode applies.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"register card\"\n6:   - \"brand product fill-in card\"\n7:   - \"design register checklist\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: general\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: ---\n12: \n13: # Register Card\n14: \n15: Fill this in once at the start of a design task, before the mode workflow runs. It resolves the surface to Brand or Product and hands each mode its dial defaults. Full rationale: `../register.md`.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## 1. SET THE REGISTER\n20: \n21: | Question | Answer |\n22: |---|---|\n23: | What surface is this? (page / route / file) | `__________` |\n24: | Task cue | landing / campaign / portfolio points to Brand. dashboard / admin / settings / tool points to Product |\n25: | Declared `register` in PRODUCT.md or DESIGN.md? | `__________` (authoritative if present) |\n26: | **Register (first match wins)** | [ ] Brand (design IS the product) [ ] Product (design SERVES the product) |\n27: \n28: A mixed product is set per surface, not per project: the marketing page is Brand, the app shell is Product.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## 2. READ THE DIALS\n33: \n34: Copy the column for the chosen register.\n35: \n36: | Dial | If Brand | If Product |\n37: |---|---|---|\n38: | Density | Generous, one big move | Dense, efficient |\n39: | Motion budget | One rehearsed entrance, earned scroll motion | 150 to 250 ms state transitions, no page-load choreography |\n40: | Color dosage | Committed / Full / Drenched, may exceed 10% accent | Restrained, accent at or below 10% for action / selection / state |\n41: | Copy register | Expressive, voice-led | Plain, functional, one register |\n42: | Anti-slop watch | cream background, eyebrow on every section, numbered scaffolding, over-round | low-contrast gray text, color as decoration, snap-grid cards |\n43: | Audit severity | Weight distinctiveness and voice | Weight affordance, accessibility, consistency |\n44: \n45: Color strategy: Restrained (Product default) · Committed (Brand identity) · Full palette (campaigns or data viz) · Drenched (Brand heroes).\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ## 3. HAND OFF TO THE MODES\n50: \n51: - interface: density, motion budget, color strategy\n52: - foundations: color strategy, token density\n53: - motion: motion budget (choreography vs state only)\n54: - audit: audit-severity weighting\n55: - md-generator: record the extracted surface's register\n56: \n57: If a mode default contradicts this card, the card wins for posture, and the mode owns the craft within it.\n\n(End of file - total 57 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Register Card\ndescription: One-page fill-in card to set the Brand-vs-Product register for a surface and read off the six dial defaults each design mode applies.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"register card\"\n  - \"brand product fill-in card\"\n  - \"design register checklist\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Register Card\n\nFill this in once at the start of a design task, before the mode workflow runs. It resolves the surface to Brand or Product and hands each mode its dial defaults. Full rationale: `../register.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. SET THE REGISTER\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/assets/register_card.md","text":"---\ntitle: Register Card\ndescription: One-page fill-in card to set the Brand-vs-Product register for a surface and read off the six dial defaults each design mode applies.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"register card\"\n  - \"brand product fill-in card\"\n  - \"design register checklist\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Register Card\n\nFill this in once at the start of a design task, before the mode workflow runs. It resolves the surface to Brand or Product and hands each mode its dial defaults. Full rationale: `../register.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. SET THE REGISTER\n\n| Question | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| What surface is this? (page / route / file) | `__________` |\n| Task cue | landing / campaign / portfolio points to Brand. dashboard / admin / settings / tool points to Product |\n| Declared `register` in PRODUCT.md or DESIGN.md? | `__________` (authoritative if present) |\n| **Register (first match wins)** | [ ] Brand (design IS the product) [ ] Product (design SERVES the product) |\n\nA mixed product is set per surface, not per project: the marketing page is Brand, the app shell is Product.\n\n---\n\n## 2. READ THE DIALS\n\nCopy the column for the chosen register.\n\n| Dial | If Brand | If Product |\n|---|---|---|\n| Density | Generous, one big move | Dense, efficient |\n| Motion budget | One rehearsed entrance, earned scroll motion | 150 to 250 ms state transitions, no page-load choreography |\n| Color dosage | Committed / Full / Drenched, may exceed 10% accent | Restrained, accent at or below 10% for action / selection / state |\n| Copy register | Expressive, voice-led | Plain, functional, one register |\n| Anti-slop watch | cream background, eyebrow on every section, numbered scaffolding, over-round | low-contrast gray text, color as decoration, snap-grid cards |\n| Audit severity | Weight distinctiveness and voice | Weight affordance, accessibility, consistency |\n\nColor strategy: Restrained (Product default) · Committed (Brand identity) · Full palette (campaigns or data viz) · Drenched (Brand heroes).\n\n---\n\n## 3. HAND OFF TO THE MODES\n\n- interface: density, motion budget, color strategy\n- foundations: color strategy, token density\n- motion: motion budget (choreography vs state only)\n- audit: audit-severity weighting\n- md-generator: record the extracted surface's register\n\nIf a mode default contradicts this card, the card wins for posture, and the mode owns the craft within it.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":57,"totalLines":57,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/assets/register_card.md","time":{"start":1782532362988,"end":1782532362992}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0df4b7570568c22b016a3f490add34819197403d42f4ccba16"}},"id":"prt_f073552e5001T0Oihmic0q4jX1","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782532363436,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f073554aa001eJUfmqlUrPBmbE","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"e71ed84a96990e75b9a129ea446b8dd65bdb4226","messageID":"msg_f0734ffdc001tCsCBnREJfT4D1","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":135959,"input":19747,"output":462,"reasoning":38,"cache":{"write":0,"read":115712}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782532365307,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f07355bfa001Y3MlRoA0H6qSjI","messageID":"msg_f07355602001Wyb7U10hovPGEj","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","snapshot":"e71ed84a96990e75b9a129ea446b8dd65bdb4226","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532373526,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_hNj2GdlZJRSos7WPkRNtYhUg","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json","offset":1,"limit":1000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n3:   \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n4:   \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All five modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n5:   \"discriminator\": {\n6:     \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n7:     \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/) or playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\"\n8:   },\n9:   \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n10:     \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n11:     \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. The original flat skill name is preserved as packetSkillName; the packet folder is the short mode key, so folder != packetSkillName is grandfathered here and recorded per mode via grandfatheredFolderMismatch.\",\n12:     \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true when the packet folder (short mode key, e.g. 'interface') differs from packetSkillName (the preserved flat name, e.g. 'interface'). All five sk-design modes preserve their original flat names, so all five are grandfathered.\"\n13:   },\n14:   \"modes\": [\n15:     {\n16:       \"workflowMode\": \"interface\",\n17:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n18:       \"packet\": \"design-interface\",\n19:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\",\n20:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n21:       \"aliases\": [\"interface design\", \"frontend design\", \"visual design\", \"visual identity\", \"make it look good\", \"looks templated\", \"redesign the ui\", \"hero section\", \"ui build\", \"design variations\"],\n22:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n23:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n24:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\"\n25:       }\n26:     },\n27:     {\n28:       \"workflowMode\": \"foundations\",\n29:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n30:       \"packet\": \"design-foundations\",\n31:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\",\n32:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n33:       \"aliases\": [\"design foundations\", \"color system\", \"oklch palette\", \"color token system\", \"dark mode palette\", \"typography scale\", \"font pairing\", \"spacing system\", \"responsive layout\", \"design tokens\"],\n34:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n35:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n36:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\"\n37:       }\n38:     },\n39:     {\n40:       \"workflowMode\": \"motion\",\n41:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n42:       \"packet\": \"design-motion\",\n43:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-motion\",\n44:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n45:       \"aliases\": [\"motion design\", \"animate this\", \"micro-interactions\", \"transitions\", \"AnimatePresence\", \"exit animation\", \"reduced motion\", \"morphing icons\", \"motion performance\"],\n46:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n47:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n48:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-motion\"\n49:       }\n50:     },\n51:     {\n52:       \"workflowMode\": \"audit\",\n53:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n54:       \"packet\": \"design-audit\",\n55:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\",\n56:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n57:       \"aliases\": [\"design audit\", \"ui critique\", \"accessibility audit\", \"performance audit\", \"anti-slop detection\", \"production hardening\", \"design quality score\", \"P0 P1 design findings\"],\n58:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n59:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n60:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\"\n61:       }\n62:     },\n63:     {\n64:       \"workflowMode\": \"md-generator\",\n65:       \"backendKind\": \"playwright-extract\",\n66:       \"packet\": \"design-md-generator\",\n67:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-md-generator\",\n68:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n69:       \"aliases\": [\"extract design system\", \"generate design.md\", \"capture website css\", \"design tokens from url\", \"create design reference\", \"design-to-markdown\", \"extract design tokens\"],\n70:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n71:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n72:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-md-generator\"\n73:       }\n74:     }\n75:   ]\n76: }\n\n(End of file - total 76 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All five modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n  \"discriminator\": {\n    \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n    \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/) or playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\"\n  },\n  \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n    \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n    \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. The original flat skill name is preserved as packetSkillName; the packet folder is the short mode key, so folder != packetSkillName is grandfathered here and recorded per mode via grandfatheredFolderMismatch.\",\n    \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true when the packet folder (short mode key, e.g. 'interface') differs from packetSkillName (the preserved flat name, e.g. 'interface'). All five sk-design modes preserve their original flat names, so all five are grandfathered.\"\n  },\n  \"modes\": [\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"interface\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-interface\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json","text":"{\n  \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All five modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n  \"discriminator\": {\n    \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n    \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/) or playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\"\n  },\n  \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n    \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n    \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. The original flat skill name is preserved as packetSkillName; the packet folder is the short mode key, so folder != packetSkillName is grandfathered here and recorded per mode via grandfatheredFolderMismatch.\",\n    \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true when the packet folder (short mode key, e.g. 'interface') differs from packetSkillName (the preserved flat name, e.g. 'interface'). All five sk-design modes preserve their original flat names, so all five are grandfathered.\"\n  },\n  \"modes\": [\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"interface\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-interface\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"interface design\", \"frontend design\", \"visual design\", \"visual identity\", \"make it look good\", \"looks templated\", \"redesign the ui\", \"hero section\", \"ui build\", \"design variations\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"foundations\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-foundations\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"design foundations\", \"color system\", \"oklch palette\", \"color token system\", \"dark mode palette\", \"typography scale\", \"font pairing\", \"spacing system\", \"responsive layout\", \"design tokens\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"motion\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-motion\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-motion\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"motion design\", \"animate this\", \"micro-interactions\", \"transitions\", \"AnimatePresence\", \"exit animation\", \"reduced motion\", \"morphing icons\", \"motion performance\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-motion\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"audit\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-audit\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"design audit\", \"ui critique\", \"accessibility audit\", \"performance audit\", \"anti-slop detection\", \"production hardening\", \"design quality score\", \"P0 P1 design findings\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"md-generator\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"playwright-extract\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-md-generator\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-md-generator\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"extract design system\", \"generate design.md\", \"capture website css\", \"design tokens from url\", \"create design reference\", \"design-to-markdown\", \"extract design tokens\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-md-generator\"\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":76,"totalLines":76,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json","time":{"start":1782532373518,"end":1782532373525}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_053371a57b5009f1016a3f491577f481918f8c8c4fb74dec61"}},"id":"prt_f07357c08001nGfFdr8JKsxUrJ","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07355602001Wyb7U10hovPGEj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532373557,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_C85moyuDg0vaVANecpf2jIeE","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/graph-metadata.json","offset":1,"limit":1000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/graph-metadata.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"schema_version\": 2,\n3:   \"skill_id\": \"sk-design\",\n4:   \"family\": \"sk-code\",\n5:   \"category\": \"design\",\n6:   \"importance_tier\": \"important\",\n7:   \"edges\": {\n8:     \"depends_on\": [],\n9:     \"enhances\": [\n10:       {\n11:         \"target\": \"sk-code\",\n12:         \"weight\": 0.6,\n13:         \"context\": \"Design output (direction, foundations, motion, audit findings, DESIGN.md) feeds sk-code implementation in the detected code surface\"\n14:       }\n15:     ],\n16:     \"siblings\": [\n17:       {\n18:         \"target\": \"sk-code\",\n19:         \"weight\": 0.5,\n20:         \"context\": \"Design-and-build peer in the sk-code family; sk-design owns taste, sk-code owns implementation\"\n21:       },\n22:       {\n23:         \"target\": \"sk-code-review\",\n24:         \"weight\": 0.4,\n25:         \"context\": \"Reviews implementation quality after design and build work converge\"\n26:       }\n27:     ],\n28:     \"conflicts_with\": [],\n29:     \"prerequisite_for\": []\n30:   },\n31:   \"manual\": {\n32:     \"depends_on\": [],\n33:     \"related_to\": [\n34:       \"sk-code\",\n35:       \"sk-code-review\",\n36:       \"mcp-figma\",\n37:       \"mcp-open-design\"\n38:     ]\n39:   },\n40:   \"domains\": [\n41:     \"design\",\n42:     \"ui-design\",\n43:     \"visual-design\",\n44:     \"design-systems\",\n45:     \"motion-design\",\n46:     \"design-audit\",\n47:     \"design-tokens\"\n48:   ],\n49:   \"intent_signals\": [\n50:     \"design family\",\n51:     \"sk-design\",\n52:     \"make it look good\",\n53:     \"interface design\",\n54:     \"visual direction\",\n55:     \"design tokens\",\n56:     \"typography\",\n57:     \"color palette\",\n58:     \"layout system\",\n59:     \"motion design\",\n60:     \"micro-interactions\",\n61:     \"design audit\",\n62:     \"accessibility audit\",\n63:     \"DESIGN.md\",\n64:     \"style reference\"\n65:   ],\n66:   \"derived\": {\n67:     \"trigger_phrases\": [\n68:       \"sk-design\",\n69:       \"design family\",\n70:       \"design router\",\n71:       \"make this look good\",\n72:       \"route design work\",\n73:       \"design tokens\",\n74:       \"motion design\",\n75:       \"design audit\",\n76:       \"DESIGN.md extraction\",\n77:       \"interface design\",\n78:       \"frontend design\",\n79:       \"visual design\",\n80:       \"make it look good\",\n81:       \"looks templated\",\n82:       \"redesign the ui\",\n83:       \"hero section\",\n84:       \"typography and palette\",\n85:       \"color palette\",\n86:       \"font pairing\",\n87:       \"ux quality checklist\",\n88:       \"give me N design variations\",\n89:       \"oklch palette\",\n90:       \"color token system\",\n91:       \"dark mode palette\",\n92:       \"typography scale\",\n93:       \"spacing system\",\n94:       \"responsive layout\",\n95:       \"animate this\",\n96:       \"micro-interactions\",\n97:       \"AnimatePresence\",\n98:       \"exit animation\",\n99:       \"reduced motion\",\n100:       \"morphing icons\",\n101:       \"motion performance\",\n102:       \"ui critique\",\n103:       \"accessibility audit\",\n104:       \"performance audit\",\n105:       \"anti-slop detection\",\n106:       \"production hardening\",\n107:       \"design quality score\",\n108:       \"P0 P1 design findings\",\n109:       \"extract design system\",\n110:       \"generate design.md\",\n111:       \"capture website css\",\n112:       \"design tokens from url\",\n113:       \"create design reference\",\n114:       \"design-to-markdown\",\n115:       \"extract design tokens\"\n116:     ],\n117:     \"key_topics\": [\n118:       \"sk-design\",\n119:       \"mode-registry\",\n120:       \"workflowMode\",\n121:       \"backendKind\",\n122:       \"reference-base\",\n123:       \"interface-mode\",\n124:       \"foundations-mode\",\n125:       \"motion-mode\",\n126:       \"audit-mode\",\n127:       \"md-generator-mode\",\n128:       \"shared-design-reference-base\",\n129:       \"anti-slop\",\n130:       \"design-token-vocabulary\",\n131:       \"cognitive-laws\"\n132:     ],\n133:     \"key_files\": [\n134:       \".opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md\",\n135:       \".opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json\"\n136:     ],\n137:     \"entities\": [\n138:       {\n139:         \"name\": \"sk-design\",\n140:         \"kind\": \"skill\",\n141:         \"path\": \".opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md\",\n142:         \"source\": \"derived\"\n143:       },\n144:       {\n145:         \"name\": \"mode-registry\",\n146:         \"kind\": \"config\",\n147:         \"path\": \".opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json\",\n148:         \"source\": \"derived\"\n149:       }\n150:     ],\n151:     \"causal_summary\": \"sk-design is the single public design skill that routes a request to one of five design modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) by workflowMode through mode-registry.json over a shared design reference base. The four doc-guidance modes cite the shared reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) for consistent vocabulary, while md-generator runs its own Playwright CSS-extraction backend (backendKind discriminates the two). The hub holds no per-mode design logic; every mode keeps its own judgment, examples, and verification in its packet, and all five route by hub membership so the advisor sees exactly one design identity.\",\n152:     \"source_docs\": [\n153:       \"SKILL.md\",\n154:       \"mode-registry.json\"\n155:     ],\n156:     \"created_at\": \"2026-06-25T00:00:00Z\",\n157:     \"last_updated_at\": \"2026-06-26T00:00:00Z\"\n158:   }\n159: }\n\n(End of file - total 159 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"schema_version\": 2,\n  \"skill_id\": \"sk-design\",\n  \"family\": \"sk-code\",\n  \"category\": \"design\",\n  \"importance_tier\": \"important\",\n  \"edges\": {\n    \"depends_on\": [],\n    \"enhances\": [\n      {\n        \"target\": \"sk-code\",\n        \"weight\": 0.6,\n        \"context\": \"Design output (direction, foundations, motion, audit findings, DESIGN.md) feeds sk-code implementation in the detected code surface\"\n      }\n    ],\n    \"siblings\": [\n      {\n        \"target\": \"sk-code\",\n        \"weight\": 0.5,\n        \"context\": \"Design-and-build peer in the sk-code family; sk-design owns taste, sk-code owns implementation\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/graph-metadata.json","text":"{\n  \"schema_version\": 2,\n  \"skill_id\": \"sk-design\",\n  \"family\": \"sk-code\",\n  \"category\": \"design\",\n  \"importance_tier\": \"important\",\n  \"edges\": {\n    \"depends_on\": [],\n    \"enhances\": [\n      {\n        \"target\": \"sk-code\",\n        \"weight\": 0.6,\n        \"context\": \"Design output (direction, foundations, motion, audit findings, DESIGN.md) feeds sk-code implementation in the detected code surface\"\n      }\n    ],\n    \"siblings\": [\n      {\n        \"target\": \"sk-code\",\n        \"weight\": 0.5,\n        \"context\": \"Design-and-build peer in the sk-code family; sk-design owns taste, sk-code owns implementation\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"target\": \"sk-code-review\",\n        \"weight\": 0.4,\n        \"context\": \"Reviews implementation quality after design and build work converge\"\n      }\n    ],\n    \"conflicts_with\": [],\n    \"prerequisite_for\": []\n  },\n  \"manual\": {\n    \"depends_on\": [],\n    \"related_to\": [\n      \"sk-code\",\n      \"sk-code-review\",\n      \"mcp-figma\",\n      \"mcp-open-design\"\n    ]\n  },\n  \"domains\": [\n    \"design\",\n    \"ui-design\",\n    \"visual-design\",\n    \"design-systems\",\n    \"motion-design\",\n    \"design-audit\",\n    \"design-tokens\"\n  ],\n  \"intent_signals\": [\n    \"design family\",\n    \"sk-design\",\n    \"make it look good\",\n    \"interface design\",\n    \"visual direction\",\n    \"design tokens\",\n    \"typography\",\n    \"color palette\",\n    \"layout system\",\n    \"motion design\",\n    \"micro-interactions\",\n    \"design audit\",\n    \"accessibility audit\",\n    \"DESIGN.md\",\n    \"style reference\"\n  ],\n  \"derived\": {\n    \"trigger_phrases\": [\n      \"sk-design\",\n      \"design family\",\n      \"design router\",\n      \"make this look good\",\n      \"route design work\",\n      \"design tokens\",\n      \"motion design\",\n      \"design audit\",\n      \"DESIGN.md extraction\",\n      \"interface design\",\n      \"frontend design\",\n      \"visual design\",\n      \"make it look good\",\n      \"looks templated\",\n      \"redesign the ui\",\n      \"hero section\",\n      \"typography and palette\",\n      \"color palette\",\n      \"font pairing\",\n      \"ux quality checklist\",\n      \"give me N design variations\",\n      \"oklch palette\",\n      \"color token system\",\n      \"dark mode palette\",\n      \"typography scale\",\n      \"spacing system\",\n      \"responsive layout\",\n      \"animate this\",\n      \"micro-interactions\",\n      \"AnimatePresence\",\n      \"exit animation\",\n      \"reduced motion\",\n      \"morphing icons\",\n      \"motion performance\",\n      \"ui critique\",\n      \"accessibility audit\",\n      \"performance audit\",\n      \"anti-slop detection\",\n      \"production hardening\",\n      \"design quality score\",\n      \"P0 P1 design findings\",\n      \"extract design system\",\n      \"generate design.md\",\n      \"capture website css\",\n      \"design tokens from url\",\n      \"create design reference\",\n      \"design-to-markdown\",\n      \"extract design tokens\"\n    ],\n    \"key_topics\": [\n      \"sk-design\",\n      \"mode-registry\",\n      \"workflowMode\",\n      \"backendKind\",\n      \"reference-base\",\n      \"interface-mode\",\n      \"foundations-mode\",\n      \"motion-mode\",\n      \"audit-mode\",\n      \"md-generator-mode\",\n      \"shared-design-reference-base\",\n      \"anti-slop\",\n      \"design-token-vocabulary\",\n      \"cognitive-laws\"\n    ],\n    \"key_files\": [\n      \".opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md\",\n      \".opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json\"\n    ],\n    \"entities\": [\n      {\n        \"name\": \"sk-design\",\n        \"kind\": \"skill\",\n        \"path\": \".opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md\",\n        \"source\": \"derived\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"mode-registry\",\n        \"kind\": \"config\",\n        \"path\": \".opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json\",\n        \"source\": \"derived\"\n      }\n    ],\n    \"causal_summary\": \"sk-design is the single public design skill that routes a request to one of five design modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) by workflowMode through mode-registry.json over a shared design reference base. The four doc-guidance modes cite the shared reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) for consistent vocabulary, while md-generator runs its own Playwright CSS-extraction backend (backendKind discriminates the two). The hub holds no per-mode design logic; every mode keeps its own judgment, examples, and verification in its packet, and all five route by hub membership so the advisor sees exactly one design identity.\",\n    \"source_docs\": [\n      \"SKILL.md\",\n      \"mode-registry.json\"\n    ],\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-06-25T00:00:00Z\",\n    \"last_updated_at\": \"2026-06-26T00:00:00Z\"\n  }\n}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":159,"totalLines":159,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/graph-metadata.json","time":{"start":1782532373552,"end":1782532373556}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_053371a57b5009f1016a3f4915780481918c7f244645802251"}},"id":"prt_f07357c21001pjQRUnQh0xMlJm","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07355602001Wyb7U10hovPGEj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532373580,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_ihPZUeylIjZPwxFOGnHgu1sZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"audit|design-audit|workflowMode|routingClass|advisorRouting","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design","include":"*.{json,md}"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/manual_testing_playbook/09--cluster/009-oklch-clustering.md:\n  Line 71: For a deeper stability audit, run `cd backend && npx vitest run cluster` with `--reporter verbose` to see each unit test case output. Inspect a single `colorToken` by running `node -e \"const t = require('./<--output>/tokens.json'); console.log(JSON.stringify(t.colorTokens[0].stability, null, 2))\"` to confirm the `signals` array explains the classification (e.g., `pages: 100%`, `text/border usage`, `css-var: --color-brand`). Cross-check that tokens with `cssVariableNames` populated are never classified as L4.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/manual_testing_playbook/07--report/007-report-generation.md:\n  Line 24: This scenario validates report, preview, and proof generation for `REPORT-001`. It focuses on confirming `report-gen.ts`, `preview-gen.ts`, and `proof.ts` each accept a `tokens.json` (and where applicable a `DESIGN.md` or source URL) as input and produce valid HTML/visual artifacts with no errors. The three scripts cover distinct review needs: a token-to-section HTML report for provenance auditing, a CSS visual preview that renders the design system as styled HTML, and a fidelity proof that compares live extraction against the token set.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/README.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"The single advisor-routable design skill: a hub that routes to five design modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator).\"\n\n  Line 6:   - \"ui design interface foundations motion audit\"\n\n  Line 13: > Make a UI look custom and intentional instead of templated, across direction, system, motion, audit and CSS extraction.\n\n  Line 21: | **Use it for** | Distinctive UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, design systems, motion, quality audit and live-site CSS extraction. |\n\n  Line 24: | **Produces** | Design direction and tokens, motion specs, an audit with scores or a Style Reference DESIGN.md. |\n\n  Line 65: | `design-audit` | Design QA: accessibility, performance, responsive, anti-slop and quality scoring. |\n\n  Line 78: Reach for sk-design when output looks generic and needs taste, when a visual system or motion language needs designing, when a UI needs an accessibility and anti-slop audit or when a live site's design system needs extracting. For the implementation itself, use `sk-code`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/assets/register_card.md:\n  Line 54: - audit: audit-severity weighting\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/design_token_vocabulary.md:\n  Line 24: Keep token language consistent when design children discuss visual systems, so a term means the same thing across interface, foundations, motion, and audit work.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md:\n  Line 28: Set the register at the start of any design task, before the mode-specific workflow runs. Each mode (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) reads the register and applies the dial settings for the chosen posture. The register is shared vocabulary, not a sixth mode and not a replacement for mode workflows.\n\n  Line 78: - **audit** reads the audit-severity dial so a finding is weighted by posture: distinctiveness for Brand, affordance and consistency for Product.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/anti_slop_principles.md:\n  Line 28: Cite these principles during direction critique, token review, motion planning, and audit findings. Children own the detailed workflow that applies them.\n\n  Line 60: - `audit` uses it as slop-detection vocabulary.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/cognitive_laws.md:\n  Line 3: description: Eight shared cognitive laws that design children can cite when shaping hierarchy, interaction, motion, and audit rationale.\n\n  Line 16: Eight shared cognitive laws that design children cite as concise rationale for hierarchy, interaction, motion, and audit decisions.\n\n  Line 24: Give design children a compact, citable rationale set for making and auditing design choices. These laws are shared vocabulary, not a complete UX research method.\n\n  Line 28: Reference a law by name when justifying a hierarchy, interaction, timing, or audit decision. Children own the workflow that applies each law.\n\n  Line 71: - `audit` cites them when explaining design-quality findings.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/feature_catalog/05--report-preview/report-preview.md:\n  Line 20: Renders visual artifacts from a validated DESIGN.md + tokens.json pair. Three scripts cover distinct review needs: a token-to-section HTML report for provenance auditing, a CSS visual preview that renders the design system as styled HTML, and a fidelity proof that compares live extraction against the token set. These outputs serve human review, team handoff, and stakeholder sign-off. All three scripts take `tokens.json` as their first argument and write to an output directory.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/graph-metadata.json:\n  Line 13:         \"context\": \"Design output (direction, foundations, motion, audit findings, DESIGN.md) feeds sk-code implementation in the detected code surface\"\n\n  Line 46:     \"design-audit\",\n\n  Line 61:     \"design audit\",\n\n  Line 62:     \"accessibility audit\",\n\n  Line 75:       \"design audit\",\n\n  Line 103:       \"accessibility audit\",\n\n  Line 104:       \"performance audit\",\n\n  Line 120:       \"workflowMode\",\n\n  Line 126:       \"audit-mode\",\n\n  Line 151:     \"causal_summary\": \"sk-design is the single public design skill that routes a request to one of five design modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) by workflowMode through mode-registry.json over a shared design reference base. The four doc-guidance modes cite the shared reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) for consistent vocabulary, while md-generator runs its own Playwright CSS-extraction backend (backendKind discriminates the two). The hub holds no per-mode design logic; every mode keeps its own judgment, examples, and verification in its packet, and all five route by hub membership so the advisor sees exactly one design identity.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json:\n  Line 4:   \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All five modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n\n  Line 6:     \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n\n  Line 9:   \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n\n  Line 10:     \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n\n  Line 16:       \"workflowMode\": \"interface\",\n\n  Line 22:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n\n  Line 23:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n\n  Line 28:       \"workflowMode\": \"foundations\",\n\n  Line 34:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n\n  Line 35:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n\n  Line 40:       \"workflowMode\": \"motion\",\n\n  Line 46:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n\n  Line 47:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n\n  Line 52:       \"workflowMode\": \"audit\",\n\n  Line 54:       \"packet\": \"design-audit\",\n\n  Line 55:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\",\n\n  Line 57:       \"aliases\": [\"design audit\", \"ui critique\", \"accessibility audit\", \"performance audit\", \"anti-slop detection\", \"production hardening\", \"design quality score\", \"P0 P1 design findings\"],\n\n  Line 58:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n\n  Line 59:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n\n  Line 60:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\"\n\n  Line 64:       \"workflowMode\": \"md-generator\",\n\n  Line 70:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n\n  Line 71:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/references/corpus_map.md:\n  Line 27: This child owns static systems. It does not own broad interface direction (`interface`), motion build (`motion`), or review/scoring (`audit`).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:\n  Line 15: `foundations` owns the static visual system of the `sk-design` family: color, type, spacing, layout, hierarchy, grids, responsive adaptation, theming, and token vocabulary. It turns a visual direction into a coherent system, or audits a system proposal before implementation.\n\n  Line 38: - The task is a review, score, accessibility audit, or production-hardening report. Use `audit`.\n\n  Line 51: - `audit` when the finished visual system needs scoring and release hardening.\n\n  Line 326: - `audit` scores the result for accessibility, performance, responsiveness, theming, and anti-slop risk.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:\n  Line 18: - Five nested mode packets: `design-interface`, `design-foundations`, `design-motion`, `design-audit` and `design-md-generator`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/assets/motion_performance_failure_card.md:\n  Line 16: Check a motion build against this card before handing it off. Each row is a pattern that drops frames, drains battery or stutters under load. This is a build-side card for catching the failure while you write the motion, not a release audit. Severity scoring and findings reports for motion performance belong to the `audit` mode. The deeper technique guidance lives in `references/performance_reduced_motion.md`.\n\n  Line 60: A build that clears every box is ready for the `audit` mode to score. A box left unchecked is a frame-rate defect to fix before handoff, not a finding to defer.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md:\n  Line 3: description: Snippet-level accessibility fixes the audit report cites by reference. Accessible names, keyboard, focus and dialogs, semantics, forms and errors, live-region announcements, contrast and motion.\n\n  Line 16: This is a fix-reference card, not a workflow. When the audit files an accessibility finding, it points the owner here for the concrete shape of the fix, then `sk-code` makes the change once the user accepts it. The audit cites these snippets, it does not apply them. The priority order, the user-impact framing, plus the contrast and touch numbers all live in `../references/accessibility_performance.md`. This card is the snippet layer underneath that reference: the smallest correct change for each common defect.\n\n  Line 163: 1. The audit files the accessibility finding with its evidence and severity from `../references/audit_contract.md`.\n\n  Line 166: 4. The audit stops at naming the fix. Applying it is `sk-code` work after the user accepts the recommendation.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/assets/interface_preflight_card.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"A mechanical fill-in pass/fail card to run on a built or planned interface before calling it done. Covers hero, bento, eyebrow and meta-label sweep, button contrast, breakpoint overflow, real imagery, copy audit, motion motivation, reduced motion, mobile collapse, and the AI-tell sweep. Every box is binary.\"\n\n  Line 123: | Copy self-audit run over every visible string, every flagged or grammatically broken string rewritten | [ ] |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/README.md:\n  Line 108: | `audit` | Scores the finished system for accessibility, responsiveness, theming and anti-slop risk |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/assets/animate_presence_checklist.md:\n  Line 97: Report any open fail in the audit findings format from `references/animate_presence_patterns.md` Section 7, for example `components/modal.tsx:42 - [exit-requires-wrapper] conditional motion.div is not wrapped`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md:\n  Line 2: title: design-audit\n\n  Line 5:   - \"design audit\"\n\n  Line 7:   - \"accessibility audit\"\n\n  Line 14: # design-audit\n\n  Line 25: | **Invoke with** | `audit design`, `critique UI`, `design review`, `accessibility audit`, `looks AI-generated` |\n\n  Line 37: `audit` closes that gap. It walks a surface against accessibility, performance, responsive, theming and anti-slop checks, names each defect with evidence and ranks it by user impact. It is the critic in the `sk-design` family, the sibling that judges rather than creates.\n\n  Line 41: `audit` produces a findings-first report: concrete findings come first, then a five-dimension score that summarizes them. Each finding carries evidence, user impact, a recommended direction and an owner. The mode reviews and routes, it does not implement. Accepted fixes go to `sk-code`, while direction goes to `interface`, tokens go to `foundations` and choreography goes to `motion`. If you want a new visual direction instead of a critique, reach for `interface`.\n\n  Line 47: **Step 1: Invoke it.** Routing keywords like `audit design` or `accessibility audit` reach this mode through `sk-design`. You can also point it at a target directly.\n\n  Line 49: **Step 2: Run the audit.**\n\n  Line 60: python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md --type readme\n\n  Line 69: The audit runs the same shape every time. It resolves the surface to one concrete target, then states what evidence is available and what is missing, so a visual claim never rests on evidence that was never gathered. Findings come next, each with evidence and a severity, ordered worst-first. Only then does the five-dimension score appear, as a summary of the findings rather than a replacement for them. The report closes by mapping every finding to an owner and naming the residual risk if the surface ships as-is.\n\n  Line 73: Before scoring, the audit reads the Brand-vs-Product register. That one call sets the audit-severity dial. On a Brand surface, a generic-but-functional result is a real finding, so blandness scores against Anti-Patterns. On a Product surface, an expressive-but-unclear result is a real finding, so theatrics score against accessibility and consistency. The same observation routes to opposite verdicts depending on posture, which is why the register is resolved first.\n\n  Line 85: Reach for `audit` when you need a verdict on an existing or planned surface: a release-readiness check, an accessibility gate, a slop review or a production-hardening pass. Use it when someone says a design \"looks AI-generated\" and you need to prove it with named tells. Skip it when you want to invent a direction, build a token system or write motion, since those belong to the sibling modes.\n\n  Line 91: | `interface` | Owns the direction changes the audit recommends |\n\n  Line 105: | README structure | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md --type readme` reports zero issues |\n\n  Line 114: | [`references/audit_contract.md`](./references/audit_contract.md) | Severity model, `/20` scoring contract and findings schema |\n\n  Line 122: | [`assets/audit_report_template.md`](./assets/audit_report_template.md) | Fill-in findings-first report skeleton with the five-dimension score |\n\n  Line 124: | [`../shared/register.md`](../shared/register.md) | The Brand-vs-Product register that sets the audit-severity dial |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md:\n  Line 3: description: Fill-in audit report skeleton. Findings-first, with a five-dimension score out of 20, an AI-default verdict, P0-P3 issues, owner mapping and evidence caveats.\n\n  Line 5:   - \"audit report template\"\n\n  Line 6:   - \"design audit report\"\n\n  Line 7:   - \"fill in audit report\"\n\n  Line 16: Copy this skeleton and fill it in for one audited surface. Findings come first, the score is a summary of the findings, and the deliverable stops at reporting. The audit names what is wrong and who owns the fix. It does not implement the fix, which belongs to `sk-code` after the user accepts the recommendations. Severity and scoring rules live in `../references/audit_contract.md`. Resolve the surface register before scoring so dimension weighting is correct: `../../shared/assets/register_card.md`.\n\n  Line 26: | Surface audited (page / route / file) | `__________` |\n\n  Line 32: Register sets the audit-severity weighting. Brand weights distinctiveness and voice, so a generic-but-functional surface is a real finding. Product weights affordance, accessibility and consistency, so an expressive-but-unclear surface is a real finding.\n\n  Line 52: List findings before the score. Order P0, then P1, then P2, then P3. Use the findings schema from `../references/audit_contract.md`. One finding per issue. Do not bury a P0 under polish.\n\n  Line 114: Score each dimension 0 to 4 from the findings above. The score summarizes the findings, it does not replace them. Full rubric is in `../references/audit_contract.md`.\n\n  Line 131: Group the findings by who owns the fix. The audit routes work, it does not do the work.\n\n  Line 156: Close honestly. State what the audit could not verify and what would close the gap.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/README.md:\n  Line 80: Before the token system, the skill sets one posture and reads the brief into three working values. The shared [`../shared/register.md`](../shared/register.md) decides whether the surface is a Brand surface (design IS the product) or a Product surface (design SERVES the product), which gates density, motion budget, color dosage, copy register, anti-slop strictness, and audit severity. Then [`references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md`](./references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md) reads the brief into the VARIANCE, MOTION, and DENSITY dials within that posture. The dials are the agent's internal calibration stated in a one-line Design Read, never a pick-a-vibe menu surfaced to the user.\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"audit|design-audit|workflowMode|routingClass|advisorRouting","time":{"start":1782532373568,"end":1782532373579}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_053371a57b5009f1016a3f491578108191a699e10b59291ca2"}},"id":"prt_f07357c32001f1Y7ueWgenRfLS","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07355602001Wyb7U10hovPGEj"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782532374060,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f07357e29001OxgNCrA7IPdi1g","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"e71ed84a96990e75b9a129ea446b8dd65bdb4226","messageID":"msg_f07355602001Wyb7U10hovPGEj","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":147284,"input":11914,"output":187,"reasoning":15,"cache":{"write":0,"read":135168}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782532375786,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f073584e9001BNHvsTRPOYW5Fc","messageID":"msg_f07357f67001n7NjQU25tkP4eq","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","snapshot":"e71ed84a96990e75b9a129ea446b8dd65bdb4226","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1782532396015,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f073596320010BF7l1x3IOQses","messageID":"msg_f07357f67001n7NjQU25tkP4eq","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","type":"text","text":"The audit mode is already fairly mature: it has an evidence model, report template, a11y quick-fix asset, AI-tell catalog, transform routing, and hardening matrix. The remaining research will focus on practical improvements that reduce audit friction and improve routing/report consistency without turning audit into an implementation skill.","time":{"start":1782532380210,"end":1782532396013},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_041b0478a3b44386016a3f491c300c8191aad6f93e3c4b2588","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532396072,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_zVw0ZlxcJNUpMeVebfamTgis","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/01--score/002-findings-first-score.md","offset":1,"limit":900},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/01--score/002-findings-first-score.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Findings-First Score Scenario\n3: description: Manual scenario verifying severity-ordered findings and the five-dimension /20 design audit score.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"test design audit score\"\n6:   - \"test findings first audit\"\n7:   - \"audit score scenario\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: reference\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: expected_intent: AUDIT_CONTRACT\n12: expected_resources:\n13:   - references/audit_contract.md\n14: ---\n15: \n16: **Exact prompt**\n17: \n18: ```\n19: Audit this dashboard for release readiness and give me a design quality score with severity-ranked P0-P1 findings.\n20: ```\n21: \n22: # AUDIT-SCORE-001 | Findings-First Score\n23: \n24: ## Target\n25: \n26: Supply one concrete dashboard or app UI artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot: a source file path, a rendered URL, a screenshot, or a design plan. If no UI target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\"; do not invent UI evidence.\n27: \n28: ## Prompt\n29: \n30: `Audit <TARGET> for release readiness and give me a design quality score.`\n31: \n32: ## Expected Process\n33: \n34: 1. Route to `audit`.\n35: 2. Load `references/audit_contract.md`.\n36: 3. Produce P0-P3 findings before summary.\n37: 4. Score accessibility, performance, responsive design, theming, and anti-patterns out of 4 each.\n38: \n39: ## Pass Criteria\n40: \n41: - Findings are severity ordered.\n42: - Every finding has evidence, impact, recommendation, and owner.\n43: - Score totals to `/20` with a rating band.\n44: - Evidence gaps are named instead of hidden.\n\n(End of file - total 44 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Findings-First Score Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying severity-ordered findings and the five-dimension /20 design audit score.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test design audit score\"\n  - \"test findings first audit\"\n  - \"audit score scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: AUDIT_CONTRACT\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/audit_contract.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nAudit this dashboard for release readiness and give me a design quality score with severity-ranked P0-P1 findings.\n```","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/01--score/002-findings-first-score.md","text":"---\ntitle: Findings-First Score Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying severity-ordered findings and the five-dimension /20 design audit score.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test design audit score\"\n  - \"test findings first audit\"\n  - \"audit score scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: AUDIT_CONTRACT\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/audit_contract.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nAudit this dashboard for release readiness and give me a design quality score with severity-ranked P0-P1 findings.\n```\n\n# AUDIT-SCORE-001 | Findings-First Score\n\n## Target\n\nSupply one concrete dashboard or app UI artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot: a source file path, a rendered URL, a screenshot, or a design plan. If no UI target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\"; do not invent UI evidence.\n\n## Prompt\n\n`Audit <TARGET> for release readiness and give me a design quality score.`\n\n## Expected Process\n\n1. Route to `audit`.\n2. Load `references/audit_contract.md`.\n3. Produce P0-P3 findings before summary.\n4. Score accessibility, performance, responsive design, theming, and anti-patterns out of 4 each.\n\n## Pass Criteria\n\n- Findings are severity ordered.\n- Every finding has evidence, impact, recommendation, and owner.\n- Score totals to `/20` with a rating band.\n- Evidence gaps are named instead of hidden.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":44,"totalLines":44,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/01--score/002-findings-first-score.md","time":{"start":1782532396061,"end":1782532396070}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_041b0478a3b44386016a3f492bfc988191b3e80d98e35e07a4"}},"id":"prt_f0735d3f1001U25M2TLsdGCr0n","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07357f67001n7NjQU25tkP4eq"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532396108,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_sdUzgW7j5lx038DtOsdRq3Fg","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/01--score/004-evidence-capture.md","offset":1,"limit":900},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/01--score/004-evidence-capture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Evidence Capture Scenario\n3: description: Manual scenario verifying target resolution, the three evidence types and honest confirmed-or-inferred labeling when evidence is out of reach.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"test evidence capture\"\n6:   - \"test inferred evidence label\"\n7:   - \"evidence capture scenario\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: reference\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: expected_intent: EVIDENCE_CAPTURE\n12: expected_resources:\n13:   - references/evidence_capture.md\n14: ---\n15: \n16: **Exact prompt**\n17: \n18: ```\n19: I only have a screenshot of this screen and no source target. Walk the evidence and tell me what you can confirm versus infer.\n20: ```\n21: \n22: # AUDIT-SCORE-003 | Evidence Capture\n23: \n24: ## Target\n25: \n26: Supply one concrete artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot where some evidence is reachable and some is not, for example a screenshot of a surface whose source you cannot open. If no target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\". Do not invent source, rendered or scan evidence to fill the gap.\n27: \n28: ## Prompt\n29: \n30: `Audit <TARGET>. I can give you a screenshot but not the source. Tell me what you can confirm and what you can only infer.`\n31: \n32: ## Expected Process\n33: \n34: 1. Load `references/evidence_capture.md` and `references/audit_contract.md`.\n35: 2. Resolve the request to one concrete target, preferring a source path over a dev-server URL when both name the same surface.\n36: 3. State the resolved target and the evidence available versus the evidence missing at the top of the report.\n37: 4. Label every finding confirmed when read from real evidence, or inferred when it names what would confirm it.\n38: \n39: ## Pass Criteria\n40: \n41: - The resolved target is stated before any finding, and an unresolvable target is escalated rather than guessed.\n42: - Each finding cites at least one of the three evidence types: source, rendered or design-artifact.\n43: - A screenshot-only finding is labeled inferred and names the source that would confirm it.\n44: - No browser scan, overlay or detector is claimed unless it actually ran, and a missing scan is reported as a fallback signal rather than a clean pass.\n45: - An inferred finding keeps its inferred label all the way into the score, never quietly upgraded to a fact.\n\n(End of file - total 45 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Evidence Capture Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying target resolution, the three evidence types and honest confirmed-or-inferred labeling when evidence is out of reach.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test evidence capture\"\n  - \"test inferred evidence label\"\n  - \"evidence capture scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: EVIDENCE_CAPTURE\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/evidence_capture.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nI only have a screenshot of this screen and no source target. Walk the evidence and tell me what you can confirm versus infer.\n```","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/01--score/004-evidence-capture.md","text":"---\ntitle: Evidence Capture Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying target resolution, the three evidence types and honest confirmed-or-inferred labeling when evidence is out of reach.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test evidence capture\"\n  - \"test inferred evidence label\"\n  - \"evidence capture scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: EVIDENCE_CAPTURE\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/evidence_capture.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nI only have a screenshot of this screen and no source target. Walk the evidence and tell me what you can confirm versus infer.\n```\n\n# AUDIT-SCORE-003 | Evidence Capture\n\n## Target\n\nSupply one concrete artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot where some evidence is reachable and some is not, for example a screenshot of a surface whose source you cannot open. If no target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\". Do not invent source, rendered or scan evidence to fill the gap.\n\n## Prompt\n\n`Audit <TARGET>. I can give you a screenshot but not the source. Tell me what you can confirm and what you can only infer.`\n\n## Expected Process\n\n1. Load `references/evidence_capture.md` and `references/audit_contract.md`.\n2. Resolve the request to one concrete target, preferring a source path over a dev-server URL when both name the same surface.\n3. State the resolved target and the evidence available versus the evidence missing at the top of the report.\n4. Label every finding confirmed when read from real evidence, or inferred when it names what would confirm it.\n\n## Pass Criteria\n\n- The resolved target is stated before any finding, and an unresolvable target is escalated rather than guessed.\n- Each finding cites at least one of the three evidence types: source, rendered or design-artifact.\n- A screenshot-only finding is labeled inferred and names the source that would confirm it.\n- No browser scan, overlay or detector is claimed unless it actually ran, and a missing scan is reported as a fallback signal rather than a clean pass.\n- An inferred finding keeps its inferred label all the way into the score, never quietly upgraded to a fact.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":45,"totalLines":45,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/01--score/004-evidence-capture.md","time":{"start":1782532396102,"end":1782532396107}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_041b0478a3b44386016a3f492bfca88191824a956502e82570"}},"id":"prt_f0735d4340012od4VNHzMB9QgF","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07357f67001n7NjQU25tkP4eq"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532396162,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_H2kq5q9WzHAGOOhEKufu7Dh4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md","offset":1,"limit":900},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Accessibility And Performance Gate Scenario\n3: description: Manual scenario verifying accessibility and performance audit behavior for release blocking issues.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"test accessibility audit\"\n6:   - \"test performance gate\"\n7:   - \"a11y performance scenario\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: reference\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: expected_intent: ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE\n12: expected_resources:\n13:   - references/accessibility_performance.md\n14: ---\n15: \n16: **Exact prompt**\n17: \n18: ```\n19: Check this modal for accessibility and performance before release: keyboard, focus, contrast, WCAG, and any animation jank.\n20: ```\n21: \n22: # AUDIT-A11Y-001 | Accessibility And Performance Gate\n23: \n24: ## Target\n25: \n26: Supply one concrete interactive component artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot (for example a modal and animated drawer): a source file path, a rendered URL, or a screenshot. If no component target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\"; do not invent rendered or measured evidence.\n27: \n28: ## Prompt\n29: \n30: `Review <TARGET> for accessibility and performance issues before release.`\n31: \n32: ## Expected Process\n33: \n34: 1. Load `references/accessibility_performance.md` and `references/audit_contract.md`.\n35: 2. Check accessible names, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms/announcements, contrast, motion, and performance.\n36: 3. Severity-rank release blockers.\n37: \n38: ## Pass Criteria\n39: \n40: - Flags missing names, focus traps, keyboard traps, or contrast failures as P0/P1 as appropriate.\n41: - Identifies motion jank risks with concrete property/mechanism alternatives.\n42: - Distinguishes measured evidence from static risk.\n43: - Maps motion repair to `motion` and implementation to `sk-code`.\n44: - Uses the current Core Web Vital Interaction to Next Paint (INP), not the deprecated First Input Delay (FID), matching the `references/corpus_map.md` modernization guard.\n\n(End of file - total 44 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Accessibility And Performance Gate Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying accessibility and performance audit behavior for release blocking issues.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test accessibility audit\"\n  - \"test performance gate\"\n  - \"a11y performance scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/accessibility_performance.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nCheck this modal for accessibility and performance before release: keyboard, focus, contrast, WCAG, and any animation jank.\n```","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md","text":"---\ntitle: Accessibility And Performance Gate Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying accessibility and performance audit behavior for release blocking issues.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test accessibility audit\"\n  - \"test performance gate\"\n  - \"a11y performance scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: ACCESSIBILITY_PERFORMANCE\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/accessibility_performance.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nCheck this modal for accessibility and performance before release: keyboard, focus, contrast, WCAG, and any animation jank.\n```\n\n# AUDIT-A11Y-001 | Accessibility And Performance Gate\n\n## Target\n\nSupply one concrete interactive component artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot (for example a modal and animated drawer): a source file path, a rendered URL, or a screenshot. If no component target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\"; do not invent rendered or measured evidence.\n\n## Prompt\n\n`Review <TARGET> for accessibility and performance issues before release.`\n\n## Expected Process\n\n1. Load `references/accessibility_performance.md` and `references/audit_contract.md`.\n2. Check accessible names, keyboard, focus, semantics, forms/announcements, contrast, motion, and performance.\n3. Severity-rank release blockers.\n\n## Pass Criteria\n\n- Flags missing names, focus traps, keyboard traps, or contrast failures as P0/P1 as appropriate.\n- Identifies motion jank risks with concrete property/mechanism alternatives.\n- Distinguishes measured evidence from static risk.\n- Maps motion repair to `motion` and implementation to `sk-code`.\n- Uses the current Core Web Vital Interaction to Next Paint (INP), not the deprecated First Input Delay (FID), matching the `references/corpus_map.md` modernization guard.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":44,"totalLines":44,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/02--a11y-performance/006-accessibility-performance-gate.md","time":{"start":1782532396157,"end":1782532396161}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_041b0478a3b44386016a3f492bfcb08191815cabf4add2f2c6"}},"id":"prt_f0735d449001L4zxOmsS1AUwqx","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07357f67001n7NjQU25tkP4eq"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532396283,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Rz0O0iTpZfr9u3rZnPGVbTIq","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md","offset":1,"limit":1000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: design-audit\n3: description: \"The sk-design QA and critique mode that reviews built or planned interfaces, files severity-ranked findings and scores five dimensions out of 20.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"design audit\"\n6:   - \"critique UI\"\n7:   - \"accessibility audit\"\n8:   - \"design quality score\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # design-audit\n15: \n16: > Tells you exactly what is wrong with an interface, how bad each issue is and who owns the fix, without touching the code.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. AT A GLANCE\n21: \n22: | Aspect | What you get |\n23: |---|---|\n24: | **Use it for** | Reviewing a UI for accessibility, performance, responsive, theming and AI-slop problems |\n25: | **Invoke with** | `audit design`, `critique UI`, `design review`, `accessibility audit`, `looks AI-generated` |\n26: | **Works on** | A source file, a rendered URL, a screenshot or a design plan |\n27: | **Produces** | Severity-ranked P0-P3 findings, a five-dimension `/20` score and an owner map |\n28: \n29: ---\n30: \n31: ## 2. OVERVIEW\n32: \n33: ### Why This Mode Exists\n34: \n35: An interface can pass every automated scan and still fail real users: a focus trap a mouse never hits, a cream body background that screams machine-generated, a form that loses work when the network drops. Those gaps hide in the space between a green check and what a person actually experiences. Without a structured review, they ship.\n36: \n37: `audit` closes that gap. It walks a surface against accessibility, performance, responsive, theming and anti-slop checks, names each defect with evidence and ranks it by user impact. It is the critic in the `sk-design` family, the sibling that judges rather than creates.\n38: \n39: ### What It Does\n40: \n41: `audit` produces a findings-first report: concrete findings come first, then a five-dimension score that summarizes them. Each finding carries evidence, user impact, a recommended direction and an owner. The mode reviews and routes, it does not implement. Accepted fixes go to `sk-code`, while direction goes to `interface`, tokens go to `foundations` and choreography goes to `motion`. If you want a new visual direction instead of a critique, reach for `interface`.\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ## 3. QUICK START\n46: \n47: **Step 1: Invoke it.** Routing keywords like `audit design` or `accessibility audit` reach this mode through `sk-design`. You can also point it at a target directly.\n48: \n49: **Step 2: Run the audit.**\n50: \n51: ```text\n52: Audit src/pages/checkout.tsx for release readiness and give me a design quality score.\n53: ```\n54: \n55: A findings-first report ordered P0, P1, P2, P3, then a `/20` score with a rating band and an owner map.\n56: \n57: **Step 3: Verify the docs.**\n58: \n59: ```bash\n60: python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md --type readme\n61: ```\n62: \n63: Reports zero issues.\n64: \n65: ---\n66: \n67: ## 4. HOW IT WORKS\n68: \n69: The audit runs the same shape every time. It resolves the surface to one concrete target, then states what evidence is available and what is missing, so a visual claim never rests on evidence that was never gathered. Findings come next, each with evidence and a severity, ordered worst-first. Only then does the five-dimension score appear, as a summary of the findings rather than a replacement for them. The report closes by mapping every finding to an owner and naming the residual risk if the surface ships as-is.\n70: \n71: ### Register-Gated Severity\n72: \n73: Before scoring, the audit reads the Brand-vs-Product register. That one call sets the audit-severity dial. On a Brand surface, a generic-but-functional result is a real finding, so blandness scores against Anti-Patterns. On a Product surface, an expressive-but-unclear result is a real finding, so theatrics score against accessibility and consistency. The same observation routes to opposite verdicts depending on posture, which is why the register is resolved first.\n74: \n75: ### The AI-Tell Catalog\n76: \n77: The anti-patterns dimension leans on a model-specific tell catalog. A ghost-card border plus shadow, over-rounded cards, a diagonal stripe background, an image-hover transform, a cream body background: each is a structural pattern a generator reaches for by reflex, turned into a checkable rule. One isolated tell is polish. Three or more on one surface is the dimension failing.\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ## 5. INTEGRATION & NAVIGATION\n82: \n83: ### When To Use This Mode\n84: \n85: Reach for `audit` when you need a verdict on an existing or planned surface: a release-readiness check, an accessibility gate, a slop review or a production-hardening pass. Use it when someone says a design \"looks AI-generated\" and you need to prove it with named tells. Skip it when you want to invent a direction, build a token system or write motion, since those belong to the sibling modes.\n86: \n87: ### Related Skills\n88: \n89: | Skill | Relationship |\n90: |---|---|\n91: | `interface` | Owns the direction changes the audit recommends |\n92: | `foundations` | Owns color, type, layout, responsive and theming token fixes |\n93: | `motion` | Owns motion choreography and reduced-motion fixes |\n94: | `sk-code` | Implements every accepted fix after the user approves it |\n95: \n96: ---\n97: \n98: ## 6. VERIFICATION\n99: \n100: The mode ships a manual testing playbook. Each scenario runs a prompt against the live mode and its on-disk references, then records PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL or SKIP.\n101: \n102: | Check | Result |\n103: |---|---|\n104: | Manual playbook | Run the scenarios in [`manual_testing_playbook/`](./manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md). Release is ready when all PASS or SKIP only for a missing target |\n105: | README structure | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md --type readme` reports zero issues |\n106: \n107: ---\n108: \n109: ## 7. RELATED DOCUMENTS\n110: \n111: | Document | Purpose |\n112: |---|---|\n113: | [`SKILL.md`](./SKILL.md) | Runtime instructions and routing logic |\n114: | [`references/audit_contract.md`](./references/audit_contract.md) | Severity model, `/20` scoring contract and findings schema |\n115: | [`references/accessibility_performance.md`](./references/accessibility_performance.md) | Accessibility and performance checks with pass and fail numbers |\n116: | [`references/critique_hardening.md`](./references/critique_hardening.md) | Holistic critique, cognitive load, personas and polish |\n117: | [`references/anti_patterns_production.md`](./references/anti_patterns_production.md) | Anti-slop signals, theming drift, copy clarity and production details |\n118: | [`references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md`](./references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md) | Model-specific AI tells turned into checkable P0-P3 findings |\n119: | [`references/transform_remediation.md`](./references/transform_remediation.md) | Register-gated bolder, quieter and distill verbs mapped to findings and owners |\n120: | [`references/evidence_capture.md`](./references/evidence_capture.md) | Target resolution, the three evidence types and confirmed-or-inferred labeling |\n121: | [`references/hardening_edge_cases.md`](./references/hardening_edge_cases.md) | Production-readiness matrix of extreme inputs, errors, concurrency and i18n |\n122: | [`assets/audit_report_template.md`](./assets/audit_report_template.md) | Fill-in findings-first report skeleton with the five-dimension score |\n123: | [`assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md`](./assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md) | Snippet-level accessibility fixes the report cites by reference |\n124: | [`../shared/register.md`](../shared/register.md) | The Brand-vs-Product register that sets the audit-severity dial |\n\n(End of file - total 124 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: design-audit\ndescription: \"The sk-design QA and critique mode that reviews built or planned interfaces, files severity-ranked findings and scores five dimensions out of 20.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"design audit\"\n  - \"critique UI\"\n  - \"accessibility audit\"\n  - \"design quality score\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# design-audit\n\n> Tells you exactly what is wrong with an interface, how bad each issue is and who owns the fix, without touching the code.\n\n---\n\n## 1. AT A GLANCE","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md","text":"---\ntitle: design-audit\ndescription: \"The sk-design QA and critique mode that reviews built or planned interfaces, files severity-ranked findings and scores five dimensions out of 20.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"design audit\"\n  - \"critique UI\"\n  - \"accessibility audit\"\n  - \"design quality score\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# design-audit\n\n> Tells you exactly what is wrong with an interface, how bad each issue is and who owns the fix, without touching the code.\n\n---\n\n## 1. AT A GLANCE\n\n| Aspect | What you get |\n|---|---|\n| **Use it for** | Reviewing a UI for accessibility, performance, responsive, theming and AI-slop problems |\n| **Invoke with** | `audit design`, `critique UI`, `design review`, `accessibility audit`, `looks AI-generated` |\n| **Works on** | A source file, a rendered URL, a screenshot or a design plan |\n| **Produces** | Severity-ranked P0-P3 findings, a five-dimension `/20` score and an owner map |\n\n---\n\n## 2. OVERVIEW\n\n### Why This Mode Exists\n\nAn interface can pass every automated scan and still fail real users: a focus trap a mouse never hits, a cream body background that screams machine-generated, a form that loses work when the network drops. Those gaps hide in the space between a green check and what a person actually experiences. Without a structured review, they ship.\n\n`audit` closes that gap. It walks a surface against accessibility, performance, responsive, theming and anti-slop checks, names each defect with evidence and ranks it by user impact. It is the critic in the `sk-design` family, the sibling that judges rather than creates.\n\n### What It Does\n\n`audit` produces a findings-first report: concrete findings come first, then a five-dimension score that summarizes them. Each finding carries evidence, user impact, a recommended direction and an owner. The mode reviews and routes, it does not implement. Accepted fixes go to `sk-code`, while direction goes to `interface`, tokens go to `foundations` and choreography goes to `motion`. If you want a new visual direction instead of a critique, reach for `interface`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. QUICK START\n\n**Step 1: Invoke it.** Routing keywords like `audit design` or `accessibility audit` reach this mode through `sk-design`. You can also point it at a target directly.\n\n**Step 2: Run the audit.**\n\n```text\nAudit src/pages/checkout.tsx for release readiness and give me a design quality score.\n```\n\nA findings-first report ordered P0, P1, P2, P3, then a `/20` score with a rating band and an owner map.\n\n**Step 3: Verify the docs.**\n\n```bash\npython3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md --type readme\n```\n\nReports zero issues.\n\n---\n\n## 4. HOW IT WORKS\n\nThe audit runs the same shape every time. It resolves the surface to one concrete target, then states what evidence is available and what is missing, so a visual claim never rests on evidence that was never gathered. Findings come next, each with evidence and a severity, ordered worst-first. Only then does the five-dimension score appear, as a summary of the findings rather than a replacement for them. The report closes by mapping every finding to an owner and naming the residual risk if the surface ships as-is.\n\n### Register-Gated Severity\n\nBefore scoring, the audit reads the Brand-vs-Product register. That one call sets the audit-severity dial. On a Brand surface, a generic-but-functional result is a real finding, so blandness scores against Anti-Patterns. On a Product surface, an expressive-but-unclear result is a real finding, so theatrics score against accessibility and consistency. The same observation routes to opposite verdicts depending on posture, which is why the register is resolved first.\n\n### The AI-Tell Catalog\n\nThe anti-patterns dimension leans on a model-specific tell catalog. A ghost-card border plus shadow, over-rounded cards, a diagonal stripe background, an image-hover transform, a cream body background: each is a structural pattern a generator reaches for by reflex, turned into a checkable rule. One isolated tell is polish. Three or more on one surface is the dimension failing.\n\n---\n\n## 5. INTEGRATION & NAVIGATION\n\n### When To Use This Mode\n\nReach for `audit` when you need a verdict on an existing or planned surface: a release-readiness check, an accessibility gate, a slop review or a production-hardening pass. Use it when someone says a design \"looks AI-generated\" and you need to prove it with named tells. Skip it when you want to invent a direction, build a token system or write motion, since those belong to the sibling modes.\n\n### Related Skills\n\n| Skill | Relationship |\n|---|---|\n| `interface` | Owns the direction changes the audit recommends |\n| `foundations` | Owns color, type, layout, responsive and theming token fixes |\n| `motion` | Owns motion choreography and reduced-motion fixes |\n| `sk-code` | Implements every accepted fix after the user approves it |\n\n---\n\n## 6. VERIFICATION\n\nThe mode ships a manual testing playbook. Each scenario runs a prompt against the live mode and its on-disk references, then records PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL or SKIP.\n\n| Check | Result |\n|---|---|\n| Manual playbook | Run the scenarios in [`manual_testing_playbook/`](./manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md). Release is ready when all PASS or SKIP only for a missing target |\n| README structure | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/validate_document.py .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md --type readme` reports zero issues |\n\n---\n\n## 7. RELATED DOCUMENTS\n\n| Document | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| [`SKILL.md`](./SKILL.md) | Runtime instructions and routing logic |\n| [`references/audit_contract.md`](./references/audit_contract.md) | Severity model, `/20` scoring contract and findings schema |\n| [`references/accessibility_performance.md`](./references/accessibility_performance.md) | Accessibility and performance checks with pass and fail numbers |\n| [`references/critique_hardening.md`](./references/critique_hardening.md) | Holistic critique, cognitive load, personas and polish |\n| [`references/anti_patterns_production.md`](./references/anti_patterns_production.md) | Anti-slop signals, theming drift, copy clarity and production details |\n| [`references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md`](./references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md) | Model-specific AI tells turned into checkable P0-P3 findings |\n| [`references/transform_remediation.md`](./references/transform_remediation.md) | Register-gated bolder, quieter and distill verbs mapped to findings and owners |\n| [`references/evidence_capture.md`](./references/evidence_capture.md) | Target resolution, the three evidence types and confirmed-or-inferred labeling |\n| [`references/hardening_edge_cases.md`](./references/hardening_edge_cases.md) | Production-readiness matrix of extreme inputs, errors, concurrency and i18n |\n| [`assets/audit_report_template.md`](./assets/audit_report_template.md) | Fill-in findings-first report skeleton with the five-dimension score |\n| [`assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md`](./assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md) | Snippet-level accessibility fixes the report cites by reference |\n| [`../shared/register.md`](../shared/register.md) | The Brand-vs-Product register that sets the audit-severity dial |","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":124,"totalLines":124,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/README.md","time":{"start":1782532396269,"end":1782532396281}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_041b0478a3b44386016a3f492bfcc48191a393099af2a87c15"}},"id":"prt_f0735d4e80010ffpy7ThjHZwuH","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07357f67001n7NjQU25tkP4eq"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532396285,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_HSflZmeDNZVgxlDtRAGRYMIK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/03--slop-hardening/001-ai-fingerprint-tells.md","offset":1,"limit":900},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/03--slop-hardening/001-ai-fingerprint-tells.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: AI Fingerprint Tells Scenario\n3: description: Manual scenario verifying model-specific AI tells are detected as checkable findings with the right severity and owner.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"test ai fingerprint tells\"\n6:   - \"test model specific tell detection\"\n7:   - \"ai fingerprint tells scenario\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: reference\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: expected_intent: ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION\n12: expected_resources:\n13:   - references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md\n14: ---\n15: \n16: **Exact prompt**\n17: \n18: ```\n19: This dashboard looks AI-generated. Audit it for model-specific fingerprint tells (Codex, Gemini, 2026-general) and report them as checkable findings.\n20: ```\n21: \n22: # AUDIT-SLOP-002 | AI Fingerprint Tells\n23: \n24: ## Target\n25: \n26: Supply one concrete UI artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot likely to carry generator tells, for example a ghost-card border plus shadow, over-rounded cards, a diagonal stripe background, an image-hover transform or a cream body background: a source file path, a rendered URL or a screenshot. If no target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\". Do not invent tells.\n27: \n28: ## Prompt\n29: \n30: `Audit <TARGET> for model-specific AI tells and tell me which generator they point at.`\n31: \n32: ## Expected Process\n33: \n34: 1. Load `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` and `references/audit_contract.md`.\n35: 2. Walk the catalog and check each concrete rule against the surface.\n36: 3. File a finding for every hit with the exact element, the user impact and the owner.\n37: 4. Score the gallery: one isolated tell is P3 or P2, while three or more tells on one surface fail the Anti-Patterns dimension at P1 or higher.\n38: \n39: ## Pass Criteria\n40: \n41: - Each tell is filed with the exact element, selector or file and line as evidence, not a vague impression.\n42: - A tell read from source is labeled confirmed. A tell suspected from a screenshot alone is labeled inferred with the source that would confirm it.\n43: - Severity follows the rule of thumb: one tell is low, three or more stacked tells push the Anti-Patterns dimension to P1, a tell that also breaks a user task climbs to P0.\n44: - Most tells route to the Anti-Patterns dimension, with the noted exceptions touching Theming or Performance.\n45: - A clean pass is reported as no model-specific tells found, not as proof the design is distinctive.\n\n(End of file - total 45 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: AI Fingerprint Tells Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying model-specific AI tells are detected as checkable findings with the right severity and owner.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test ai fingerprint tells\"\n  - \"test model specific tell detection\"\n  - \"ai fingerprint tells scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nThis dashboard looks AI-generated. Audit it for model-specific fingerprint tells (Codex, Gemini, 2026-general) and report them as checkable findings.\n```","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/03--slop-hardening/001-ai-fingerprint-tells.md","text":"---\ntitle: AI Fingerprint Tells Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying model-specific AI tells are detected as checkable findings with the right severity and owner.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test ai fingerprint tells\"\n  - \"test model specific tell detection\"\n  - \"ai fingerprint tells scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: ANTI_PATTERNS_PRODUCTION\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nThis dashboard looks AI-generated. Audit it for model-specific fingerprint tells (Codex, Gemini, 2026-general) and report them as checkable findings.\n```\n\n# AUDIT-SLOP-002 | AI Fingerprint Tells\n\n## Target\n\nSupply one concrete UI artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot likely to carry generator tells, for example a ghost-card border plus shadow, over-rounded cards, a diagonal stripe background, an image-hover transform or a cream body background: a source file path, a rendered URL or a screenshot. If no target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\". Do not invent tells.\n\n## Prompt\n\n`Audit <TARGET> for model-specific AI tells and tell me which generator they point at.`\n\n## Expected Process\n\n1. Load `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` and `references/audit_contract.md`.\n2. Walk the catalog and check each concrete rule against the surface.\n3. File a finding for every hit with the exact element, the user impact and the owner.\n4. Score the gallery: one isolated tell is P3 or P2, while three or more tells on one surface fail the Anti-Patterns dimension at P1 or higher.\n\n## Pass Criteria\n\n- Each tell is filed with the exact element, selector or file and line as evidence, not a vague impression.\n- A tell read from source is labeled confirmed. A tell suspected from a screenshot alone is labeled inferred with the source that would confirm it.\n- Severity follows the rule of thumb: one tell is low, three or more stacked tells push the Anti-Patterns dimension to P1, a tell that also breaks a user task climbs to P0.\n- Most tells route to the Anti-Patterns dimension, with the noted exceptions touching Theming or Performance.\n- A clean pass is reported as no model-specific tells found, not as proof the design is distinctive.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":45,"totalLines":45,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/03--slop-hardening/001-ai-fingerprint-tells.md","time":{"start":1782532396235,"end":1782532396283}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_041b0478a3b44386016a3f492bfcb48191bcad5993781d7225"}},"id":"prt_f0735d486001kmc4AFiU9cmtII","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07357f67001n7NjQU25tkP4eq"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532396288,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_lP0LlsjAGZSAc2ZZ0qAvc4j1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/03--slop-hardening/009-hardening-edge-cases.md","offset":1,"limit":900},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/03--slop-hardening/009-hardening-edge-cases.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Hardening Edge Cases Scenario\n3: description: Manual scenario verifying the production-readiness matrix probes extreme inputs, errors, permissions, concurrency and internationalization.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"test hardening edge cases\"\n6:   - \"test production readiness matrix\"\n7:   - \"hardening edge cases scenario\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: reference\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: expected_intent: CRITIQUE_HARDENING\n12: expected_resources:\n13:   - references/hardening_edge_cases.md\n14: ---\n15: \n16: **Exact prompt**\n17: \n18: ```\n19: Critique this form for production readiness and harden the edge cases: extreme inputs, empty and error states, i18n, and RTL.\n20: ```\n21: \n22: # AUDIT-SLOP-003 | Hardening Edge Cases\n23: \n24: ## Target\n25: \n26: Supply one concrete interactive artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot that takes input or fetches data, for example a form, a table or a submit flow: a source file path, a rendered URL or a screenshot. If no target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\". Do not invent failures.\n27: \n28: ## Prompt\n29: \n30: `Audit <TARGET> for production readiness: extreme inputs, network errors, permissions, concurrency and internationalization.`\n31: \n32: ## Expected Process\n33: \n34: 1. Load `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` and `references/audit_contract.md`.\n35: 2. Walk the matrix against real evidence, labeling any probe that cannot run on the available evidence as inferred.\n36: 3. File each failure with the exact element, the user impact and a severity.\n37: 4. Route the owner: `foundations` for layout, logical-property and token fixes, `interface` for empty-state and error-state direction, `sk-code` for implementation.\n38: \n39: ## Pass Criteria\n40: \n41: - Probes cover extreme inputs, API and network errors, permissions and rate limits, concurrency, internationalization and RTL, text expansion and CJK and emoji.\n42: - A missing empty, loading or error state is filed as a production-readiness finding even when the happy path is flawless.\n43: - Severity follows user impact: lost work or a stranded flow is P0 or P1, a cosmetic overflow with a workaround is P2 or P3.\n44: - RTL failures trace to physical CSS properties and route to `foundations`. Double-submission is flagged when the action is not disabled while in flight.\n45: - Resilience gaps that block assistive use route to Accessibility, with the disabled-control explanation pointing at `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md`.\n\n(End of file - total 45 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Hardening Edge Cases Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying the production-readiness matrix probes extreme inputs, errors, permissions, concurrency and internationalization.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test hardening edge cases\"\n  - \"test production readiness matrix\"\n  - \"hardening edge cases scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: CRITIQUE_HARDENING\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/hardening_edge_cases.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nCritique this form for production readiness and harden the edge cases: extreme inputs, empty and error states, i18n, and RTL.\n```","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/03--slop-hardening/009-hardening-edge-cases.md","text":"---\ntitle: Hardening Edge Cases Scenario\ndescription: Manual scenario verifying the production-readiness matrix probes extreme inputs, errors, permissions, concurrency and internationalization.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"test hardening edge cases\"\n  - \"test production readiness matrix\"\n  - \"hardening edge cases scenario\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: reference\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nexpected_intent: CRITIQUE_HARDENING\nexpected_resources:\n  - references/hardening_edge_cases.md\n---\n\n**Exact prompt**\n\n```\nCritique this form for production readiness and harden the edge cases: extreme inputs, empty and error states, i18n, and RTL.\n```\n\n# AUDIT-SLOP-003 | Hardening Edge Cases\n\n## Target\n\nSupply one concrete interactive artifact in the `<TARGET>` slot that takes input or fetches data, for example a form, a table or a submit flow: a source file path, a rendered URL or a screenshot. If no target is available, record SKIP with the blocker \"no target artifact supplied\". Do not invent failures.\n\n## Prompt\n\n`Audit <TARGET> for production readiness: extreme inputs, network errors, permissions, concurrency and internationalization.`\n\n## Expected Process\n\n1. Load `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` and `references/audit_contract.md`.\n2. Walk the matrix against real evidence, labeling any probe that cannot run on the available evidence as inferred.\n3. File each failure with the exact element, the user impact and a severity.\n4. Route the owner: `foundations` for layout, logical-property and token fixes, `interface` for empty-state and error-state direction, `sk-code` for implementation.\n\n## Pass Criteria\n\n- Probes cover extreme inputs, API and network errors, permissions and rate limits, concurrency, internationalization and RTL, text expansion and CJK and emoji.\n- A missing empty, loading or error state is filed as a production-readiness finding even when the happy path is flawless.\n- Severity follows user impact: lost work or a stranded flow is P0 or P1, a cosmetic overflow with a workaround is P2 or P3.\n- RTL failures trace to physical CSS properties and route to `foundations`. Double-submission is flagged when the action is not disabled while in flight.\n- Resilience gaps that block assistive use route to Accessibility, with the disabled-control explanation pointing at `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md`.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":45,"totalLines":45,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual_testing_playbook/03--slop-hardening/009-hardening-edge-cases.md","time":{"start":1782532396257,"end":1782532396286}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_041b0478a3b44386016a3f492bfcbc8191957a7fc21501c5bd"}},"id":"prt_f0735d4cf0012ZGk9bBbzlyuZs","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f07357f67001n7NjQU25tkP4eq"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782532396792,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f0735d6f1001iIYEXyGJgPrJfo","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"e71ed84a96990e75b9a129ea446b8dd65bdb4226","messageID":"msg_f07357f67001n7NjQU25tkP4eq","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":155058,"input":7627,"output":471,"reasoning":16,"cache":{"write":0,"read":146944}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782532398715,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f0735de79001ErQ8FbvW1zIhT4","messageID":"msg_f0735d89d001kQK9OWTKrkcbwo","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","snapshot":"e71ed84a96990e75b9a129ea446b8dd65bdb4226","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1782532415240,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"id":"prt_f0735e743001RLcCUtIClADuXP","messageID":"msg_f0735d89d001kQK9OWTKrkcbwo","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","type":"text","text":"Manual scenarios confirm the strongest current controls are evidence labeling, INP modernization, model-specific tells, and the edge-case matrix. Next I’m comparing those against the prior corpus expansion and raw external source corpus for missed high-leverage additions.","time":{"start":1782532400963,"end":1782532415237},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_003d9726a0d6407a016a3f4930f6ac8191bd52793243327191","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532415295,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_vnxxmeDIDfR7Gss6uVEpYHFZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/research.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/research.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep-Research Synthesis: sk-design reference and asset expansion\n2: \n3: > **Packet:** `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion`\n4: > **Run:** 2-lineage fan-out, 16 iterations total (opus48-claude2 converged at 6, gpt55fast ran the full 10), merged into this consolidated matrix.\n5: > **Question:** Per sk-design sub-skill, what are the highest-leverage expansions to `references/` and `assets/`, grounded in the prior corpus research + gap-analysis and the 43-entry external corpus, honoring an \"if effective\" bar.\n6: > **Status:** Findings only. Every addition is a scope decision; implementation is a separate, gated follow-up. Out of scope: taxonomy/architecture, net-new sub-skills, implementation.\n7: \n8: The `Src` column records lineage agreement: **both** = both lineages independently proposed it (high confidence), **opus** / **gpt** = surfaced by one lineage.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. Summary\n13: \n14: 1. **Both lineages independently ranked the same #1: a shared Brand-vs-Product operating register (`shared/register.md`).** Opus grounded it in `impeccable` + `bolder`/`quieter`/`distill`; GPT grounded it in `colorize` + `animate`. Independent convergence on the same must-add (gap 05) makes this the highest-confidence finding in the run.\n15: 2. **Four of five modes ship zero assets** (only md-generator has any). The highest-ROI first asset per mode is named below; the audit report template is the strongest case because the audit deliverable *is* a report.\n16: 3. **`design-audit` is the densest expansion target; `design-md-generator` is the leanest** (mostly do-NOT). Both lineages agree.\n17: 4. **The expansion is operational, not bulk import.** Both lineages explicitly reject importing the corpus wholesale; the leverage is in checklists, decision cards, and the register, not more style presets.\n18: 5. **One genuine divergence — md-generator forward-authoring — reconciles:** document the measured-vs-authored *boundary* (GPT's `authoring_boundary.md`) without building the forward-authoring *capability* (Opus routes that to the out-of-scope `design-spec` child). Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 2. Method\n23: \n24: Two heterogeneous lineages over the same charter, fresh context per iteration, one mode-focus per pass:\n25: - **opus48-claude2** (Claude Opus 4.8, cli-claude-code, xhigh): 6 iterations, converged (newInfoRatio 1.0 → 0.25; all key questions answered; quality guards passed). Produced the rigorous spine: cross-cutting prerequisites, priority ranking, negative-knowledge table.\n26: - **gpt55fast** (openai/gpt-5.5-fast, cli-opencode, xhigh): 10 iterations, final newInfoRatio 0.03. Produced more granular per-mode assets (motion cards, audit evidence references, foundations adaptation matrix).\n27: \n28: Grounding inputs (read-only): `001-corpus-research/research/research.md` (settled taxonomy + per-child corpus map), `001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md` (current-state-validated severity table), the 43-entry `external/` corpus, and the live `sk-design/` tree.\n29: \n30: **Inventory baseline (filesystem-confirmed):**\n31: \n32: | Mode | references | assets | Maturity |\n33: |---|---|---|---|\n34: | design-interface | 13 | **0** | Vendored Anthropic base; no `corpus_map.md`; draws on none of the taste corpus |\n35: | design-foundations | 5 | **0** | Well-covered static system; real holes in data-viz + adaptation |\n36: | design-motion | 5 | **0** | Well-covered; gesture basics present; missing restraint gate + reusable cards |\n37: | design-audit | 5 | **0** | Densest expansion target; deliverable is a report yet ships no template |\n38: | design-md-generator | 8 (+4 examples) | 2 | Most mature; mostly do-NOT |\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ## 3. Per-Mode Expansion Matrix (primary deliverable)\n43: \n44: Effort: **S** ≈ ≤0.5d · **M** ≈ 0.5–1.5d. Severity reflects the gap-analysis, re-validated against live state.\n45: \n46: ### 3.1 Shared base (cross-cutting prerequisite)\n47: \n48: | ID | Type | Title | Why it raises usefulness | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n49: |----|------|-------|--------------------------|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n50: | XC-1 | reference | `shared/register.md` — Brand-vs-Product operating register | The must-add prerequisite (gap 05). Gates density, motion budget, color dosage, copy register, anti-slop strictness, and audit severity. Absent today. Unblocks the most downstream work. | impeccable; bolder/quieter/distill; colorize:14; animate:14 | **both** | must (05) | M |\n51: | XC-2 | asset | `shared/assets/register_card.md` — one-page Brand/Product routing card | Operationalizes XC-1 with the Brand/Product questions + downstream defaults per mode. | anti_slop_principles; register sources above | gpt | should | S |\n52: \n53: **Do-NOT (shared):** a sixth \"intake/register\" child (register is shared content, not a sub-skill); duplicating N1/N2 independently in interface + audit (author once, reference twice); re-litigating gap severities.\n54: \n55: ### 3.2 design-interface\n56: \n57: Gaps: vendored base draws on none of the taste/craft corpus; zero assets; no mechanical layout pre-flight gate (N2); no mock-content discipline (N1).\n58: \n59: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n60: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n61: | IF-A1 | asset | `assets/interface_preflight_card.md` — fill-in mechanical pass/fail card | Converts the prose two-pass into a checkable gate: hero line count, eyebrow/meta-label sweep, gapless bento, real-imagery, button contrast, copy audit, motion motivation, reduced-motion, mobile collapse, AI tells. First asset for the mode. | taste-skill:919; gpt-tasteskill:67; impeccable | **both** | should (N2) | M |\n62: | IF-R1 | reference | `references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md` — Design Read + three dials | Structured intake mapping variance/motion/density dials to layout/motion/density choices, with use-case presets. | taste-skill:43 | **both** | should (08t) | S–M |\n63: | IF-R2 | reference | `references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md` | The mechanical anti-default checklist the aesthetic calibration omits. **Shared N2 artifact with audit AU-R5 (author once).** | gpt-tasteskill §2–7; redesign; taste §14 | opus | should (09/N2) | M |\n64: | IF-R3 | reference | `references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md` | Build-side N1: plausible names/numbers/copy, no lorem, no AI-tell phrasing, one-copy-register, image-seed discipline. Twin of audit AU-R4. | taste-skill:321; redesign; gpt-tasteskill §7 | **both** | should (N1) | S |\n65: | IF-R4 | reference | `references/design-process/visual_asset_strategy.md` | When to require real images vs generated imagery vs Simple Icons/devicon logos, with explicit placeholder slots. | taste-skill:262 | gpt | nice | S |\n66: | IF-R5 | subsection | AIDA + gapless-bento note (under `variation_diversity.md`) | Landing-page-only structure/bento math, explicitly NOT default for product UI. | gpt-tasteskill:22,42 | gpt | nice | S |\n67: \n68: **Do-NOT:** more aesthetic preset files as the first expansion (already guarded critique-against-only); gpt-taste Python-RNG randomization as a mandate (redundant with `variation_diversity.md`); GSAP-first / static-forbidden as default behavior (landing-page-only); forward DESIGN.md authoring.\n69: \n70: ### 3.3 design-foundations\n71: \n72: Gaps: no data-viz foundations; no adaptation matrix; no structured intake; zero assets. Gestalt/grid + OKLCH already covered (do-NOT line).\n73: \n74: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n75: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n76: | FN-R1 | reference | `references/data_viz.md` — data-visualization foundations | The clearest coverage hole: chart-type selection, axis/encoding, color-for-data (sequential/diverging/categorical), sparklines, table alignment beyond tabular-nums. | colorize:85; designer-skills ui-design; gap 14d | **both** | should (14d) | M |\n77: | FN-R2 | reference | `references/layout/adaptation_matrix.md` | Device/input/context adaptation (mobile/tablet/desktop/print/constrained) as rethinking-for-context, not pixel scaling. | adapt:37 | gpt | should | S–M |\n78: | FN-R3 | reference | `references/intake/design_read_dials.md` — density-dial intake | Foundations owns the density dial of the shared three-dial intake. **Coordinate ownership with interface (see Open Questions).** | taste-skill §0–1 | opus | should (08t) | S |\n79: | FN-R4 | subsection | brand-seed color fold-in to `color/palette_theming.md` | Greenfield path: derive a palette from one brand seed when no system exists (gap N3). Keep small, no standalone file. | impeccable; gap N3 | **both** | nice (N3) | S |\n80: | FN-A1 | asset | `assets/token_starter.md` — fill-in OKLCH ramp + type + spacing scaffold | First foundations asset; wires the static-system refs into a fill-in keyed to `design_token_vocabulary.md`. (GPT's `density_structure_matrix.md` folds in here.) | oklch-skill; layout:61,150 | **both** | nice | M |\n81: \n82: **Do-NOT:** another OKLCH/contrast/dark-mode basics guide (already owned); splitting foundations into color/layout children (taxonomy); a heavy new Gestalt/grid reference (covered by `shared/cognitive_laws.md` + `layout_responsive.md`); taste-skill brief→design-system framework map (interface/sk-code concern).\n83: \n84: ### 3.4 design-motion\n85: \n86: Gaps: gesture basics already covered, but the restraint gate is missing; emil advanced-craft not distilled; no reusable pattern/failure cards; zero assets.\n87: \n88: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n89: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n90: | MO-R1 | reference | `references/animation_decision_framework.md` — restraint gate | Strongest anti-slop motion lever: 100+/day = never animate, never animate keyboard-initiated actions, tens/day = reduce. Missing today. | emil-design-eng §1–2 | opus | should (08e) | S–M |\n91: | MO-A1 | asset | `assets/motion_pattern_cards.md` — reusable pattern cards | Loading/feedback/state/page-transition/gesture/toast/drag-drop/hover/focus cards with owner + state fields. First motion asset. | interaction-design:10 | gpt | should | S–M |\n92: | MO-A2 | asset | `assets/animate_presence_checklist.md` | Exit wrapper, exit prop, key, symmetry, presence hook, safeToRemove, mode, nested-exit checks. | mastering-animate-presence:21 | gpt | should | S |\n93: | MO-A3 | asset | `assets/motion_performance_failure_card.md` | Failure-mode card: layout thrash, scroll polling, endless rAF, mixed systems, layer promotion, paint-heavy effects, blur. | fixing-motion-performance:52 | gpt | should | S |\n94: | MO-R2 | subsection | advanced-craft + `polish_details` top-up to `micro_interactions.md` | popover transform-origin-from-trigger, `:active` scale(0.97), `scale(0.95)+opacity`, concentric radii, optical alignment, tabular nums. | emil-design-eng; make-interfaces-feel-better:19 | **both** | should (08e) | S |\n95: | MO-R3 | reference | `references/advanced_rendering.md` — propose-first toolkit | View Transitions morph-from-trigger, virtual scroll, GPU/Canvas for data, spring drag-drop — bounded by overdrive's propose-before-building. | overdrive; emil | opus | nice (06) | M |\n96: \n97: **Do-NOT:** gesture *basics* (already in `micro_interactions.md` §4); GSAP scroll paradigms as default mandates (admit only inside MO-R3); motion-performance *review* (audit's surface); a default \"all interfaces must be motion-rich\" rule; emil's \"Initial Response\" identity framing; a separate `design-interaction` child.\n98: \n99: ### 3.5 design-audit (densest)\n100: \n101: Gaps: no AI-fingerprint/model-tell catalog; no evidence-capture model; no remediation/transform routing; no a11y/hardening quick-fix surface; no report template despite the deliverable being a report.\n102: \n103: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n104: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n105: | AU-R1 | reference | `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` — model-specific defect catalog | Highest-leverage single addition family-wide: concrete checkable Codex (tracking/ghost-card/over-round/sketchy-SVG/stripes), Gemini (img-hover), 2026-general (cream-bg/eyebrow-every-section/section-fade) tells. Turns \"feels AI-made\" into P0–P3 findings. | impeccable | opus | should (07) | M |\n106: | AU-A1 | asset | `assets/audit_report_template.md` — fill-in 5-dim `/20` + P0–P3 report | The strongest first-asset case in the family: the audit deliverable IS a report. Findings-first skeleton with score, anti-pattern verdict, owner mapping, evidence caveats. | audit:12; audit_contract | **both** | should | M |\n107: | AU-R2 | reference | `references/transform_remediation.md` — bolder/quieter/distill verbs (register-gated) | Maps directional transform verbs + redesign to findings, owner mode, accepted remediation path. **Depends on XC-1.** Shared with interface. | bolder; quieter; distill; redesign; gap 04/11 | **both** | should (04/11) | S–M |\n108: | AU-R3 | reference | `references/evidence_capture.md` | Evidence model: file/source resolution, browser evidence, deterministic scans, screenshot/overlay notes, fallback labels. | critique:12 | gpt | should | M |\n109: | AU-A2 | asset | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Snippet-level fixes: accessible names, keyboard, focus/dialogs, semantics, forms/errors, announcements, contrast, motion. | fixing-accessibility:33 | gpt | should | S |\n110: | AU-R4 | reference | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` | Production-readiness matrix: extreme inputs, API/network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, i18n/RTL, text expansion, CJK/emoji. | harden:14 | gpt | should | S–M |\n111: | AU-R5 | reference | mock-content review check + mechanical layout gate (folded into `anti_patterns_production.md`) | Review-side N1 + N2 twins of interface IF-R3/IF-R2. Author the gates once, audit references the review view. | redesign; taste §14; impeccable | opus | should (N1/N2) | S |\n112: \n113: **Do-NOT:** critique/cognitive-load/Nielsen/hardening/polish duplication (already in `critique_hardening.md`); CWV/a11y/perf duplication (already in `accessibility_performance.md`; do not revert INP→FID); implementing fixes (sk-code's boundary); full two-sub-agent critique orchestration (keep evidence principles only); elevating a11y to a standalone child.\n114: \n115: ### 3.6 design-md-generator (leanest — expansion mostly not effective)\n116: \n117: Gaps: essentially none. The only skew: all 4 worked examples are SaaS-minimalist. The one genuine in-scope reference is the authoring boundary (the divergence, reconciled).\n118: \n119: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n120: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n121: | MD-R1 | reference | `references/authoring_boundary.md` — measured vs brief-authored vs inferred | Clarifies the fidelity boundary + source-of-truth labels WITHOUT building forward-authoring. Protects the cardinal fidelity rule against the design-spec pull. | md SKILL cardinal rule:248; stitch-skill:17 (boundary only) | gpt | should | S–M |\n122: | MD-A1 | asset | `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` | Quick card: measured tokens / brief-provided / inferred / missing-backing? Prevents fabricated values. | design_md_format cardinal rules:27 | gpt | nice | S |\n123: | MD-A2 | asset (example) | 5th DESIGN.md exemplar in a non-SaaS aesthetic (editorial / e-commerce / maximalist) | All 4 exemplars are SaaS-minimalist; one distinct aesthetic broadens format coverage. Requires a real extraction run, so only nice-to-have. | v3 format + fresh extraction | **both** | nice | S–M |\n124: \n125: **Do-NOT (dominant verdict):** forward DESIGN.md/PRODUCT.md *authoring capability* (stitch, gap 10 — different input contract; routes to the net-new `design-spec` child; out of scope for 009); a second extraction backend/crawler (pipeline already extracts/writes/validates/reports); duplicate format/taxonomy references; inventing values or weakening `tokens.json` fidelity.\n126: \n127: ---\n128: \n129: ## 4. Family-Wide Priority Ranking\n130: \n131: Should-adds by leverage (corpus strength × coverage hole × checkability × cross-lineage agreement):\n132: \n133: 1. **XC-1 `shared/register.md`** (must) — both lineages' #1; gates the most downstream work.\n134: 2. **IF-A1 + AU-A1 first assets** (both) — the two highest-ROI fill-in cards (preflight + audit report).\n135: 3. **AU-R1 model-tell catalog** (opus) — most concrete, highest checkable value, no current analog.\n136: 4. **N1/N2 author-once gates** (IF-R2 + IF-R3 + AU-R5, both) — convert the most common LLM defects into checkable gates.\n137: 5. **AU-R2 transform/remediation verbs** (both, register-dependent) + **AU-R3 evidence-capture** (gpt).\n138: 6. **FN-R1 data-viz** (both) + **FN-R2 adaptation matrix** (gpt) — the two real foundations holes.\n139: 7. **MO-R1 restraint gate** (opus) + the three motion asset cards MO-A1/A2/A3 (gpt).\n140: 8. **MD-R1 authoring-boundary** (gpt) — low effort, protects fidelity.\n141: \n142: Nice-to-haves (IF-R4/R5, FN-R4/A1, MO-R2/R3, AU-R5 enrich, MD-A1/A2) rank below.\n143: \n144: ---\n145: \n146: ## 5. Recommended Implementation Sequence (gated follow-up)\n147: \n148: 1. **XC-1 `shared/register.md` + XC-2 card first** — unblocks AU-R1/R2 + IF-R1/R2.\n149: 2. **Interface + audit first-assets** (IF-A1, AU-A1) — highest operator leverage; converts the taste corpus into repeatable checks.\n150: 3. **Author N1 + N2 once** (interface owns, audit references) — prevents drift.\n151: 4. **Audit cluster** (AU-R1, AU-R2, AU-R3, AU-A2) — densest payoff, most concrete corpus.\n152: 5. **Foundations holes** (FN-R1 data-viz, FN-R2 adaptation) — without duplicating basics.\n153: 6. **Motion cards** (MO-R1 gate + MO-A1/A2/A3) — package known rules into reusable cards.\n154: 7. **md-generator authoring-boundary** (MD-R1) — adds the boundary while protecting cardinal fidelity. Treat md-generator as otherwise done.\n155: \n156: ---\n157: \n158: ## 6. Eliminated Alternatives (negative knowledge)\n159: \n160: | Approach | Reason eliminated | Src |\n161: |---|---|---|\n162: | Bulk-import the external corpus | Leverage is operational refs + cards, not volume; both lineages reject it | both |\n163: | gpt-taste Python-RNG \"true randomization\" as an interface mandate | Redundant with `variation_diversity.md`; contradicts grounding-first | opus |\n164: | Aesthetic presets as a chooser in interface | Already guarded critique-against-only; must not become pick-a-vibe | both |\n165: | Splitting foundations into color/layout children | Taxonomy, decided | both |\n166: | Heavy new Gestalt/grid reference | Already covered by `shared/cognitive_laws.md` + `layout_responsive.md` | opus |\n167: | Adding gesture basics to motion | Already in `micro_interactions.md` §4 | opus |\n168: | Folding motion-performance *review* into motion | Owned by audit; build-vs-review boundary is correct | both |\n169: | Overdrive/advanced rendering as core motion behavior | Nice-to-have only; propose-first, not default | both |\n170: | Duplicating critique/CWV/a11y in new audit references | Already deep in `critique_hardening.md` + `accessibility_performance.md` | both |\n171: | Implementing fixes inside audit | Audit reports/scores; implementation is sk-code | both |\n172: | Forward DESIGN.md authoring *capability* in md-generator | Different input contract; routes to net-new `design-spec`; out of scope (boundary doc IS in scope) | both |\n173: | A second extraction backend in md-generator | Pipeline already extracts/writes/validates/reports | gpt |\n174: | `designer-skills-main` full process lifecycle, slides/canvas/poster, output-skill | Out-of-family / scope rulings in gap-analysis | gpt |\n175: | A sixth intake/register child | Register is shared content, not a sub-skill | opus |\n176: \n177: ---\n178: \n179: ## 7. Open Questions / Divergences\n180: \n181: 1. **md-generator forward-authoring (the one real divergence).** Opus routes forward-authoring fully out of scope (to a net-new `design-spec` child); GPT proposes an `authoring_boundary.md` reference + source-of-truth router. **Reconciliation:** the boundary *documentation* (labels for measured / brief-provided / inferred / absent) is in-scope and low-risk; the forward-authoring *capability* stays out of scope. Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n182: 2. **Three-dials ownership.** `VISUAL_DENSITY`→foundations, `DESIGN_VARIANCE`→interface, `MOTION_INTENSITY`→motion. gap-analysis routes the intake to foundations; an interface/shared home may fit better. Decide at build time (affects IF-R1 vs FN-R3).\n183: 3. **N1/N2 owning home.** `shared/` vs interface-owned-with-audit-reference. Either preserves \"author once\"; pick at build time.\n184: 4. **Effort estimates are coarse (S/M).** Calibrate against actual authoring + validation in the follow-up.\n185: 5. **Pre-existing defect to fix alongside:** `design-audit/SKILL.md §8` cites `changelog/v1.0.0.1.md`, which the v1.0.0.0 pre-release collapse removed. Repoint to `v1.0.0.0.md`.\n186: \n187: ---\n188: \n189: <!-- ANCHOR:references -->\n190: ## 8. References\n191: \n192: ### This run (lineage artifacts)\n193: - `research/lineages/opus48-claude2/research.md` + `iterations/iteration-00{1..6}.md` (converged)\n194: - `research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md` + `iterations/iteration-0{01..10}.md`\n195: - `research/deep-research-findings-registry.json` (merged, 18 key findings) + `research/fanout-attribution.md`\n196: \n197: ### Grounding inputs (read-only)\n198: - `001-corpus-research/research/research.md` (settled taxonomy + per-child corpus map)\n199: - `001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md` (current-state-validated severity table)\n200: - `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md`\n201: \n202: ### Corpus sources cited (subset of the 43-entry external/)\n203: - Interface/craft: `gpt-tasteskill`, `taste-skill`, `redesign-skill`, `bencium-innovative-ux-designer`, `design-lab`\n204: - Foundations: `oklch-skill`, `layout`, `baseline`, `adapt`, `colorize`, `designer-skills-main` (ui-design data-viz)\n205: - Motion: `emil-design-eng`, `overdrive`, `animate`, `interaction-design`, `mastering-animate-presence`, `fixing-motion-performance`, `make-interfaces-feel-better`\n206: - Audit/transform: `impeccable`, `redesign-skill`, `bolder`, `quieter`, `distill`, `audit`, `critique`, `polish`, `harden`, `fixing-accessibility`\n207: - Spec/authoring: `stitch-skill` (boundary only; forward-authoring routed out of scope)\n208: <!-- /ANCHOR:references -->\n\n(End of file - total 208 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep-Research Synthesis: sk-design reference and asset expansion\n\n> **Packet:** `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion`\n> **Run:** 2-lineage fan-out, 16 iterations total (opus48-claude2 converged at 6, gpt55fast ran the full 10), merged into this consolidated matrix.\n> **Question:** Per sk-design sub-skill, what are the highest-leverage expansions to `references/` and `assets/`, grounded in the prior corpus research + gap-analysis and the 43-entry external corpus, honoring an \"if effective\" bar.\n> **Status:** Findings only. Every addition is a scope decision; implementation is a separate, gated follow-up. Out of scope: taxonomy/architecture, net-new sub-skills, implementation.\n\nThe `Src` column records lineage agreement: **both** = both lineages independently proposed it (high confidence), **opus** / **gpt** = surfaced by one lineage.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Summary\n\n1. **Both lineages independently ranked the same #1: a shared Brand-vs-Product operating register (`shared/register.md`).** Opus grounded it in `impeccable` + `bolder`/`quieter`/`distill`; GPT grounded it in `colorize` + `animate`. Independent convergence on the same must-add (gap 05) makes this the highest-confidence finding in the run.\n2. **Four of five modes ship zero assets** (only md-generator has any). The highest-ROI first asset per mode is named below; the audit report template is the strongest case because the audit deliverable *is* a report.\n3. **`design-audit` is the densest expansion target; `design-md-generator` is the leanest** (mostly do-NOT). Both lineages agree.\n4. **The expansion is operational, not bulk import.** Both lineages explicitly reject importing the corpus wholesale; the leverage is in checklists, decision cards, and the register, not more style presets.\n5. **One genuine divergence — md-generator forward-authoring — reconciles:** document the measured-vs-authored *boundary* (GPT's `authoring_boundary.md`) without building the forward-authoring *capability* (Opus routes that to the out-of-scope `design-spec` child). Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/research.md","text":"# Deep-Research Synthesis: sk-design reference and asset expansion\n\n> **Packet:** `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion`\n> **Run:** 2-lineage fan-out, 16 iterations total (opus48-claude2 converged at 6, gpt55fast ran the full 10), merged into this consolidated matrix.\n> **Question:** Per sk-design sub-skill, what are the highest-leverage expansions to `references/` and `assets/`, grounded in the prior corpus research + gap-analysis and the 43-entry external corpus, honoring an \"if effective\" bar.\n> **Status:** Findings only. Every addition is a scope decision; implementation is a separate, gated follow-up. Out of scope: taxonomy/architecture, net-new sub-skills, implementation.\n\nThe `Src` column records lineage agreement: **both** = both lineages independently proposed it (high confidence), **opus** / **gpt** = surfaced by one lineage.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Summary\n\n1. **Both lineages independently ranked the same #1: a shared Brand-vs-Product operating register (`shared/register.md`).** Opus grounded it in `impeccable` + `bolder`/`quieter`/`distill`; GPT grounded it in `colorize` + `animate`. Independent convergence on the same must-add (gap 05) makes this the highest-confidence finding in the run.\n2. **Four of five modes ship zero assets** (only md-generator has any). The highest-ROI first asset per mode is named below; the audit report template is the strongest case because the audit deliverable *is* a report.\n3. **`design-audit` is the densest expansion target; `design-md-generator` is the leanest** (mostly do-NOT). Both lineages agree.\n4. **The expansion is operational, not bulk import.** Both lineages explicitly reject importing the corpus wholesale; the leverage is in checklists, decision cards, and the register, not more style presets.\n5. **One genuine divergence — md-generator forward-authoring — reconciles:** document the measured-vs-authored *boundary* (GPT's `authoring_boundary.md`) without building the forward-authoring *capability* (Opus routes that to the out-of-scope `design-spec` child). Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Method\n\nTwo heterogeneous lineages over the same charter, fresh context per iteration, one mode-focus per pass:\n- **opus48-claude2** (Claude Opus 4.8, cli-claude-code, xhigh): 6 iterations, converged (newInfoRatio 1.0 → 0.25; all key questions answered; quality guards passed). Produced the rigorous spine: cross-cutting prerequisites, priority ranking, negative-knowledge table.\n- **gpt55fast** (openai/gpt-5.5-fast, cli-opencode, xhigh): 10 iterations, final newInfoRatio 0.03. Produced more granular per-mode assets (motion cards, audit evidence references, foundations adaptation matrix).\n\nGrounding inputs (read-only): `001-corpus-research/research/research.md` (settled taxonomy + per-child corpus map), `001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md` (current-state-validated severity table), the 43-entry `external/` corpus, and the live `sk-design/` tree.\n\n**Inventory baseline (filesystem-confirmed):**\n\n| Mode | references | assets | Maturity |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| design-interface | 13 | **0** | Vendored Anthropic base; no `corpus_map.md`; draws on none of the taste corpus |\n| design-foundations | 5 | **0** | Well-covered static system; real holes in data-viz + adaptation |\n| design-motion | 5 | **0** | Well-covered; gesture basics present; missing restraint gate + reusable cards |\n| design-audit | 5 | **0** | Densest expansion target; deliverable is a report yet ships no template |\n| design-md-generator | 8 (+4 examples) | 2 | Most mature; mostly do-NOT |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Per-Mode Expansion Matrix (primary deliverable)\n\nEffort: **S** ≈ ≤0.5d · **M** ≈ 0.5–1.5d. Severity reflects the gap-analysis, re-validated against live state.\n\n### 3.1 Shared base (cross-cutting prerequisite)\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why it raises usefulness | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|--------------------------|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| XC-1 | reference | `shared/register.md` — Brand-vs-Product operating register | The must-add prerequisite (gap 05). Gates density, motion budget, color dosage, copy register, anti-slop strictness, and audit severity. Absent today. Unblocks the most downstream work. | impeccable; bolder/quieter/distill; colorize:14; animate:14 | **both** | must (05) | M |\n| XC-2 | asset | `shared/assets/register_card.md` — one-page Brand/Product routing card | Operationalizes XC-1 with the Brand/Product questions + downstream defaults per mode. | anti_slop_principles; register sources above | gpt | should | S |\n\n**Do-NOT (shared):** a sixth \"intake/register\" child (register is shared content, not a sub-skill); duplicating N1/N2 independently in interface + audit (author once, reference twice); re-litigating gap severities.\n\n### 3.2 design-interface\n\nGaps: vendored base draws on none of the taste/craft corpus; zero assets; no mechanical layout pre-flight gate (N2); no mock-content discipline (N1).\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| IF-A1 | asset | `assets/interface_preflight_card.md` — fill-in mechanical pass/fail card | Converts the prose two-pass into a checkable gate: hero line count, eyebrow/meta-label sweep, gapless bento, real-imagery, button contrast, copy audit, motion motivation, reduced-motion, mobile collapse, AI tells. First asset for the mode. | taste-skill:919; gpt-tasteskill:67; impeccable | **both** | should (N2) | M |\n| IF-R1 | reference | `references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md` — Design Read + three dials | Structured intake mapping variance/motion/density dials to layout/motion/density choices, with use-case presets. | taste-skill:43 | **both** | should (08t) | S–M |\n| IF-R2 | reference | `references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md` | The mechanical anti-default checklist the aesthetic calibration omits. **Shared N2 artifact with audit AU-R5 (author once).** | gpt-tasteskill §2–7; redesign; taste §14 | opus | should (09/N2) | M |\n| IF-R3 | reference | `references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md` | Build-side N1: plausible names/numbers/copy, no lorem, no AI-tell phrasing, one-copy-register, image-seed discipline. Twin of audit AU-R4. | taste-skill:321; redesign; gpt-tasteskill §7 | **both** | should (N1) | S |\n| IF-R4 | reference | `references/design-process/visual_asset_strategy.md` | When to require real images vs generated imagery vs Simple Icons/devicon logos, with explicit placeholder slots. | taste-skill:262 | gpt | nice | S |\n| IF-R5 | subsection | AIDA + gapless-bento note (under `variation_diversity.md`) | Landing-page-only structure/bento math, explicitly NOT default for product UI. | gpt-tasteskill:22,42 | gpt | nice | S |\n\n**Do-NOT:** more aesthetic preset files as the first expansion (already guarded critique-against-only); gpt-taste Python-RNG randomization as a mandate (redundant with `variation_diversity.md`); GSAP-first / static-forbidden as default behavior (landing-page-only); forward DESIGN.md authoring.\n\n### 3.3 design-foundations\n\nGaps: no data-viz foundations; no adaptation matrix; no structured intake; zero assets. Gestalt/grid + OKLCH already covered (do-NOT line).\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| FN-R1 | reference | `references/data_viz.md` — data-visualization foundations | The clearest coverage hole: chart-type selection, axis/encoding, color-for-data (sequential/diverging/categorical), sparklines, table alignment beyond tabular-nums. | colorize:85; designer-skills ui-design; gap 14d | **both** | should (14d) | M |\n| FN-R2 | reference | `references/layout/adaptation_matrix.md` | Device/input/context adaptation (mobile/tablet/desktop/print/constrained) as rethinking-for-context, not pixel scaling. | adapt:37 | gpt | should | S–M |\n| FN-R3 | reference | `references/intake/design_read_dials.md` — density-dial intake | Foundations owns the density dial of the shared three-dial intake. **Coordinate ownership with interface (see Open Questions).** | taste-skill §0–1 | opus | should (08t) | S |\n| FN-R4 | subsection | brand-seed color fold-in to `color/palette_theming.md` | Greenfield path: derive a palette from one brand seed when no system exists (gap N3). Keep small, no standalone file. | impeccable; gap N3 | **both** | nice (N3) | S |\n| FN-A1 | asset | `assets/token_starter.md` — fill-in OKLCH ramp + type + spacing scaffold | First foundations asset; wires the static-system refs into a fill-in keyed to `design_token_vocabulary.md`. (GPT's `density_structure_matrix.md` folds in here.) | oklch-skill; layout:61,150 | **both** | nice | M |\n\n**Do-NOT:** another OKLCH/contrast/dark-mode basics guide (already owned); splitting foundations into color/layout children (taxonomy); a heavy new Gestalt/grid reference (covered by `shared/cognitive_laws.md` + `layout_responsive.md`); taste-skill brief→design-system framework map (interface/sk-code concern).\n\n### 3.4 design-motion\n\nGaps: gesture basics already covered, but the restraint gate is missing; emil advanced-craft not distilled; no reusable pattern/failure cards; zero assets.\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| MO-R1 | reference | `references/animation_decision_framework.md` — restraint gate | Strongest anti-slop motion lever: 100+/day = never animate, never animate keyboard-initiated actions, tens/day = reduce. Missing today. | emil-design-eng §1–2 | opus | should (08e) | S–M |\n| MO-A1 | asset | `assets/motion_pattern_cards.md` — reusable pattern cards | Loading/feedback/state/page-transition/gesture/toast/drag-drop/hover/focus cards with owner + state fields. First motion asset. | interaction-design:10 | gpt | should | S–M |\n| MO-A2 | asset | `assets/animate_presence_checklist.md` | Exit wrapper, exit prop, key, symmetry, presence hook, safeToRemove, mode, nested-exit checks. | mastering-animate-presence:21 | gpt | should | S |\n| MO-A3 | asset | `assets/motion_performance_failure_card.md` | Failure-mode card: layout thrash, scroll polling, endless rAF, mixed systems, layer promotion, paint-heavy effects, blur. | fixing-motion-performance:52 | gpt | should | S |\n| MO-R2 | subsection | advanced-craft + `polish_details` top-up to `micro_interactions.md` | popover transform-origin-from-trigger, `:active` scale(0.97), `scale(0.95)+opacity`, concentric radii, optical alignment, tabular nums. | emil-design-eng; make-interfaces-feel-better:19 | **both** | should (08e) | S |\n| MO-R3 | reference | `references/advanced_rendering.md` — propose-first toolkit | View Transitions morph-from-trigger, virtual scroll, GPU/Canvas for data, spring drag-drop — bounded by overdrive's propose-before-building. | overdrive; emil | opus | nice (06) | M |\n\n**Do-NOT:** gesture *basics* (already in `micro_interactions.md` §4); GSAP scroll paradigms as default mandates (admit only inside MO-R3); motion-performance *review* (audit's surface); a default \"all interfaces must be motion-rich\" rule; emil's \"Initial Response\" identity framing; a separate `design-interaction` child.\n\n### 3.5 design-audit (densest)\n\nGaps: no AI-fingerprint/model-tell catalog; no evidence-capture model; no remediation/transform routing; no a11y/hardening quick-fix surface; no report template despite the deliverable being a report.\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| AU-R1 | reference | `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` — model-specific defect catalog | Highest-leverage single addition family-wide: concrete checkable Codex (tracking/ghost-card/over-round/sketchy-SVG/stripes), Gemini (img-hover), 2026-general (cream-bg/eyebrow-every-section/section-fade) tells. Turns \"feels AI-made\" into P0–P3 findings. | impeccable | opus | should (07) | M |\n| AU-A1 | asset | `assets/audit_report_template.md` — fill-in 5-dim `/20` + P0–P3 report | The strongest first-asset case in the family: the audit deliverable IS a report. Findings-first skeleton with score, anti-pattern verdict, owner mapping, evidence caveats. | audit:12; audit_contract | **both** | should | M |\n| AU-R2 | reference | `references/transform_remediation.md` — bolder/quieter/distill verbs (register-gated) | Maps directional transform verbs + redesign to findings, owner mode, accepted remediation path. **Depends on XC-1.** Shared with interface. | bolder; quieter; distill; redesign; gap 04/11 | **both** | should (04/11) | S–M |\n| AU-R3 | reference | `references/evidence_capture.md` | Evidence model: file/source resolution, browser evidence, deterministic scans, screenshot/overlay notes, fallback labels. | critique:12 | gpt | should | M |\n| AU-A2 | asset | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Snippet-level fixes: accessible names, keyboard, focus/dialogs, semantics, forms/errors, announcements, contrast, motion. | fixing-accessibility:33 | gpt | should | S |\n| AU-R4 | reference | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` | Production-readiness matrix: extreme inputs, API/network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, i18n/RTL, text expansion, CJK/emoji. | harden:14 | gpt | should | S–M |\n| AU-R5 | reference | mock-content review check + mechanical layout gate (folded into `anti_patterns_production.md`) | Review-side N1 + N2 twins of interface IF-R3/IF-R2. Author the gates once, audit references the review view. | redesign; taste §14; impeccable | opus | should (N1/N2) | S |\n\n**Do-NOT:** critique/cognitive-load/Nielsen/hardening/polish duplication (already in `critique_hardening.md`); CWV/a11y/perf duplication (already in `accessibility_performance.md`; do not revert INP→FID); implementing fixes (sk-code's boundary); full two-sub-agent critique orchestration (keep evidence principles only); elevating a11y to a standalone child.\n\n### 3.6 design-md-generator (leanest — expansion mostly not effective)\n\nGaps: essentially none. The only skew: all 4 worked examples are SaaS-minimalist. The one genuine in-scope reference is the authoring boundary (the divergence, reconciled).\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| MD-R1 | reference | `references/authoring_boundary.md` — measured vs brief-authored vs inferred | Clarifies the fidelity boundary + source-of-truth labels WITHOUT building forward-authoring. Protects the cardinal fidelity rule against the design-spec pull. | md SKILL cardinal rule:248; stitch-skill:17 (boundary only) | gpt | should | S–M |\n| MD-A1 | asset | `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` | Quick card: measured tokens / brief-provided / inferred / missing-backing? Prevents fabricated values. | design_md_format cardinal rules:27 | gpt | nice | S |\n| MD-A2 | asset (example) | 5th DESIGN.md exemplar in a non-SaaS aesthetic (editorial / e-commerce / maximalist) | All 4 exemplars are SaaS-minimalist; one distinct aesthetic broadens format coverage. Requires a real extraction run, so only nice-to-have. | v3 format + fresh extraction | **both** | nice | S–M |\n\n**Do-NOT (dominant verdict):** forward DESIGN.md/PRODUCT.md *authoring capability* (stitch, gap 10 — different input contract; routes to the net-new `design-spec` child; out of scope for 009); a second extraction backend/crawler (pipeline already extracts/writes/validates/reports); duplicate format/taxonomy references; inventing values or weakening `tokens.json` fidelity.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Family-Wide Priority Ranking\n\nShould-adds by leverage (corpus strength × coverage hole × checkability × cross-lineage agreement):\n\n1. **XC-1 `shared/register.md`** (must) — both lineages' #1; gates the most downstream work.\n2. **IF-A1 + AU-A1 first assets** (both) — the two highest-ROI fill-in cards (preflight + audit report).\n3. **AU-R1 model-tell catalog** (opus) — most concrete, highest checkable value, no current analog.\n4. **N1/N2 author-once gates** (IF-R2 + IF-R3 + AU-R5, both) — convert the most common LLM defects into checkable gates.\n5. **AU-R2 transform/remediation verbs** (both, register-dependent) + **AU-R3 evidence-capture** (gpt).\n6. **FN-R1 data-viz** (both) + **FN-R2 adaptation matrix** (gpt) — the two real foundations holes.\n7. **MO-R1 restraint gate** (opus) + the three motion asset cards MO-A1/A2/A3 (gpt).\n8. **MD-R1 authoring-boundary** (gpt) — low effort, protects fidelity.\n\nNice-to-haves (IF-R4/R5, FN-R4/A1, MO-R2/R3, AU-R5 enrich, MD-A1/A2) rank below.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Recommended Implementation Sequence (gated follow-up)\n\n1. **XC-1 `shared/register.md` + XC-2 card first** — unblocks AU-R1/R2 + IF-R1/R2.\n2. **Interface + audit first-assets** (IF-A1, AU-A1) — highest operator leverage; converts the taste corpus into repeatable checks.\n3. **Author N1 + N2 once** (interface owns, audit references) — prevents drift.\n4. **Audit cluster** (AU-R1, AU-R2, AU-R3, AU-A2) — densest payoff, most concrete corpus.\n5. **Foundations holes** (FN-R1 data-viz, FN-R2 adaptation) — without duplicating basics.\n6. **Motion cards** (MO-R1 gate + MO-A1/A2/A3) — package known rules into reusable cards.\n7. **md-generator authoring-boundary** (MD-R1) — adds the boundary while protecting cardinal fidelity. Treat md-generator as otherwise done.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Eliminated Alternatives (negative knowledge)\n\n| Approach | Reason eliminated | Src |\n|---|---|---|\n| Bulk-import the external corpus | Leverage is operational refs + cards, not volume; both lineages reject it | both |\n| gpt-taste Python-RNG \"true randomization\" as an interface mandate | Redundant with `variation_diversity.md`; contradicts grounding-first | opus |\n| Aesthetic presets as a chooser in interface | Already guarded critique-against-only; must not become pick-a-vibe | both |\n| Splitting foundations into color/layout children | Taxonomy, decided | both |\n| Heavy new Gestalt/grid reference | Already covered by `shared/cognitive_laws.md` + `layout_responsive.md` | opus |\n| Adding gesture basics to motion | Already in `micro_interactions.md` §4 | opus |\n| Folding motion-performance *review* into motion | Owned by audit; build-vs-review boundary is correct | both |\n| Overdrive/advanced rendering as core motion behavior | Nice-to-have only; propose-first, not default | both |\n| Duplicating critique/CWV/a11y in new audit references | Already deep in `critique_hardening.md` + `accessibility_performance.md` | both |\n| Implementing fixes inside audit | Audit reports/scores; implementation is sk-code | both |\n| Forward DESIGN.md authoring *capability* in md-generator | Different input contract; routes to net-new `design-spec`; out of scope (boundary doc IS in scope) | both |\n| A second extraction backend in md-generator | Pipeline already extracts/writes/validates/reports | gpt |\n| `designer-skills-main` full process lifecycle, slides/canvas/poster, output-skill | Out-of-family / scope rulings in gap-analysis | gpt |\n| A sixth intake/register child | Register is shared content, not a sub-skill | opus |\n\n---\n\n## 7. Open Questions / Divergences\n\n1. **md-generator forward-authoring (the one real divergence).** Opus routes forward-authoring fully out of scope (to a net-new `design-spec` child); GPT proposes an `authoring_boundary.md` reference + source-of-truth router. **Reconciliation:** the boundary *documentation* (labels for measured / brief-provided / inferred / absent) is in-scope and low-risk; the forward-authoring *capability* stays out of scope. Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n2. **Three-dials ownership.** `VISUAL_DENSITY`→foundations, `DESIGN_VARIANCE`→interface, `MOTION_INTENSITY`→motion. gap-analysis routes the intake to foundations; an interface/shared home may fit better. Decide at build time (affects IF-R1 vs FN-R3).\n3. **N1/N2 owning home.** `shared/` vs interface-owned-with-audit-reference. Either preserves \"author once\"; pick at build time.\n4. **Effort estimates are coarse (S/M).** Calibrate against actual authoring + validation in the follow-up.\n5. **Pre-existing defect to fix alongside:** `design-audit/SKILL.md §8` cites `changelog/v1.0.0.1.md`, which the v1.0.0.0 pre-release collapse removed. Repoint to `v1.0.0.0.md`.\n\n---\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:references -->\n## 8. References\n\n### This run (lineage artifacts)\n- `research/lineages/opus48-claude2/research.md` + `iterations/iteration-00{1..6}.md` (converged)\n- `research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md` + `iterations/iteration-0{01..10}.md`\n- `research/deep-research-findings-registry.json` (merged, 18 key findings) + `research/fanout-attribution.md`\n\n### Grounding inputs (read-only)\n- `001-corpus-research/research/research.md` (settled taxonomy + per-child corpus map)\n- `001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md` (current-state-validated severity table)\n- `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md`\n\n### Corpus sources cited (subset of the 43-entry external/)\n- Interface/craft: `gpt-tasteskill`, `taste-skill`, `redesign-skill`, `bencium-innovative-ux-designer`, `design-lab`\n- Foundations: `oklch-skill`, `layout`, `baseline`, `adapt`, `colorize`, `designer-skills-main` (ui-design data-viz)\n- Motion: `emil-design-eng`, `overdrive`, `animate`, `interaction-design`, `mastering-animate-presence`, `fixing-motion-performance`, `make-interfaces-feel-better`\n- Audit/transform: `impeccable`, `redesign-skill`, `bolder`, `quieter`, `distill`, `audit`, `critique`, `polish`, `harden`, `fixing-accessibility`\n- Spec/authoring: `stitch-skill` (boundary only; forward-authoring routed out of scope)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:references -->","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":208,"totalLines":208,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/research.md","time":{"start":1782532415275,"end":1782532415292}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_003d9726a0d6407a016a3f493f348081918b78fce3b78ee05f"}},"id":"prt_f07361f07001VnOGcLo4CHNo4y","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","messageID":"msg_f0735d89d001kQK9OWTKrkcbwo"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532415296,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c97ffeoYuqUQ1KEMV7ea","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_fopkfGsLJnlupW882mnFNh97","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md","offset":80,"limit":110},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n80: | P1 | Asset | `assets/animate_presence_checklist.md` | Exit wrapper, exit prop, key, symmetry, presence hook, safeToRemove, mode, and nested-exit checks. | AnimatePresence priority categories and rules [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/mastering-animate-presence.md:21]. | 0.5d |\n81: | P1 | Asset | `assets/motion_performance_failure_card.md` | Failure-mode card for layout thrash, scroll polling, endless rAF, mixed systems, layer promotion, paint-heavy effects, and blur. | `fixing-motion-performance` quick reference [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-motion-performance.md:52]. | 0.5d |\n82: | P2 | Reference subsection | Add `polish_details` to `micro_interactions.md` | Concentric radii, optical alignment, tabular numbers, image outlines, scale-on-press, and transition-property rules. | `make-interfaces-feel-better` core principles [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md:19]. | 0.5d |\n83: \n84: Do not add:\n85: \n86: - Overdrive/advanced rendering as core motion behavior. Prior gap analysis classifies advanced rendering as nice-to-have [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:30].\n87: - A default rule that all interfaces must be motion-rich. Current success criteria require motion not to exhaust the user [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:306].\n88: \n89: ### 3.5 `design-audit`\n90: \n91: | Priority | Type | Proposed file | What it adds | Sources | Effort |\n92: |---|---|---|---|---|---|\n93: | P1 | Reference | `references/evidence_capture.md` | Evidence model for file/source target resolution, browser evidence, deterministic scans, screenshot/overlay notes, and fallback labels. | `critique` requires independent assessment and detector/browser evidence [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md:12]. | 1.0d |\n94: | P1 | Asset | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Snippet-level fixes for accessible names, keyboard, focus/dialogs, semantics, forms/errors, announcements, contrast, and motion. | `fixing-accessibility` priority categories and quick fixes [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-accessibility.md:33]. | 0.75d |\n95: | P1 | Reference | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` | Production-readiness matrix for extreme inputs, API/network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, i18n, RTL, text expansion, and CJK/emoji. | `harden` edge-case assessment [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/harden.md:14]. | 0.75d |\n96: | P1 | Reference | `references/transform_remediation.md` | Maps bolder/quieter/distill/redesign verbs to findings, owner mode, and accepted remediation path. | Prior gap analysis flags transform verbs and redesign/remediation as should-adds [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:17]. | 0.75d |\n97: | P2 | Asset | `assets/audit_report_template.md` | Findings-first report skeleton with score, anti-pattern verdict, positive findings, priority issues, owner mapping, and evidence caveats. | `audit` five-dimension score and severity contract [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md:12]. | 0.5d |\n98: \n99: Do not add:\n100: \n101: - Fix implementation into audit. Current audit integration delegates direction to interface, color/type/layout to foundations, motion to motion, and implementation to sk-code [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:337].\n102: - Full two-sub-agent critique orchestration from `critique.md`; keep only evidence principles unless a later workflow packet owns orchestration.\n103: \n104: ### 3.6 `design-md-generator`\n105: \n106: | Priority | Type | Proposed file | What it adds | Sources | Effort |\n107: |---|---|---|---|---|---|\n108: | P1 | Reference | `references/authoring_boundary.md` | Distinguishes measured extraction, brief-authored Style Reference, and hybrid extension; defines source-of-truth labels and fidelity constraints. | Current cardinal fidelity rule [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:248]; `stitch-skill` forward authoring goal [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:17]. | 1.0d |\n109: | P1 | Asset | `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` | Quick card that asks: measured tokens, brief-provided values, inferred style direction, or missing backing data? Prevents fabricated values. | v3 format cardinal rules [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/design_md_format.md:27]. | 0.5d |\n110: | P1 | Asset | `assets/brief_to_style_reference_prompt.md` | Prompt skeleton for non-extraction authoring that requires explicit labels for measured, brief-provided, inferred, and absent sections. | `stitch-skill` output structure [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:115]; writing guide voice rules [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/writing_style_guide.md:29]. | 0.75d |\n111: | P2 | Reference subsection | Add component decision examples to `component_taxonomy.md` | Enriches component selection guide with examples for dialog/toast/banner, card/list/table, dropdown/radio/segmented control where needed. | Current component taxonomy already defines Use lines and decision logic [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/references/component_taxonomy.md:347]. | 0.25d |\n112: \n113: Do not add:\n114: \n115: - A second extraction backend or crawler path. Current pipeline already extracts, writes, validates, and reports [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:206].\n116: - A rename or new `design-spec` child in this phase. The phase scope excludes taxonomy changes [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md:53].\n117: \n118: ## 4. Implementation Sequence\n119: \n120: | Step | Scope | Why first |\n121: |---|---|---|\n122: | 1 | `shared/register.md` and `shared/assets/register_card.md` | Gates multiple mode decisions and prior gap analysis marks it must-add. |\n123: | 2 | `design-interface/assets/interface_preflight_card.md` plus `brief_to_dials.md` | Highest operator leverage; converts taste corpus into repeatable checks. |\n124: | 3 | `design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md` and `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Makes review/fix guidance evidence-backed before new content expands. |\n125: | 4 | `foundations` register/data-viz/adaptation references | Completes static visual-system gaps without duplicating basics. |\n126: | 5 | `motion` pattern/performance assets | Packages already-known rules into reusable cards. |\n127: | 6 | `md-generator` authoring boundary and prompt skeleton | Adds forward authoring while protecting cardinal fidelity. |\n128: \n129: ## 5. Do-Not-Add List\n130: \n131: - Do not reopen parent taxonomy or architecture.\n132: - Do not create net-new sub-skills.\n133: - Do not import the full `designer-skills-main` process lifecycle.\n134: - Do not import slides/canvas/poster workflows into the five current modes unless a later scope ruling approves presentation work.\n135: - Do not add generic anti-truncation output guidance; prior analysis classifies `output-skill` as out-of-family [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:36].\n136: - Do not add GSAP-heavy or motion-rich defaults to all interface/motion work.\n137: - Do not expand `md-generator` by inventing values or weakening `tokens.json` fidelity.\n138: - Do not add large references without an associated mode owner and a concrete operator action.\n139: \n140: ## 6. Residual Risks\n141: \n142: - Exact effort estimates are inferred from document size and current skill patterns; implementation should calibrate them against template and validation work.\n143: - Some external corpus advice is aggressive and landing-page-specific. Implementation must label those references as conditional rather than default.\n144: - `md-generator` forward authoring is the highest-risk addition because it can blur measured vs inferred truth. It needs explicit source labels and validation language before use.\n145: \n146: ## 7. References\n147: \n148: ### Prior research\n149: \n150: - `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/research.md`\n151: - `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md`\n152: - `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md`\n153: \n154: ### Live skill state\n155: \n156: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md`\n157: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md`\n158: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md`\n159: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.m