"returned_memory_ids\": [3467], \"run\": 2, \"scoringMethod\": \"fallback\", \"ts\": \"2026-05-21T06:45:41.311822Z\"}\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/benchmarks/benchmark-2026-05-21-cap-top-k/runs/arm-a-off.jsonl:\n  Line 88: {\"arm\": \"A\", \"category\": \"paraphrase\", \"difficulty\": \"medium\", \"fixture_id\": \"fixture-038\", \"gold_doc_ids\": [\"system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/016-embedder-testing-and-architecture/002-spec-memory-stack/015-cascade-reorder-and-nomic-hf-local-default/implementation-summary.md\"], \"gold_memory_ids\": [4544], \"hit_at_10\": false, \"latency_ms\": 574.864, \"memory_index_hash\": \"sha256:27063843a74a89517afb0b5aa1e5355ca4bf67053f7ea2d97656cb7a4964ba1b\", \"memory_index_size\": 8537, \"query\": \"implementation summary for local-first cascade reorder and Nomic hf-local default\", \"reciprocal_rank\": 0.0, \"rerank_gate\": {\"reason\": \"eligible:complex-query+high-authority\", \"shouldRerank\": true, \"triggers\": [\"complex-query\", \"high-authority\"]}, \"rerank_provider\": \"none\", \"rerank_used\": false, \"result_count\": 1, \"returned_doc_ids\": [\"memory_index:3467\", \"system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/016-embedder-testing-and-architecture/001-local-embeddings-foundation/020-catalog-playbook-alignment-audit/implementation-summary.md\"], \"returned_memory_ids\": [3467], \"run\": 2, \"scoringMethod\": \"fallback\", \"ts\": \"2026-05-21T06:22:36.078261Z\"}\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/references/skill_benchmark/operator_guide.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"How to run Lane C (skill-benchmark): invocation, the opt-in advisor probe, Mode A pipeline, dimension coverage, verdict bands, and target eligibility for benchmarking whether a skill is well-routed, discoverable, efficient, and useful in practice.\"\n\n  Line 22: Run Lane C with `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark` (or `/deep:skill-benchmark`). The orchestrator runs the D5 structural hard gate first, then per-scenario contamination-lint → router-replay → score, then writes a dual JSON+Markdown report. Mode A is deterministic and is the CI gate; the D1-inter advisor probe, the live trace (Mode B), and the D4-R task-outcome ablation are all opt-in (live/paid), kept off the CI path.\n\n  Line 24: > **Mode B (live playbook) — BUILT** (packet `122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/010-skill-benchmark-live-playbook-mode`). Beyond the synthetic-fixture Mode A above, Lane C can now use a skill's own `manual_testing_playbook` as the corpus and score it in two trace-modes over one parser:\n\n  Line 33: # Mode A (router-replay, deterministic — the CI gate). Run on a skill that has an\n\n  Line 42: `--advisor-mode=python` enables the **D1-inter** advisor probe — the deterministic in-repo SQLite advisor, scored out-of-band so the answer cannot leak. It is **off by default** (and in CI) to keep the pure-router path fast and dependency-free; enable it to lift a Mode A run from 4-dimension to 5-dimension coverage.\n\n  Line 67: | Dim | What | Mode A |\n\n  Line 83: D1-inter is **built and deterministic** but opt-in (`--advisor-mode=python`); the live in-situ trace (Mode B) is built. The weighted **D4** dimension stays `unscored-mode-a` on purpose — its grader scores *hallucination*, not task usefulness, so folding it would mislabel the number. Real usefulness is the opt-in **D4-R task-outcome ablation** (`--d4`), reported separately as advisory `D4_task_outcome`, never summed into the weighted score. Mode A stays honest about coverage: the aggregate normalizes over the dimensions actually measured.\n\n  Line 91: Mode A needs a parseable `INTENT_SIGNALS` + `RESOURCE_MAP` router (e.g. the `cli-*` skills). Skills without that pattern report `router_unparseable` and gate — that is a real signal that the skill is not smart-router-routable, not a harness bug. A skill that routes via a different mechanism is a candidate for live-mode (Mode B) measurement once built.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/references/skill_benchmark/scenario_authoring.md:\n  Line 43: `expected.intentKeys`/`expected.resources` may be left `[]` while a skill's router map is still being confirmed; Mode A treats empty gold as non-penalizing (scores structure/efficiency only). Populate from a router-extract pass to get real D1-intra/D2 signal.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/references/skill_benchmark/scoring_contract.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Authoritative D1-D5 computation for the Lane C Skill Benchmark Report: point weights, Mode A deterministic scoring, the opt-in advisor probe for D1-inter, deferred live-mode dimensions, and funnel/bottleneck ranking.\"\n\n  Line 22: Lane C scores a skill across five dimensions (D1-D5) and rolls them into a single verdict. D5 (structural connectivity) is a static hard gate that runs first. Mode A (router-replay) scores everything that needs no live model deterministically; D1-inter is built but opt-in via the in-repo advisor. The weighted **D4** dimension (a hallucination-grader proxy) stays unscored in the aggregate **by design** — it does not measure task usefulness. Real routine-task usefulness is measured separately by the opt-in **D4-R task-outcome ablation**, reported as an advisory signal (never folded into the weighted score); the live trace (Mode B) is built. The aggregate normalizes over the dimensions actually measured so the headline number stays honest about coverage.\n\n  Line 33: - **D2** (Mode A proxy) = recall of expected resources in the routed set. Live mode replaces this with Hit@1 / Hit@3 / Recall@5 / MRR over the observed file-load trace.\n\n  Line 34: - **D3** (Mode A proxy) = `1 - wastedRouted / totalRouted` (over-routing penalty). Live mode replaces with calls/tokens-to-first-expected.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 768: This category covers 6 scenario summaries while the linked feature files remain the canonical execution contract. These scenarios validate Lane C (Skill-Benchmark): the `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark` arm, the contamination gate, router-replay (Mode A), the D5 connectivity hard gate, scoring against the private gold, and the dual report plus remediation taxonomy. See `SKILL.md` \"Lane C: Skill-Benchmark\" and `references/skill_benchmark/operator_guide.md` for the source-of-truth contract.\n\n  Line 796: ### SB-045 | Router-Replay (Mode A, Deterministic)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/changelog/v1.10.0.0.md:\n  Line 1: deep-improvement is now a genuine **three-lane** skill: this release brings Lane C (skill-benchmark) to release status by completing the live half of it. Lane C already had a deterministic router-replay benchmark (Mode A, built under packet 122); v1.10.0.0 adds the prerequisite that made a real skill benchmarkable (router-benchmarkability) and the \"Mode B\" that benchmarks a skill against its OWN `manual_testing_playbook` executed live through `cli-opencode` — the way the skill is actually used, not a synthetic replay. It also relocates the script test suites to live lane-locally beside the code they cover.\n\n  Line 11: - **Machine-readable router for `sk-code`.** Lane C's Mode A needs an `INTENT_SIGNALS` + `RESOURCE_MAP` router to replay. `sk-code` keeps its router in a referenced doc (`references/smart_routing.md`), not inline in `SKILL.md`, so the benchmark couldn't read it. Added a machine-readable router block (DEFAULT_RESOURCE + 14 intents + a RESOURCE_MAP covering every routable content file) to `smart_routing.md`, with a drift-guard regression test that fails if any mapped path goes missing on disk or any routable doc stops being covered.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/manual_testing_playbook/10--skill-benchmark/scoring-vs-private-gold.md:\n  Line 17: This scenario validates that `scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs` scores a router-replay result against private gold and aggregates the D1–D5 dimensions. The orchestrator `run-skill-benchmark.cjs` loads public/private fixture pairs from `assets/skill_benchmark/fixtures/<skill-id>/` (`<id>.public.json` + `<id>.private.json`); the private gold (`expected.intentKeys`, `expected.resources`, `expected.skillId`, `expected.negativeActivation`) never crosses the dispatch boundary and is joined post-route. `scoreScenario()` computes Mode A dimensions deterministically: D1-intra (`0.4*intentRecall + 0.6*resourceRecall`), D2 (resource-recall discovery proxy), D3 (over-routing efficiency proxy), with D1-inter scored only when `--advisor-mode=python` supplies an advisor probe and D4 always `unscored-mode-a` (needs live ablation). `aggregate()` averages the scenario `modeAScore`s, attaches the D5 connectivity score (hard gate), and derives the verdict (`PASS` ≥80, `CONDITIONAL` 50–79, `FAIL` <50, `BLOCKED-BY-STRUCTURE` on a D5 gate). The bundled `deep-improvement` fixture `agent-improve-001` exercises the full lint → route → score path, so running the orchestrator against `deep-improvement` produces at least one scored scenario row with a populated `dims.d1intra`.\n\n  Line 74: | `../../scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs` | `scoreScenario()` + `aggregate()` — Mode A dimension scoring and roll-up |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/manual_testing_playbook/10--skill-benchmark/mode-wiring-routing.md:\n  Line 76: | `../../references/skill_benchmark/operator_guide.md` | Canonical invocation + Mode A pipeline reference |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/manual_testing_playbook/10--skill-benchmark/router-replay-mode-a.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"SB-045 -- Router-Replay Mode A Determinism\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Manual validation scenario for SB-045: Router-Replay Mode A Determinism.\"\n\n  Line 9: # SB-045 -- Router-Replay Mode A Determinism\n\n  Line 17: This scenario validates that `scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs` (Mode A, deterministic) produces stable, repeatable routing decisions for a fixed task — the property that makes it the CI gate. The script reads the target `SKILL.md`, extracts `INTENT_SIGNALS`, `RESOURCE_MAP`, and `DEFAULT_RESOURCE` from the fenced router block, then reproduces the in-skill semantics: lowercase the task, score each intent by counting which keywords appear as substrings (weighted), keep intents within `AMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1` of the top score, and union the default resource with `RESOURCE_MAP[intent]` for the selected intents. The standalone CLI is `router-replay.cjs --skill <skill-root> --task \"<task text>\"`: it prints `{ parseable, intents, resources, missingResources, scores }` and exits `0` on a successful replay (even with zero intents) / `2` on an unparseable router. Determinism is verified by running the identical task twice and diffing the JSON output.\n\n  Line 23: - Objective: Validate that router-replay (Mode A) is deterministic — the same task on the same skill yields byte-identical routing JSON across runs — and selects the expected intent with existing routed paths.\n\n  Line 24: - Real user request: `Confirm the Mode A router replay returns the same routing decision every time for a given task so it is safe as a CI gate.`\n\n  Line 46: | SB-045 | Router-Replay Mode A Determinism | Validate deterministic Mode A routing replay across two identical runs | `Validate that router-replay produces stable, repeatable routing decisions for a fixture task and is exit-0 deterministic.` | rm -rf /tmp/sb-045 &amp;&amp; mkdir -p /tmp/sb-045 &amp;&amp; \\<br>node .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs \\<br>  --skill .opencode/skills/cli-codex \\<br>  --task \"review this diff for security vulnerabilities and give a second opinion\" \\<br>  &gt; /tmp/sb-045/run1.json ; echo \"run1-exit=$?\" ; \\<br>node .opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs \\<br>  --skill .opencode/skills/cli-codex \\<br>  --task \"review this diff for security vulnerabilities and give a second opinion\" \\<br>  &gt; /tmp/sb-045/run2.json ; echo \"run2-exit=$?\" ; \\<br>diff /tmp/sb-045/run1.json /tmp/sb-045/run2.json &amp;&amp; echo \"DETERMINISTIC\" ; \\<br>node -e \"const r=require('/tmp/sb-045/run1.json');console.log('parseable='+r.parseable+' hasREVIEW='+r.intents.includes('REVIEW')+' resources='+r.resources.length+' missing='+r.missingResources.length);\" | both runs `run1-exit=0` / `run2-exit=0`; `diff` empty and prints `DETERMINISTIC`; JSON `\"parseable\": true`; `hasREVIEW=true`; `resources` &gt; 0; `missing=0` (`missingResources` empty) | `terminal transcript, command output, generated files, and PASS/FAIL verdict` | PASS when both runs exit 0, are `parseable:true`, the JSON is byte-identical across runs, and the expected REVIEW intent + non-empty existing resources are routed; FAIL otherwise. | If the two outputs differ: routing is not deterministic — inspect `scoreIntents()`/`selectIntents()` and the `scores.sort` order in `router-replay.cjs`<br>If `parseable:false` (exit 2): the target `SKILL.md` lacks a parseable `INTENT_SIGNALS`/`RESOURCE_MAP` block — check `extractDictBody()` and `parseRouter()`<br>If `missingResources` is non-empty: a rout...\n  Line 74: | `../../scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs` | Mode A deterministic in-skill smart-router replay |\n\n  Line 76: | `../../references/skill_benchmark/operator_guide.md` | Documents Mode A as the deterministic CI gate |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/after/skill-benchmark-report.json:\n  Line 89:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with observed-load Hit@k/Recall@k/MRR\"\n\n  Line 96:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with calls/tokens-to-first-expected\"\n\n  Line 124:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with observed-load Hit@k/Recall@k/MRR\"\n\n  Line 131:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with calls/tokens-to-first-expected\"\n\n  Line 150:     \"note\": \"Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode.\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/router-final/skill-benchmark-report.json:\n  Line 207:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with observed-load Hit@k/Recall@k/MRR\"\n\n  Line 214:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with calls/tokens-to-first-expected\"\n\n  Line 252:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with observed-load Hit@k/Recall@k/MRR\"\n\n  Line 259:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with calls/tokens-to-first-expected\"\n\n  Line 297:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with observed-load Hit@k/Recall@k/MRR\"\n\n  Line 342:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with observed-load Hit@k/Recall@k/MRR\"\n\n  Line 349:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with calls/tokens-to-first-expected\"\n\n  Line 387:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with observed-load Hit@k/Recall@k/MRR\"\n\n  Line 394:           \"note\": \"Mode A proxy; live-mode replaces with cal